window.HB_DATA = window.HB_DATA || {}; window.HB_DATA.en = {"modules":{"esencia":{"title":"The Essence of DeMolay","subtitle":"What DeMolay is, what it believes, what it offers you, and how to explain it to anyone.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"What DeMolay Is","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay is the **premier leadership training organization** for young men between the ages of **12 and 21**. And it can claim something no one else can: it is the **only youth organization in the world run by its youth members**, with adults serving as advisors rather than bosses."},{"t":"p","text":"It was founded in **1919 in Kansas City, Missouri**, by an original group of **nine young men**. That group has grown to **more than a thousand Chapters**. Wherever you travel, you will never be far from a DeMolay Chapter."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"You are a DeMolay **for life**. From the time you join until you turn 21, you are an **Active DeMolay**. At age 21 you become a **Senior DeMolay**, and you can stay connected by joining the **Alumni Association** or by becoming an **Advisor**."},{"t":"h","text":"What DeMolay Believes"},{"t":"list","items":["Every individual is unique and vital.","Young men will think and act thoughtfully and responsibly if given a chance.","Young men must be involved in the decisions that affect them.","Young men need to share experiences, but in a structure where they can learn responsibility and develop their own style at their own pace.","Young men need to have fun and socialize with others."]},{"t":"p","text":"The heart of DeMolay is the combination of **independence** and **fraternalism**: original thinking, creative planning, responsible decision-making, and cooperative action. DeMolay gives you an atmosphere with a **real chance to succeed and the freedom to learn**."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Why DeMolay Exists: The Purposes","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay's primary purpose is to **build better citizens and create leaders** through the development of **character**. Everything else — meetings, events, ritual, projects — points back to that."},{"t":"p","text":"Important: DeMolay does **not try to replace** your home, your place of worship, or your school. It **supplements** them with a program that teaches good citizenship in practice."},{"t":"h","text":"What DeMolay Offers You"},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"A wholesome occupation for your spare time","text":"Activities worth your hours instead of wasted ones: community service projects, athletics, and social events."},{"title":"Worthwhile friends","text":"Friendships that last a lifetime, with young men who share your values."},{"title":"Adult mentoring","text":"Responsible adults from your community who advise and support you without running your life."},{"title":"A complete program of all-around youth development","text":"Leadership, public speaking, responsibility, and self-reliance — all in one place, and fun while you are at it."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"You only get out of DeMolay what you put into it. Enter wholeheartedly into your Chapter's activities and the returns are both material and spiritual: lasting friendships, responsibility, and self-reliance."},{"t":"p","text":"The DeMolay ritual is also an excellent **school for public speaking**, and the community and charitable projects give you something no app can: the real satisfaction of helping make the world a better place."},{"t":"ref","text":"Read the full Purposes of DeMolay in the Handbook","page":"1"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"The Seven Cardinal Virtues","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A Chapter's entire program revolves around seven core values: the **seven cardinal virtues**. They are not ceremony filler — they are the standard a DeMolay measures himself against every single day."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Love of Parents","text":"Loving and honoring your parents — and proving it in how you treat them every day."},{"title":"Reverence","text":"Respect for sacred things: for God and for your own beliefs and those of others."},{"title":"Courtesy","text":"Treating every person with respect and good manners, always."},{"title":"Comradeship","text":"Loyal, genuine friendship with your brothers and the people around you."},{"title":"Fidelity","text":"Staying true to your word, your ideals, and your friends."},{"title":"Cleanness","text":"Clean in mind and body — in what you think, say, and do."},{"title":"Patriotism","text":"Love of and service to your country, in peace as well as in war."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Handbook fact: bringing in new members to share DeMolay is one of the best ways to practice **three** of the cardinal virtues at once — comradeship, patriotism, and fidelity."},{"t":"p","text":"The virtues are not goals for one evening every two weeks. They are goals to strive for **every day, in your daily tasks**."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"A DeMolay's Ethics: Your Code of Conduct","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Beyond the virtues, DeMolay hands you a concrete code of conduct: **A DeMolay's Ethics** — a list of **14 principles** describing how a DeMolay carries himself in any situation."},{"t":"list","items":["A DeMolay serves God.","A DeMolay honors all womanhood.","A DeMolay loves and honors his parents.","A DeMolay is honest.","A DeMolay is loyal to ideals and friends.","A DeMolay practices honest toil.","A DeMolay's word is as good as his bond.","A DeMolay is courteous.","A DeMolay is at all times a gentleman.","A DeMolay is a patriot in peace as well as war.","A DeMolay is clean in mind and body.","A DeMolay stands unswervingly for the public schools.","A DeMolay always bears the reputation of a good and law-abiding citizen.","A DeMolay, by precept and example, must preserve the high standards to which he has pledged himself."]},{"t":"p","text":"Notice how the 14 principles are the seven virtues in action: honesty, loyalty, courtesy, cleanness, patriotism... The code does not ask you to be perfect. It asks you to be **consistent** — with your word and with your example."},{"t":"ref","text":"The official text of A DeMolay's Ethics is in the Handbook","page":"233"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Your First Duties as a New Member","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Just joined? Your first duty is a single, simple one: **get involved**. You will get out of DeMolay exactly what you put into it, so jump in with both feet from day one."},{"t":"steps","items":["Stand up in your Chapter and volunteer to be on a committee.","Ask to take charge of a special project: coordinating a dance, a car wash, or a movie night.","Suggest activities you enjoy for the Chapter to try as a whole: hiking, Go-Kart riding, or forming a gaming group.","Not sure where to start? Just ask. Your Chapter will help you get started on the right foot."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Your second duty comes with a number and a deadline: share DeMolay with **2 other deserving young men** (your friends, perhaps!) within your **first year** of membership."},{"t":"p","text":"The opportunities in DeMolay are endless — you can accomplish most anything you like. But none of it happens from the sidelines. **Your first duty is to get involved.**"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Talking Points: Explain DeMolay in One Minute","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Sooner or later a friend will ask you what DeMolay is. The Handbook gives you a set of **talking points** for exactly that moment. The key: whenever possible, share real examples of how DeMolay has helped actual members — starting with you."},{"t":"table","headers":["Point","What to Say"],"rows":[["International","DeMolay has Chapters in over 26 countries and territories."],["The largest","Over 3 million young men have joined throughout history. A DeMolay is never without friends, wherever he goes."],["Select","Members are carefully selected; being known as a DeMolay is a recommendation socially and in business anywhere."],["Advisors","Responsible adults from the community — the DeMolay Dads and Moms — help with personal issues, school, finding a job, and more."],["Ceremonies","Both Degrees are beautiful and inspiring, and unlike anything else open to young men between 12 and 21."],["Character","DeMolay helps young men become better sons and better citizens: it teaches the virtues, plus toleration."],["Leadership","You learn to stand on your feet and express yourself; you can become a Chapter officer and show what you can do."],["Self-government","Chapters are governed by their own officers and members, with advice and counsel from the Chapter Advisors."],["Activities","From civic to social to athletic — hands-on experiences your school often cannot offer."],["Scholarships","Various scholarship programs are available to members."]]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"The Handbook's approach is a positive one: we sell DeMolay **by example**. Show your friend what DeMolay has done for you, and it becomes easy to convince him it can do the same for him."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full list of talking points is in the Handbook","page":"15"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"Where and when was DeMolay founded?","options":["In 1919 in Kansas City, Missouri","In 1919 in St. Louis, Missouri","In 1929 in Kansas City, Missouri","In 1909 in Chicago, Illinois"],"correct":0,"explain":"DeMolay was founded in 1919 in Kansas City, Missouri, by an original group of nine young men."},{"q":"What happens when an Active DeMolay turns 21?","options":["His DeMolay membership ends","He becomes a Senior DeMolay","He must take both Degrees again","He automatically becomes an Advisor"],"correct":1,"explain":"You are a DeMolay for life: at 21 you go from Active DeMolay to Senior DeMolay, and you can stay involved through the Alumni Association or as an Advisor."},{"q":"Which of these is NOT one of the seven cardinal virtues?","options":["Cleanness","Fidelity","Honesty","Courtesy"],"correct":2,"explain":"The seven virtues are love of parents, reverence, courtesy, comradeship, fidelity, cleanness, and patriotism. Honesty appears in A DeMolay's Ethics, but it is not one of the seven virtues."},{"q":"According to the Handbook, which of these is NOT one of the four things DeMolay offers a young man?","options":["A wholesome occupation for his spare time","Worthwhile friends","Adult mentoring","A guaranteed job after aging out"],"correct":3,"explain":"DeMolay offers four things: a wholesome occupation for spare time, worthwhile friends, adult mentoring, and a complete program of all-around youth development."},{"q":"How many principles make up A DeMolay's Ethics?","options":["7","10","12","14"],"correct":3,"explain":"A DeMolay's Ethics is the 14-principle code of conduct, running from serving God to preserving by example the high standards you pledged yourself to."},{"q":"As a new member, how many young men should you share DeMolay with, and by when?","options":["2 young men within your first year","5 young men within your first year","2 young men before your first Degree","1 young man for every year of membership"],"correct":0,"explain":"Part of your first duties is to share DeMolay with 2 other deserving young men within your first year of membership."},{"q":"According to the talking points, DeMolay has Chapters in how many countries and territories?","options":["Over 12","Over 26","Over 50","Over 100"],"correct":1,"explain":"DeMolay is an international organization with Chapters in over 26 countries and territories."},{"q":"According to the talking points, how many young men have joined DeMolay throughout its history?","options":["Over 500,000","Over 1 million","Over 3 million","Over 10 million"],"correct":2,"explain":"The talking points highlight that over 3 million young men have joined — the largest membership of any similar organization on earth."}]},"historia":{"title":"History & Legacy","subtitle":"From nine boys in Kansas City to a worldwide movement — and the 14th-century martyr who gave it a name.","minutes":10,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"March 1919: nine boys and an idea","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay was born in **March 1919** at the Scottish Rite Temple in **Kansas City, Missouri**. Frank S. Land, the Scottish Rite's social service director, had given a job to a fatherless boy named **Louis Gordon Lower**. Talking with him, Land realized many boys like Louis were looking for companionship, leadership, inspiration and healthy competition — things they couldn't always find at home, school or church."},{"t":"p","text":"Land asked Louis to bring some friends to a get-together at the Temple. Eight came along. Those nine became DeMolay's **original founders**:"},{"t":"list","items":["Louis G. Lower (the first DeMolay)","Ivan M. Bentley","Edmund Marshall","Gorman A. McBride","Jerome Jacobson","William Steinhilber","Elmer Dorsey","Clyde C. Stream","Ralph Sewell"]},{"t":"p","text":"By the second meeting there were **31**. When one of the boys asked for names connected with Masonry, Land told the story of **Jacques DeMolay**, the last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, a martyr to loyalty. The boys loved what the name stood for: **death rather than betrayal of one's friends**."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The first obligation was taken on Frank S. Land's own Bible — the one he had earned with 10 years of perfect Sunday School attendance."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Dad Land, the Founder","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"**Frank Sherman Land** (June 21, 1890 – November 8, 1959) was the soul of DeMolay for four decades, serving as **Secretary-General from 1919 until his death**. Members called him — and have called every male advisor since — **\"Dad\"**."},{"t":"list","items":["As a kid he was nicknamed the **\"Boy Preacher of St. Louis\"**: at age 10 he preached to crowds of up to 300 boys.","He joined Masonry at **Ivanhoe Lodge** (Kansas City) on June 29, 1912.","From 1922 on, he worked **full-time** for DeMolay as Grand Scribe.","He received the **Scottish Rite 33° in 1925**, at just 35.","He served as **Imperial Potentate of the Shrine of North America** (1954-1955).","At his death he was president of the Kansas City School Board and a trustee of the Harry S. Truman Presidential Library."]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Land's own definition of DeMolay: a youth organization for young men whose purpose is **\"the building of better citizens.\"**"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Lightning-fast growth","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Growth was explosive. When someone proposed capping the Mother Chapter at 75 members, Land rejected it with a phrase that set the course: to become big, they had to be big. The Mother Chapter reached **2,000 members within a year**."},{"t":"steps","items":["**September 16, 1919**: first full officer line (Averill C. Tatlock, first Master Councilor).","**September 27, 1919**: first complete degree work.","**November 1919**: the group adopts the name **Order of DeMolay**; Louis Lower is elected Master Councilor in December.","**May 8, 1920**: the world's second Chapter is born in **Omaha, Nebraska** (driven by Zoro D. Clark).","**November 20, 1920**: the temporary Grand Council forms at the Baltimore Hotel in Kansas City, with 13 members.","**March 7, 1921**: first annual session of the Grand Council at the Scottish Rite Temple. **52 Chapters** were already requesting charters, with 3,336 active members.","**March 1922**: Chapters exist in 39 of the 48 states, plus Manitoba, Puerto Rico and the Philippines."]},{"t":"p","text":"The first three charters: **No. 1** Kansas City Chapter (the **Mother Chapter**), **No. 2** Huron Chapter (Kansas City, Kansas) and **No. 3** Pittsburg Chapter (Pittsburg, Kansas)."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The largest initiation class in history: **1,099 initiates** in a single day — Templar Chapter, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, February 12, 1923."},{"t":"p","text":"The Grand Council became the **International Supreme Council** on March 1, 1954. Its Honorary Grand Masters include presidents **Franklin D. Roosevelt** (1933) and **Harry S. Truman** (1945), and Canadian Prime Minister **John G. Diefenbaker** (1958)."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full story of the founding and early years","page":"237"}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Frank A. Marshall and the Ritual","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The DeMolay Ritual — its two degrees, the **Initiatory Degree** and the **DeMolay Degree** — was written in 1919 by **Frank A. Marshall**, a Kansas City newspaperman and Masonic leader. It has remained **virtually unchanged** ever since: one of the keys to the Order's success, according to Land himself."},{"t":"list","items":["Born November 13, 1865, in Leavenworth, Kansas.","Worked **37 years** at the Kansas City Journal (1891-1928), over 20 of them as an editorial writer.","Served on the Grand Council from March 1921 until his death on March 24, 1931.","At the Grand Council's first session he was appointed **Grand Senior Steward**; Louis Lower, the first DeMolay, became **Grand Sentinel**."]}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Jacques DeMolay, our namesake","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"**Jacques DeMolay** was born in Vitrey, Haute-Saône, France, in **1244**. At 21 (1265) he joined the **Knights Templar**, the military-religious order sanctioned by the Pope in 1128 and originally known as the \"Poor Soldiers in Christ.\" In **1298** he was elected its **Grand Master**."},{"t":"p","text":"King **Philip the Fair** of France tried to control the Templars and, failing that, set out to destroy them. On **Friday, October 13, 1307**, he had every Templar in France arrested in a secret raid. **Seven years of prison and torture** followed, with a Pope forced to condemn the Order."},{"t":"p","text":"On **March 18, 1314**, a papal commission sentenced DeMolay to life in prison based on a forged confession. DeMolay and **Geoffrey de Charney** publicly retracted every confession — and that same night they were **burned at the stake** on an island in the River Seine, while the bells of Notre Dame tolled."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"His last words, as tradition records them: **\"We die innocent. The decree which condemns us is an unjust decree.\"** He died rather than betray his companions. That is why **March 18** is the most important date on the DeMolay calendar."},{"t":"p","text":"His legacy for every DeMolay: **truth, tolerance, courage and fidelity**. Today a commemorative plaque marks the site of his death in Paris."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full biography of Jacques DeMolay","page":"244"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"A legacy that lives on","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"More than a century later, millions of young men have passed through DeMolay Chapter rooms. Famous **Senior DeMolays** include **Walt Disney**, **John Wayne**, **Walter Cronkite**, Fred MacMurray, Bob Mathias, Robert Cummings and Chet Huntley."},{"t":"p","text":"The legacy is personal, too: every DeMolay who recites an Obligation, runs a service project or lends a brother a hand is carrying on what nine boys started in Kansas City in 1919."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"1919","text":"Founded at the Scottish Rite Temple, Kansas City."},{"title":"March 18, 1314","text":"Martyrdom of Jacques DeMolay in Paris."},{"title":"March 7, 1921","text":"First session of the Grand Council."},{"title":"November 8, 1959","text":"Death of Frank S. Land. Honored today as Frank S. Land Memorial Day."}]}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"Where and when was DeMolay founded?","options":["Kansas City, Missouri, in March 1919","St. Louis, Missouri, in 1921","Kansas City, Kansas, in 1920","Baltimore, Maryland, in 1919"],"correct":0,"explain":"Frank S. Land gathered the nine founders at the Scottish Rite Temple in Kansas City, Missouri, in March 1919."},{"q":"Who was the first DeMolay?","options":["Gorman A. McBride","Averill C. Tatlock","Louis Gordon Lower","Frank A. Marshall"],"correct":2,"explain":"Louis Gordon Lower was the boy Land hired and who brought his eight friends; he was the first to take the obligation."},{"q":"Who wrote the DeMolay Ritual?","options":["Frank A. Marshall, in 1919","Frank S. Land, in 1920","Alexander G. Cochran, in 1921","Louis Lower, in 1919"],"correct":0,"explain":"Marshall, a Kansas City Journal newspaperman, wrote both degrees in 1919, and the Ritual remains virtually unchanged."},{"q":"What happened on Friday, October 13, 1307?","options":["Jacques DeMolay was burned at the stake","Every Templar in France was arrested","Jacques DeMolay was elected Grand Master","The Templar order was founded"],"correct":1,"explain":"Philip the Fair ordered the secret, simultaneous capture of all Templars in France on that Friday the 13th."},{"q":"Why is March 18 the central date of the DeMolay calendar?","options":["It is the day Jacques DeMolay was martyred (1314)","It is Frank S. Land's birthday","It is the day the Order was founded","It is the day of the first charter"],"correct":0,"explain":"On March 18, 1314, Jacques DeMolay was burned at the stake after retracting the forced confessions. That is why Devotional Day falls in that week."},{"q":"Where was the world's second Chapter born?","options":["Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania (1923)","Huron, Kansas (1921)","St. Louis, Missouri (1920)","Omaha, Nebraska (May 8, 1920)"],"correct":3,"explain":"The second Chapter was instituted in Omaha, Nebraska, on May 8, 1920, driven by Zoro D. Clark."},{"q":"What was the largest initiation class in history?","options":["1,099 initiates, Templar Chapter, Pittsburgh, 1923","500 initiates, Mother Chapter, 1920","2,000 initiates, Kansas City, 1921","750 initiates, Omaha, 1922"],"correct":0,"explain":"On February 12, 1923, Templar Chapter of Pittsburgh initiated 1,099 young men in a single day."},{"q":"Until when did Frank S. Land serve as DeMolay's Secretary-General?","options":["Until retiring in 1954","Until his death on November 8, 1959","Until 1931","Until becoming Imperial Potentate"],"correct":1,"explain":"Land led DeMolay from 1919 until his death on November 8, 1959 — a date honored today as Frank S. Land Memorial Day."}]},"membresia":{"title":"Membership: From Applicant to Brother","subtitle":"Who can join, how the path into the Chapter works, and what it means to be a DeMolay for life.","minutes":8,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Who Can Become a DeMolay?","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every Chapter needs new members every single year: most join around age 14, finish high school near 18, and practically the entire Chapter turns over in about **3 years**. That's why knowing who's eligible — and inviting him — is everyone's job, not just a committee's."},{"t":"h","text":"The Eligibility Requirements"},{"t":"list","items":["A young man who has **passed his 12th birthday** and has **not yet reached his 21st**.","Of **good moral character**.","**Recommended** by an active DeMolay, a Senior DeMolay, or a Master Mason."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Membership is **NOT limited to the sons or relatives of Masons**. Any eligible young man in your community can join. Let no one answer \"no one asked me\" when asked why he isn't a DeMolay."},{"t":"h","text":"The Application"},{"t":"p","text":"Joining starts with the standard **Membership Application**, available online. It covers a brief background of the young man and the **consent of his parent(s) or guardian(s)**. The applicant must also name at least one member of the Chapter, a Senior DeMolay, or a Master Mason as a recommendation."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"The Path In, Step by Step","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Between the application and your degrees there's an orderly process. It isn't red tape — it's how the Chapter gets to know its future brother, and how his family gets to know DeMolay."},{"t":"steps","items":["**Application:** the applicant submits his Membership Application with his parents' or guardians' consent.","**Investigating committee:** the Master Councilor appoints a committee of **2 to 3 members plus an Advisor** to conduct a **home visit** with the applicant.","**Report to the Chapter:** the committee delivers its full report. Without it, the application **cannot be balloted upon**.","**Ballot:** the Chapter votes on the application. A favorable vote means the candidate is elected.","**Degrees:** the new member receives the **Initiatory Degree** and then the **DeMolay Degree**."]},{"t":"p","text":"What does the home visit look at? Four areas: his **home life**, his **social life** and the reputation of his associates, his **school record** (if in school), and his **employment record** (if employed). The watchword is diplomacy: a friendly conversation that weaves the questions in naturally — not an interrogation."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"The visit works both ways: the committee answers any questions the applicant or his parents have about DeMolay. The committee must report in some way by the next Chapter meeting."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full committee form and home-visit questions are in the Handbook","page":"17"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Fees, Deadlines, and Paperwork","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The minimums are set by DeMolay International, and your Chapter may set higher amounts through an amendment to its Bylaws to cover other items provided to each new member."},{"t":"table","headers":["Item","Minimum","What it covers"],"rows":[["Initiation fee (degrees)","$35.00","**Lifetime membership**: degree fees, patent (membership certificate), and related charges"],["Affiliation fee","$20.00","Affiliating with a Chapter when you're already a member"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Within **10 days** of conferring the Initiatory Degree, the Scribe must remit to DeMolay International the established sum for each newly initiated member. All reporting and payment is processed electronically through **eScribe**."},{"t":"p","text":"**Patents** are issued by the Service & Leadership Center once your name is reported to the Grand Secretary's office via eScribe for both degrees. It's your official certificate of membership."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Orientation: Your Big Brother and the 3 Sessions","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Securing the application is the Membership Committee's job; **making the new brother feel at home** belongs to the Orientation Committee and every active member. A Chapter without an orientation program leaves its back door open as wide as its front door."},{"t":"p","text":"The committee setup is simple: **one experienced Chapter member per candidate plus an Advisor**. That member is called a **Big Brother** (or orientation coach) and is assigned by the Master Councilor. The **Junior Councilor** is usually the Chairman and conducts the sessions. Your Big Brother is responsible for you from the moment your application arrives until you recite your DeMolay Degree Obligation in open Chapter."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Session 1 — Before the Initiatory Degree","text":"About one hour before the ceremony. The Junior Councilor explains the history of DeMolay and the Chapter, the Officers and Advisory Council, the committees, conduct and dress code, the basic rules and youth protection, and what to expect in the degree. Parents are encouraged to attend."},{"title":"Session 2 — Between the Degrees","text":"Held while the Chapter has its business meeting. Half coaching on the Initiatory Obligation, half orientation: how DeMolay operates at every level, Chapter customs, and what to expect during the DeMolay Degree."},{"title":"Session 3 — After the DeMolay Degree","text":"Obligation coaching plus the ritual work, Jurisdictional events and conclaves, your pledge to bring in new members, and practicing the Obligations to present at the next Chapter meeting."}]},{"t":"p","text":"Your Big Brother makes sure you show up for your degrees, attend meetings and activities, get to know every member and Advisor, **memorize both of your Obligations**, and develop a real, permanent interest in the Chapter."},{"t":"ref","text":"The complete orientation program, session by session","page":"19"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Obligations, Proficiency, and the Obligation Card","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every member commits to **memorizing the obligations of the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees** plus the examination queries. The examination is passed in **open Chapter**, unless the Executive Officer approves an alternate procedure."},{"t":"list","items":["**Who coaches you:** the Junior Councilor (or your Big Brother) and those working under him teach the obligations.","**Who examines you:** the **Senior Deacon** conducts the examination in open Chapter.","**Who decides:** your proficiency is decided by a **vote of the Chapter**."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Without an **obligation card** you cannot **vote** in the election of Officers or on membership applications, and you **cannot hold office**. It's the document that certifies your proficiency."},{"t":"p","text":"The card is signed by the **Chapter Advisor**, bears the **seal of the Chapter**, and is recorded on **eScribe** in your permanent record. Only **one card per member** is issued — a duplicate only if the original is lost, at the Chapter Advisor's discretion."}]},{"id":"l6","title":"From Active to Senior DeMolay… and Forever","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Active membership lasts a maximum of **9 years**: from the day you join until your 21st birthday. In practice, the average member who joins at 14 gets **3 to 4 truly active years** before school, college, or work pulls him away. When you turn 21, you become a **Senior DeMolay**."},{"t":"h","text":"Your Part in the Growth"},{"t":"p","text":"Beyond living the DeMolay teachings, every member takes on the pledge to bring in a **minimum of 2 new members within a year**: one to replace his own eventual departure (whenever it happens) and one to make the Chapter grow. It matters: a typical Chapter only has **40-60%** of its roster available for active participation, and the **Membership Committee** is a standing committee required by the Rules & Regulations."},{"t":"h","text":"Life Membership"},{"t":"p","text":"\"**Once a DeMolay, always a DeMolay**\" stopped being just a motto thanks to the Life Membership Plan: your initiation fee makes you a **member for life**. Each Chapter sets its Life Membership fee for new initiates, with two conditions: the **Executive Officer must approve the fee and the plan**, and the portion of the fee allocated to your future years must be safeguarded in a **savings or trust account**. Some Jurisdictions add fees for new members."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Questions about Life Membership go to the Executive Officer of your Jurisdiction or the Service & Leadership Center."},{"t":"ref","text":"The Life Membership Plan in detail","page":"53"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"How old must a young man be to be eligible for DeMolay membership?","options":["Past his 12th birthday and not yet 21","Between 13 and 21 years old","Past his 12th birthday and not yet 18","Between 14 and 21 years old"],"correct":0,"explain":"Eligibility runs from past the 12th birthday until before reaching the 21st, with good moral character and a recommendation."},{"q":"Do you need to be the son or relative of a Mason to join DeMolay?","options":["Yes, you must be the son of a Master Mason","Yes, at least one Masonic relative is required","No, membership is not limited to sons or relatives of Masons","Only if the Chapter has no open spots"],"correct":2,"explain":"The Handbook states it explicitly: membership is NOT limited to the sons or relatives of Masons. All you need is a recommendation from an active DeMolay, Senior DeMolay, or Master Mason."},{"q":"What must happen before an application can be balloted upon?","options":["The applicant pays the initiation fee","The investigating committee delivers its full report after the home visit","The applicant memorizes the Initiatory Obligation","The Executive Officer approves the application"],"correct":1,"explain":"The committee of 2 to 3 members plus an Advisor conducts the home visit, and the application cannot be balloted upon until a full report is made."},{"q":"What is the minimum initiation fee, and what does it get you?","options":["$20.00 and membership until age 21","$35.00 and lifetime membership","$35.00 and a renewable annual membership","$50.00 and lifetime membership"],"correct":1,"explain":"The fee for the degrees shall not be less than $35.00 and includes lifetime membership. The $20.00 figure is the minimum affiliation fee — a different thing."},{"q":"What does the new member orientation program look like?","options":["A single session after the DeMolay Degree","3 sessions, usually conducted by the Junior Councilor, with one Big Brother per candidate","5 sessions run by the Master Councilor","2 sessions led by the Advisory Council"],"correct":1,"explain":"There are 3 sessions: before the Initiatory Degree, between the two degrees, and after the DeMolay Degree. The Junior Councilor usually chairs, and each candidate gets a Big Brother."},{"q":"How long does the Scribe have to remit the fee for each new initiate to DeMolay International?","options":["10 days from the Initiatory Degree, via eScribe","30 days from the ballot, by mail","10 days from the DeMolay Degree, via eScribe","Until the end of the DeMolay fiscal year"],"correct":0,"explain":"The deadline is 10 days after conferring the Initiatory Degree, and all reporting and payment is processed electronically through eScribe."},{"q":"What happens if a member doesn't have his obligation card?","options":["He just can't attend conclaves","He can't vote in Officer elections or on applications, and can't hold office","He pays an extra $20.00 fee","He can't attend Chapter meetings"],"correct":1,"explain":"The obligation card certifies your proficiency: without it you can't vote in the election of Officers or on membership applications, and you can't hold office."},{"q":"What happens when an active member turns 21?","options":["He renews his membership by paying the affiliation fee","He automatically joins the Advisory Council","He becomes a Senior DeMolay","He loses all connection with the organization"],"correct":2,"explain":"Active membership ends at the 21st birthday (9 years maximum of active membership), and the member becomes a Senior DeMolay. Thanks to the Life Membership Plan, he remains a DeMolay forever."}]},"capitulo":{"title":"Inside the Chapter","subtitle":"How your Chapter is organized, meets, votes, and governs itself — rule by rule.","minutes":12,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Structure and committees: the Chapter's engine","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Your Chapter does not float in mid-air: it sits inside a structure that starts at DeMolay International and runs down through the **Executive Officer** of your jurisdiction, the **Sponsoring Body** (the Masonic organization that sponsors the Chapter), and the **Advisory Council**. Only then comes the Chapter itself, with the **Master Councilor (MC)** presiding, the **Senior Councilor (SC)**, the **Junior Councilor (JC)**, the Scribe, the Treasurer, and the rest of the officers."},{"t":"p","text":"The real work gets done in committees. The **MC appoints all committees and is a member of every one of them**. Each committee has a minimum of **three members**, and the first person named is the chairman. The MC works out committee assignments with his officers and Advisors right after being elected and announces them at his first regular meeting. It is recommended that the SC and JC each supervise one half of the committees, and that an Advisor be assigned to each committee when available."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Out of the 14 suggested committees, the only one required by the DeMolay Rules & Regulations is the **Membership Committee**. The rest depend on how many members your Chapter has."},{"t":"table","headers":["Committee","What it does"],"rows":[["Membership (required)","Organizes membership drives, contacts candidates about the degrees, and handles orientation of new members."],["Entertainment","Arranges entertainment for meetings, dinners, socials, and public ceremonies."],["Publicity and Chapter Communications","Handles all publicity, publishes the Chapter news publication, and maintains the website and social media."],["Obligatory Observances","Plans programs so the Chapter observes all Obligatory Days."],["Masonic Relations","Finds ways to serve the Sponsoring Body and invites Masons to Chapter meetings and functions."],["Athletics","Organizes teams, leagues, and tournaments, and makes sure every member plays some sport."],["Chapter Relations","Arranges visits to other Chapters and handles public relations not covered by publicity."],["Civic Service","Plans all civic projects undertaken by the Chapter."],["Fundraising","Plans and coordinates all money-raising projects."],["Education and Career Guidance","Brings in career-guidance speakers, arranges vocational trips, and administers Chapter scholarships."],["Awards","Promotes Merit Bars, Blue Honor Keys, RD, and more, and arranges their presentation at public ceremonies."],["Sick","Visits or calls sick members and reports at every Chapter meeting."],["Auditing","Three members plus one Advisor; examines the books of the Scribe and Treasurer and reports at the first meeting after a new MC takes office."],["Finance","Minimum of three members; supervises the Chapter's finances."]]},{"t":"p","text":"Every committee should meet **at least once between Chapter meetings**, keep its reports brief and to the point, and rotate who delivers them so it is not always the chairman talking. Well-run committees are the secret to short business meetings: if the committee has already weighed the pros and cons, the Chapter can decide fast."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full rundown of the 14 committees is in the Handbook","page":"23"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Meeting protocol: entering, moving, behaving","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Chapter meetings should be the best-run activity in DeMolay, because the same procedure repeats every time. The Chapter room gets set up before the scheduled start: ideally a property committee handles it, and many Chapters assign the job to their **7 Preceptors**, so at least three are usually on hand. Officers arrive early so the meeting opens on time."},{"t":"h","text":"How you enter the Chapter"},{"t":"steps","items":["Present your membership card to the **Sentinel**, who is stationed just outside the Chapter room door.","The Sentinel gives you the **Word of the Day** — a word chosen by the Chapter Advisor and passed to the Sentinel before the meeting starts.","Inside, when the Word of the Day is collected, members rise one at a time and whisper it to the **Deacons**."]},{"t":"p","text":"To visit a Chapter other than your own, you apply to the Sentinel and request an examining committee: **three members** of that Chapter examine you, and if their report is favorable, the word is communicated to you. Inside the room, members rise when the officers enter and keep silent unless they wish to speak — in that case, rise, wait for the MC to recognize you, and the floor is yours."},{"t":"h","text":"Gavel raps and moving around the room"},{"t":"table","headers":["Raps","Meaning"],"rows":[["1 rap","Seats the Chapter."],["2 raps","Calls up the Officers."],["3 raps","Calls up the whole Chapter."]]},{"t":"p","text":"When the MC addresses you, **do not salute — just rise**. The Sentinel admits no one while the Chapter is being opened on either Degree. If you arrive late and get permission to enter, go to the altar and give the step, sign, and token if the Chapter is working in the **Initiatory Degree**, or the sign only if on the **DeMolay Degree**; the MC returns it. Leaving mid-session works the same way: rise, get recognized, ask permission, approach the altar, give the step and sign (or sign only), turn, and retire. During prayers, members kneel in unison with the Chaplain on the left knee facing the altar (Advisors, Masons, guests, and majority DeMolays stand), and everyone responds Amen at the close."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"While the Chapter is in session, **no one passes between the altar and the East** except when the Ritual requires it."},{"t":"p","text":"To transact business, the Chapter **must open on both Degrees**: Initiatory and DeMolay. If only the Initiatory Degree is being conferred and there is no business, opening on the DeMolay Degree is not necessary. Once opened on both, the Chapter passes from one Degree to the other with a simple declaration. If an officer is missing: the SC or JC acts as MC according to rank, the JC fills in for the SC, and for any other station the MC appoints a member for that meeting."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"The Order of Business and the minutes","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every Chapter meeting follows the same **17-point Order of Business**. Knowing it means you always know where you are in the meeting and what comes next:"},{"t":"steps","items":["Opening","Calling Roll of Officers","Reading Minutes of Previous Meeting","Almoner's Report","Treasurer's Report","Sickness and Distress","Reading of Communications","Reports of Committee on Applications for Membership","Balloting for Candidates","Bills against the Chapter","Applications for Membership","Reports of Committees","Unfinished Business","New Business (this is where elections are held)","Good of the Order","Receipts of Meeting","Closing"]},{"t":"ref","text":"The official Order of Business appears in the Handbook","page":"27"},{"t":"h","text":"The minutes: your Chapter's memory"},{"t":"p","text":"The **Scribe** records everything that happens in the meeting. The pro move: use a blank form with a slot for each item in the Order of Business, take a rough draft during the meeting, and rewrite it as final minutes before the next one, for the permanent Chapter record. Communications that are not of general interest do not get read in full — a brief summary is enough."},{"t":"list","items":["**Goes in:** every resolution and motion recorded in full, with the name of the member who made it and the member who seconded it.","**Goes in:** the visitors introduced by the MC, with full names correctly spelled and correct titles (Chapter, Lodge, etc.)."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"The minutes must **never include**: jokes, controversy or arguments, or the Scribe's own opinions and comments."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Electing new members: the ballot","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"To apply to DeMolay, a young man must have **passed his 12th birthday and not reached his 21st**, and be recommended by at least one member of the Chapter or by a Senior DeMolay holding a Senior DeMolay Certificate. The application is presented at a **stated meeting** (regular meeting) and must wait **at least one week** before being voted on, unless the Executive Officer authorizes otherwise. The MC refers it to an investigation committee of **three members**, which looks into the applicant's character and fitness and delivers a written report on or before the next stated meeting, when the vote takes place."},{"t":"h","text":"The ballot procedure, step by step"},{"t":"steps","items":["The MC directs the **Senior Deacon** to prepare the ballot box with a sufficient supply of white balls and black cubes.","The Senior Deacon presents the box to the JC, the SC, and the MC, in that order, so each can inspect that it is properly prepared.","The MC announces the ballot, states whether the committee report was favorable or unfavorable, reminds everyone that 'white balls elect, and black cubes reject', and casts his ballot first.","The Senior Deacon takes the box to the SC and then the JC, who vote at their stations.","He places the box on a stand by the northwest corner of the altar, casts his own vote, then stands halfway between the altar and the SC's station facing West, inspecting each voting member's **obligation card**.","Members vote in a line regardless of rank, starting with the Scribe: the whole south side of the room first, then the north side.","The Junior Deacon relieves the Sentinel so he can vote too; afterwards the Sentinel returns to his post.","The MC asks whether all entitled members have voted, declares the ballot closed with a rap of the gavel, and the Senior Deacon carries the box (inspected by the JC and SC) to the East, where the MC reads the result."]},{"t":"table","headers":["Black cubes","Result"],"rows":[["0 or 1","The candidate is **elected** to receive the Degrees."],["2","The application **lies over** until the next stated meeting, where a new ballot is taken. On that second ballot the candidate is elected unless 3 or more black cubes appear."],["3 or more","The application is **rejected**."]]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The ballot is **secret**: it must be conducted so that every vote stays private. Speed matters too, so the meeting does not drag and the applicant does not lose interest. When several applicants are balloted together and 2 or more black cubes appear, a separate ballot is taken on each application."},{"t":"p","text":"**Objections:** an unfavorable committee report, or an objection by any member before the ballot, is referred to the Chapter Advisor (or an Advisory Council member present), and the Advisory Council decides whether it constitutes a rejection. If the candidate has been elected but has not yet received any Degree, **three members** may file a signed written objection: the Chapter votes on it, and if **one-third of the members present** sustain it, the candidate stands rejected. Once he has received any Degree, objections only proceed through a regular trial before the Advisory Council. The Advisory Council may also declare an applicant elected or rejected if it serves DeMolay's best interests; if it declares him elected, the Chairman must report it to the Executive Officer before any Degree is conferred, for approval or disapproval. And once the Chapter has ordered a ballot, the MC cannot stop it on a private request — postponement must be moved and voted by the Chapter."},{"t":"ref","text":"The complete balloting procedure is in the Handbook","page":"31"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Officer elections","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The **MC, SC, and JC are elected by ballot**, for the term set in the Chapter's Bylaws. To be elected MC you must have served as Senior or Junior Councilor, with two exceptions: when the Advisory Council feels the Chapter's best interests call for another member, or when a new Chapter is being formed. The election uses a **paper ballot** cast by the individual members only, and winning takes a **majority of the ballots, not counting blanks**. The ballots should be prepared before the meeting."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Elected by ballot","text":"Master Councilor, Senior Councilor, and Junior Councilor, voted on paper by the members."},{"title":"Appointed by the Advisory Council","text":"The Scribe (may be an active member or a Senior DeMolay) and the Treasurer (must be a legal adult and a member of the Advisory Council). They serve until a successor is named and can be removed by the Advisory Council for neglecting their duties."},{"title":"Appointed by the MC","text":"All remaining officers, who occupy their stations during the MC's term of office."}]},{"t":"steps","items":["The MC declares that a ballot will be taken for the office of MC (then SC, and so on).","The Deacons pass out ballots to all brothers presenting their obligations.","They collect the ballots and take them to the table, where they are tabulated with the **Marshal's** assistance, and he communicates the results to the MC.","If there is a tie or no candidate gets a majority, a reballot is taken.","Once the Councilor-elect is known, the MC announces it; the winner may say a few words if he wishes."]},{"t":"p","text":"Officers may be installed at the same meeting where they are elected, or within **30 days** afterwards, as the Chapter determines."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**3 consecutive absences** from Chapter meetings without an excuse approved by the Chairman of the Advisory Council (or his designated representative) create a **vacancy in the office**, filled as outlined in the Bylaws or the Rules and Regulations of DeMolay International."}]},{"id":"l6","title":"General rules every Chapter lives by","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A handful of fixed rules govern every Chapter's life, from what gifts are allowed to when the uniform can appear in public. Knowing them keeps you out of expensive mistakes."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Gifts","text":"Chapter funds cannot buy presents for retiring officers, distinguished brethren, or new members. The one exception: with Advisory Council approval, a **Past Master Councilor's Jewel** for a retiring MC whose service was outstanding and whose record is above reproach — and who conferred both the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees **from memory** at least once during his term (with an exception if he was called into the armed services)."},{"title":"The emblem","text":"Never wear the emblem of the Order anywhere you would not take your mother or sister — doing so is conduct unbecoming a DeMolay and subject to discipline. Only the duly authorized emblem may be worn, and it cannot be given away, loaned, or worn by anyone else. DeMolay names and symbols cannot be used for business or advertising outside the Order."},{"title":"Uniform and regalia in public","text":"A Chapter may appear in public in uniform in only four cases: the funeral of a member, the observance of an Obligatory Day, a public installation of Officers, or by dispensation from the Executive Officer. Degree regalia cannot be loaned for non-DeMolay purposes."},{"title":"Discretion","text":"Improperly revealing the Chapter's transactions (unlawful revelation) means immediate suspension or expulsion once proven."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**Alcohol and drugs:** spending Chapter funds on liquor, or serving it at any Chapter meeting or function, is prohibited — and no member or officer may possess or distribute alcohol or drugs at any DeMolay event. **Tobacco:** strictly prohibited at any DeMolay function, including vaping and e-cigarettes. **Energy drinks:** many jurisdictions restrict them — check your Executive Officer's policy."},{"t":"table","headers":["Topic","Exact fact"],"rows":[["Degree fee","Set by DeMolay International; never less than $35.00. The affiliation fee, never less than $20.00."],["Remittance to DeMolay International","Within 10 days of conferring the Initiatory Degree, the Scribe remits the lifetime membership sum via eScribe."],["Charter","**Letters Temporary** (a provisional authorization) are granted for a limited period; after no less than 6 months of reasonable promise and permanence, the Executive Officer may recommend the Chapter for a Charter."],["By-Laws","Every Chapter adopts uniform By-Laws; it may add others if they are consistent with DeMolay International's and approved by the Executive Officer."],["Fiscal year","January 1st through December 31st."],["Patents","Issued by the Service & Leadership Center when the member's name is reported to the Grand Secretary's office via eScribe for both Degrees."]]},{"t":"ref","text":"The full General Information section is in the Handbook","page":"35"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"Which is the only committee the DeMolay Rules & Regulations require every Chapter to have?","options":["Finance","Membership","Auditing","Publicity and Chapter Communications"],"correct":1,"explain":"Of the 14 suggested committees, only the Membership Committee is required; the rest depend on the Chapter's size."},{"q":"During a meeting, what do three raps of the gavel mean?","options":["The whole Chapter sits down","Only the Officers rise","The whole Chapter rises","The meeting is closed"],"correct":2,"explain":"One rap seats the Chapter, two raps call up the Officers, and three raps call up the whole Chapter."},{"q":"Exactly 2 black cubes appear when balloting on a candidate. What happens to his application?","options":["He is elected anyway","It is permanently rejected","It lies over until the next stated meeting","The ballot is retaken that same night"],"correct":2,"explain":"With 2 black cubes the application lies over: it is balloted again at the next stated meeting, where only 3 or more black cubes reject it."},{"q":"How many points are in the official Order of Business for a Chapter meeting?","options":["12","15","17","20"],"correct":2,"explain":"There are 17 fixed points, from Opening to Closing, repeated at every meeting."},{"q":"What must NOT appear in the minutes kept by the Scribe?","options":["The name of whoever makes each motion","His personal opinions and comments","The full names of visitors","Resolutions recorded in full"],"correct":1,"explain":"Minutes exclude jokes, controversy, and the Scribe's opinions or comments; motions and visitors are recorded."},{"q":"An officer misses 3 consecutive meetings without an excuse approved by the Chairman of the Advisory Council. What happens?","options":["He receives a formal warning","His office becomes vacant","He loses voting rights for a month","Nothing, if he explains later"],"correct":1,"explain":"Three consecutive unexcused absences create a vacancy, filled as outlined in the Bylaws or DeMolay International's rules."},{"q":"What is the only gift a Chapter may buy with its funds?","options":["A present for each new member","Gifts for all retiring officers","The Past Master Councilor's Jewel for an outstanding retiring MC","A plaque for the Chapter Advisor"],"correct":2,"explain":"Only the PMC Jewel, with Advisory Council approval and only if the MC conferred both Degrees from memory at least once during his term."},{"q":"What is the DeMolay fiscal year for Chapters?","options":["July 1st through June 30th","January 1st through December 31st","September 1st through August 31st","March 1st through February 28th"],"correct":1,"explain":"The DeMolay fiscal year for Chapters runs from January 1st through December 31st."}]},"oficiales":{"title":"Chapter Officers","subtitle":"Who does what: from the three elected leaders to the 18 appointees, with their exact duties.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"23 Offices, Three Ways In","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A Chapter runs on **23 officers**, and they don't all get there the same way. Three are elected by ballot, two are appointed by the Advisory Council, and the other 18 are picked by the Master Councilor. Every officer holds his office until his successor has been duly elected or appointed and installed."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Elected (3)","text":"Master Councilor (MC), Senior Councilor (SC), and Junior Councilor (JC). The members elect them with paper ballots, for the term set in the Chapter's Bylaws. The winner needs a majority of the ballots cast — blank ballots don't count."},{"title":"Appointed by the Advisory Council (2)","text":"Treasurer and Scribe. They serve at the Council's pleasure until their successors are appointed and installed. The Treasurer must be a legal adult, and one Advisor may serve as both Treasurer and Scribe."},{"title":"Appointed by the MC (18)","text":"The rest of the officer line. They serve at the MC's pleasure."}]},{"t":"list","items":["Senior Deacon and Junior Deacon","Senior Steward and Junior Steward","Chaplain","Almoner","Marshal","Standard Bearer","Orator","The 7 Preceptors","Sentinel","Organist"]},{"t":"p","text":"To run for any office you must be an **active member** who has qualified for his **Obligation Card** — and you need to have received it to vote in the election, too. There's one extra bar for MC: you must have served as SC or JC first, unless the Advisory Council believes another member's election will serve the Chapter best, or the Chapter is brand new."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Missing 3 consecutive Chapter meetings without being excused by the Advisory Council's Chairman (or his designated representative) automatically creates a vacancy in your office."},{"t":"p","text":"If the MC's office goes vacant, the SC becomes MC, the JC moves up to SC, and the JC's office is filled by regular election — with **2 weeks'** written notice to the members. Whoever is moving up may prefer to stay put; in that case the election is held for whichever office is vacant. Any officer can resign, and a resignation can also be demanded: a resolution moved at one regular meeting, sustained by a **three-fourths** affirmative vote of the members present at the next regular meeting, with the approval of the Jurisdiction's Executive Officer or his designated representative."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full rules on elections, vacancies, and resignations","page":"40"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Master Councilor: Setting the Pace","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The MC holds the same position a president holds in any other organization: he's the Chapter's ranking youth leader. And members mirror his mood and work ethic — if the MC radiates enthusiasm, the Chapter gives it right back. The Handbook asks him to be cheerful, fair, sympathetic, and democratic: you lead a democracy, not a dictatorship."},{"t":"h","text":"Your Term Program"},{"t":"steps","items":["As soon as you're elected — before your Installation — outline your term program with specific dates: degree conferrals, social activities, visitations, special activities, and any Obligatory Days that fall in your term.","Work out the plans in consultation with the other Officers, the Chapter Advisors, and any committees concerned.","Get it printed and hand it to every member at your first meeting as MC.","Set a personal goal: qualifying for the PMC-MSA (Past Master Councilor's Meritorious Service Award)."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The MC's term minimums: at least 1 social activity, 1 civic service project, 1 fund-raising activity, and 1 Initiation. Plus initiating his pro-rata share of the Chapter's assigned new member goal."},{"t":"p","text":"On Installation night, or as soon after as possible (often right after the election), you may appoint the committees: **Sick, Entertainment, Auditing, Finance, and Membership**, plus any others the Chapter needs. The recommended policy: every member sits on at least one committee. You're an ex-officio (non-voting) member of all of them — but let each one do its job. Check progress closely the first few weeks and reassign duties if a committee stalls."},{"t":"list","items":["See that the Chapter fully observes DeMolay's Rules & Regulations, that accurate records are kept, and that all reports and remittances to DeMolay International go out on time.","Preside at Chapter meetings; if absent, the next ranking officer presides.","Call special meetings — and he must if requested.","Appoint officers, the Standing Committees, the committees that investigate Applications for Membership, and all special committees, per the Bylaws.","Superintend the observance of the Obligatory Days falling in his term."]},{"t":"p","text":"Two details many MCs miss: **only the MC** may read the application and the investigation report in a Chapter meeting, and presiding well takes real parliamentary procedure — a copy of Robert's Rules of Order belongs in the Chapter library, as long as you don't let formality swallow the meeting. With the Advisors, the relationship is cooperation: they're there to counsel you, not to do your work."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Senior and Junior Councilor: The Line of Succession","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The SC is **second in command** and, in most cases, is working toward being MC next term. He has to stay ready to take over the MC's duties whenever needed, and he often leads parts of the ceremonies precisely to build that experience."},{"t":"list","items":["Supervise one-half of the Chapter's committees — the Handbook recommends this over tying him down to chairing any single one, though traditionally he chairs the Entertainment Committee.","Own the problem of member attendance at meetings, which is closely tied to the quality of each meeting's program.","Start sketching his own term program, so planning moves fast if he's elected MC."]},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook's best single definition of his job: **seek to lighten the workload of the MC**."},{"t":"p","text":"The JC is **third in command** and must be prepared to step up as SC or MC whenever called upon. Unlike the SC, whose duties aren't clearly spelled out anywhere in the Bylaws, the JC has one that is."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The JC's defined duty: coaching new members to earn their Obligation certifications — the memorization they need to enjoy all the rights and benefits of a member in good standing. The bigger the Chapter, the more help he needs, so a coaching committee is usually named."},{"t":"list","items":["Supervise the other half of the Chapter's committees, mirroring the recommendation for the SC.","Orient the new members: when this duty gets skipped, too many new members go inactive within a year."]}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Treasurer: Keeping the Chapter's Money Straight","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Treasurer serves a calendar-year term: **January 1 to December 31**. The primary function is keeping an accurate account of all receipts and disbursements — showing **separately** the funds that belong to the Chapter and the funds that belong to DeMolay International."},{"t":"p","text":"The money flow is simple and non-negotiable: the Scribe collects all fees and dues, hands them to the Treasurer, and the Treasurer gives the Scribe a receipt for the money received."},{"t":"list","items":["Prepare vouchers (bank checks), carefully numbered and filed.","Every payout is signed by the Treasurer or the Master Councilor and countersigned by a member of the Advisory Council, after authorization at a regular business meeting of the Chapter.","For electronic disbursements, all payout approvers must have online viewing access or be automatically copied on every transaction.","Funds belonging to DeMolay International are paid out without needing Chapter authorization.","Make a monthly report to the Advisory Council of all funds held, and a report of official acts at the DeMolay year's last meeting.","At the end of the term, deliver all money and Chapter property to the successor, or whoever the Advisory Council directs.","If the Advisory Council requests it, furnish a Bond with a responsible corporate surety company, at the Chapter's expense, to protect the funds against losses."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Cash is never used to handle any payment transaction of the Chapter. No exceptions."}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Scribe: The Third Most Important Job","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook doesn't sugarcoat it: the Scribe ranks third in importance, behind only the Chapter Advisor and the MC. The motto says it all: \"So goes the Scribe, so goes the Chapter.\" The Advisory Council appoints the Scribe for a calendar-year term (January 1 to December 31), and the job can go to an active DeMolay, a Senior DeMolay, or an Advisor. When a young member gets it, a Scribe Advisor is usually named to counsel him — and the smart move is training the next Scribe as an assistant Scribe before he takes over. One catch: the Advisory Council can remove a Scribe at any time for neglecting the duties."},{"t":"list","items":["Record all the Chapter's transactions (the minutes) and keep the records available for inspection.","Collect all fees and pay them immediately to the Treasurer, taking a receipt.","Make a monthly report to the Advisory Council, showing DeMolay International's funds separately.","See that Chapter property is cared for and keep an accurate inventory.","Make the Annual Reports and any other reports required by the Bylaws or requested by the Grand Secretary, with the proper remittances.","Send out meeting notices and the dates of the Obligatory Days.","At the end of the term, deliver all books, papers, money, and property to the successor."]},{"t":"h","text":"eScribe: The System That Holds It All Together"},{"t":"p","text":"eScribe keeps each member's complete DeMolay history: petition, initiation records, offices held, majority date. Every candidate who receives the Initiatory Degree must be reported to the Service and Leadership Center through eScribe, with the **$35** initiation fee remitted for each new initiate — that $35 buys the initiate pre-paid membership in DeMolay International for life, plus his Patent (his membership certificate). Until he's reported on eScribe, a member is **not officially registered** with the Chapter or DeMolay International."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"If the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees aren't conferred the same evening or within 10 days of one another, report the Initiatory Degree immediately with the $35 fee — then report again on eScribe when the DeMolay Degree is finally conferred. The Patent is only issued once both degrees are reported with their dates and all fees are paid."},{"t":"p","text":"The **Annual Report** is critical: it's the only method the Grand Secretary has of staying fully informed about each Chapter's financial, membership, and general condition. The Scribe and the Chairman of the Advisory Council prepare it together on eScribe. The Scribe also creates the Senior DeMolay Member Certificate there — it attests to the 21-year-old member's retirement in good standing, and should be presented publicly at his Majority Service if possible. And one habit worth preaching for life: keep your eScribe profile current. Thousands of mailings bounce back to Headquarters every year over stale addresses."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Every letter or email to DeMolay International (Service & Leadership Center, Kansas City) must carry, in the upper right-hand corner: the date, the Scribe's name, address, phone number, and the Chapter's name and location."},{"t":"ref","text":"The Scribe's full 11 duties under the Bylaws","page":"47"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Who Does What in Each Ceremony","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every ceremony has its own cast of ritual parts. Knowing them pays off twice: you know where you can step in, and every part you perform earns points on the ISC point scale toward the **Ritual bar** in the Merit Bar system."},{"t":"table","headers":["Ceremony","Parts"],"rows":[["Initiatory Degree","Master Councilor, Senior Councilor, Junior Councilor, Senior Deacon, Chaplain, the Preceptors, Senior Steward, Junior Steward, and Marshal"],["DeMolay Degree","Master Councilor, Jacques DeMolay, Geoffrey de Charney, Master Inquisitor, Senior Inquisitor, Junior Inquisitor, Senior Guard, Orator, and Marshal"],["Installation Service","Installing Officer, Installing Senior Councilor, Installing Junior Councilor, Installing Marshal, and Installing Chaplain"],["Majority Service","Master Councilor, Senior Councilor, Junior Councilor, and Chaplain"]]},{"t":"p","text":"The DeMolay Degree is the special one: several officers set their titles aside and portray historical figures from the Templars' trial, like **Jacques DeMolay** and **Geoffrey de Charney**. Other ceremonies with parts of their own: the Representative DeMolay Ceremony (Chancellor and Herald) and the Cross of Honor (MC, SC, JC, and Marshal)."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Special parts that are worth a lot on the ritual point scale: the Flower Talk is worth 40 points and the Ceremony of Light, 30. The Father Talk is worth 15."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full list of parts per ceremony and point values","page":"206"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"Which three offices are elected by ballot of the Chapter members?","options":["Master Councilor, Senior Councilor, and Junior Councilor","Master Councilor, Scribe, and Treasurer","Master Councilor, Chapter Advisor, and Scribe","Senior Councilor, Junior Councilor, and Marshal"],"correct":0,"explain":"The MC, SC, and JC are elected with paper ballots. The Scribe and Treasurer are appointed by the Advisory Council, and the other 18 officers are appointed by the MC."},{"q":"How many officers does the Master Councilor appoint?","options":["12","18","21","7"],"correct":1,"explain":"Besides the 3 elected officers and the 2 appointed by the Advisory Council, the MC appoints 18 officers, including the 7 Preceptors."},{"q":"What activity minimums must the MC meet during his term?","options":["At least 1 social, 1 civic, 1 fund-raising activity, and 1 Initiation","Just at least 1 Initiation","2 socials and 2 fund-raisers","One activity of each type per month"],"correct":0,"explain":"The Bylaws require at least one social, one civic, and one fund-raising activity, and an Initiation held at least once during his term."},{"q":"What happens if an officer misses 3 consecutive meetings without being excused by the Advisory Council's Chairman?","options":["He receives a formal warning","He loses his Obligation Card","A vacancy is automatically created in his office","He must pay a fine to the Chapter"],"correct":2,"explain":"Three consecutive unexcused absences automatically create a vacancy in the office."},{"q":"What is the Junior Councilor's one clearly defined duty in the Bylaws?","options":["Chairing the Entertainment Committee","Coaching new members for their Obligation certifications","Keeping the Chapter's minutes","Tracking meeting attendance"],"correct":1,"explain":"Coaching the Obligations is the JC's defined duty. Attendance is suggested for the SC, and the minutes belong to the Scribe."},{"q":"Which of these rules applies to handling the Chapter's money?","options":["Cash is never used for payments","The Treasurer may pay small expenses in cash","The Scribe keeps the money he collects","The MC authorizes payments without a countersignature"],"correct":0,"explain":"Payments go out as numbered checks, signed by the Treasurer or the MC and countersigned by an Advisory Council member. Cash is off-limits, and the Scribe hands everything he collects to the Treasurer in exchange for a receipt."},{"q":"How much is the initiation fee remitted for each new initiate reported on eScribe?","options":["$25","$35","$50","$10"],"correct":1,"explain":"It's $35 per initiate, which buys pre-paid membership in DeMolay International for life plus the Patent."},{"q":"If the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees aren't conferred the same evening, within how many days must they happen to be reported together?","options":["30 days","10 days","60 days","There is no deadline"],"correct":1,"explain":"If they aren't conferred the same evening or within 10 days of one another, the Initiatory is reported immediately with the $35, and the DeMolay Degree is reported separately later."}]},"adultos":{"title":"The Adults Behind the Chapter","subtitle":"Who they are, how they get there, and what powers your Advisory Council actually has.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"The Advisory Council: Your Adult Team","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Behind every strong Chapter there's a team of adult volunteers: the **Advisory Council**. The Handbook is blunt: without solid adult leadership, a Chapter fades into a \"do-nothing\" Chapter and then disappears. But the Chapter belongs to you and your brothers — the adults advise, support, and keep the framework safe."},{"t":"list","items":["Required base: at least **3 Master Masons** in good standing.","Any adult **over 21** can serve as an Advisor: moms, dads, teachers, Senior DeMolays, neighbors... you don't have to be a Mason (except for the Chairman).","DeMolay International requires a minimum of **5 Advisors** total — more hands make the load lighter for everyone.","The Sponsoring Body (the Masonic body backing the Chapter) may recommend candidates, but appointments are made by the Jurisdiction's **Executive Officer**.","The term of office is **1 year**, renewed every year."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The minimum formula: 3 Master Masons + 5 Advisors total, all 21+, appointed by the Executive Officer for 1-year terms."},{"t":"p","text":"What matters most isn't how many Advisors there are, but that **the duties are divided**: everyone has something concrete to do and nobody carries the whole Chapter alone."},{"t":"ref","text":"Organization and purpose of the Advisory Council","page":"55"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"How Someone Becomes an Advisor (and Stays One)","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Being an Advisor takes more than good intentions: there's a rigorous screening process designed to keep DeMolay a **safe** environment for you. Here's how it works for a new Advisor:"},{"t":"steps","items":["Be at least **21 years old**.","Register online at **eScribe.DeMolay.org/Sign Up** and pay the processing fee.","Pass a **background check** confirming they're suitable to work with youth.","Pass the online **DeMolay Advisor Training**, covering risk management and youth protection policies.","The registration goes to the **Executive Officer** for approval, then to the **Service & Leadership Center** for processing (some areas require extra forms).","Only then do the Advisor membership card and certificate of appointment arrive."]},{"t":"h","text":"Annual Recertification"},{"t":"p","text":"Getting certified once isn't enough. Every year, every Advisor — brand new or decades in — must complete the **Continuing Advisor Certification**, available each fall on eScribe: update their contact information, answer the **youth protection** questions, and pay the renewal fee. Everything is reviewed and approved by the Executive Officer."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Deadline: the annual certification must be received online at the Service & Leadership Center before November 30 each year. Without it, no current-year card is issued."},{"t":"p","text":"Two more facts: the Executive Officer can **remove** any Advisor who won't perform their duties, and every Council member renews a vow of allegiance to DeMolay International and the Executive Officer each year."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"The Council's Powers: Elections, Discipline, and Rules","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Advisory Council's duties are primarily **legislative and judicial**. It must meet **at least once a month**, with an agenda, parliamentary procedure, and a full written record of every meeting. It governs the Chapter's activities as long as nothing conflicts with the Bylaws of DeMolay International or the Executive Officer's orders."},{"t":"list","items":["**Organize**: select a Chairman (who must be a Mason), a Chapter Advisor, Treasurer, and Scribe, and divide the work.","**Guide without running**: help the Chapter run itself — don't run the Chapter.","**Regulate**: make sure the Chapter operates within DeMolay International's Bylaws, rules, and requirements.","**Check the budget** and watch the Chapter's finances closely.","**Select the Chapter Scribe and Treasurer** (the youth officers who keep records and funds).","**Insist on growth**: keep membership drives front and center."]},{"t":"h","text":"Membership Elections"},{"t":"p","text":"No election of an applicant for degrees or affiliation becomes final **until the Advisory Council approves it**. And if the Council declares someone elected on its own, it must send a detailed report to the Executive Officer for approval before any degree can be conferred."},{"t":"h","text":"Discipline"},{"t":"steps","items":["The Council can remove from membership anyone who violates DeMolay law or whose conduct is unworthy of the Order.","First, notice goes to the Executive Officer and formal written charges are served on the member.","The hearing must be **at least 30 days** after the charges are served; the member can answer them and be represented by any relative or a Master Mason.","The hearing happens in executive session; the decision must be in writing, signed by a **majority** of the Council.","Nothing is final without the Executive Officer's approval, and everything can be appealed to DeMolay International, whose decision is final."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Chaperone rule: every Chapter party or social event needs at least 2 Advisors present for every 5 active members."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Any Advisor who is present may exclude from a meeting or function any visitor — DeMolay, Senior DeMolay, Master Mason, or anyone else — whose presence harms the peace and harmony of the Chapter."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"The Money: The Council as Financial Guardian","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A Chapter is normally **self-supporting**: the Sponsoring Body doesn't take on direct financial responsibility, but the Council does take on the moral responsibility of making sure the Chapter stays out of debt. That's why it reviews the monthly financial reports from the Scribe and Treasurer. The Handbook's practical rule: get the money first, then buy."},{"t":"list","items":["Funds collected for DeMolay International (like Initiation fees) **belong to DeMolay International**: kept in a separate account and paid on schedule, no Chapter vote required.","Every expense needs a receipt and is paid by **check**, signed by the Treasurer or Master Councilor and countersigned by an Advisory Council member. For electronic payments, all approvers must have online viewing access or be automatically copied on transactions.","Every expenditure (except funds owed to DeMolay International) must be approved by **vote at a regular Chapter business meeting**.","**Never cash** for Chapter payments, and Chapter funds can never be loaned to anyone.","Surplus funds may be invested only if the Chapter votes for it, and each investment needs approval by a **two-thirds vote of all Advisory Council members**, always under the Executive Officer's control."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"The only gift Chapter funds can buy: a PMC's jewel for a retiring Master Councilor with an outstanding record. Nothing else. And before soliciting funds from anyone outside the Chapter, the Council needs the Executive Officer's permission."},{"t":"p","text":"The budget is usually drafted by a finance committee and approved by the Council — which still must approve **each expenditure** as it happens, and can adjust allotments if revenue changes. When each new Master Councilor is installed, the Council approves the auditing committee's report on the Treasurer's and Scribe's books."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"If a Chapter falls behind on its Annual Report and other fees to DeMolay International, it's automatically temporarily suspended — and if that suspension for nonpayment reaches 3 months, the Charter is automatically forfeited."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full detail of the financial rules","page":"61"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Chairman and Chapter Advisor: The Two Pillars","blocks":[{"t":"h","text":"Chairman of the Advisory Council"},{"t":"p","text":"The Chairman — who **must be a Mason** — is like the head coach of the Advisor team: he presides over the Council, calls and runs the monthly meetings, delegates work so nothing overlaps, acts as liaison with the Sponsoring Body, and is the **Executive Officer's primary contact** with the Council. He also makes sure the Annual Report is filed on time on eScribe and that Advisors keep getting trained."},{"t":"h","text":"Chapter Advisor"},{"t":"p","text":"Choosing the Chapter Advisor is considered **the Council's most important decision**: a Chapter's success depends more on this person than on any other single factor. They're the Chapter's administrative officer, but above all a trusted mentor you can go to with your problems. The Handbook asks for someone \"young at heart,\" if not in years."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Recommended rotation: 1 or 2 years in the role. Why? The job takes lots of time, energy, and personal expense, and someone who stays too long gets \"stale\" with no fresh ideas. Two people working for DeMolay beats one person entrenched forever."},{"t":"list","items":["Attend every meeting and activity (or make sure another Advisor covers).","See that the Chapter runs by the Bylaws and that the ritual is done well — and from memory.","Suggest and lead, never command and drive: **the Chapter belongs to the young men**, and they do the governing.","Plan the program a year ahead in general and a term ahead in detail.","Keep the program balanced across social, civic, athletic, service, and fundraising activities — with a job for every member."]},{"t":"p","text":"The **Assistant Chapter Advisor** — ideally a younger adult or a Senior DeMolay — backs up the Chapter Advisor, steps in when they're absent, and trains to take over the role someday. Succession planning is part of the job too."}]},{"id":"l6","title":"The Rest of the Team: Specialized Roles","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay International doesn't mandate one fixed Advisor lineup: each Council builds its own based on its people and reality, and one Advisor can cover two or more functions. One of them may serve as Secretary of the Council. These are the most common roles:"},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Ritual Advisor","text":"The latest edition of the Ritual, to the letter. All degree work is done **from memory** (the Bylaws require it), with an alternate for every part and officers proving proficiency before installation."},{"title":"Scribe Advisor","text":"Coaches the Chapter Scribe: minutes, fees and dues passed to the Treasurer, the monthly financial report, and reports like the Annual Report. The Scribe is appointed by the Council for 1 year — ideally a PMC or Senior DeMolay."},{"title":"Treasurer / Financial Advisor","text":"Watches financial health: the Life Membership trust account, countersigning checks, overseeing fundraising, and keeping the prescribed minimum bank balance."},{"title":"Membership Advisor","text":"Builds a recruiting plan with the Master Councilor, promotes contests and frequent Initiations, and leads new-member orientation so nobody drifts away after joining."},{"title":"Awards Advisor","text":"Knows every award cold: Merit Bars, the Blue Honor Key (first-line signer on 10 applications, plus a star for every additional 10), the Representative DeMolay Award, and the Chevalier — the highest honor. Standards stay high, always."},{"title":"Masonic & Public Relations Advisor","text":"The bond with the Sponsoring Body and the Masonic family, local press, the Chapter's social media and website, and the historical record."},{"title":"Communications Advisor","text":"Gets the word out: a current roster, a consistent format, and a reminder to every member and Advisor before each event. Brings 2 or more active DeMolays onto the team."},{"title":"Activities / Athletics Advisor","text":"Coordinates activities and sports for all ages and skill levels, finds suitable competition, and gets older members and Senior DeMolays coaching."},{"title":"Civic Service Advisor","text":"Spots community service opportunities and requires **one service project each term**."},{"title":"Fundraising Advisor","text":"Helps pick smart fundraisers, requires reporting at every step, and checks that the income matches the effort."},{"title":"Social Advisor","text":"Keeps the social calendar interesting for every age group, lines up chaperones, and guides cost and venue while the members lead — without forgetting the fun."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Nominating honors is also Council business: the Chevalier for DeMolays, the Cross of Honor for Advisors, and the Legion of Honor for Senior DeMolays or Master Masons — all filed online in eScribe. Medal of Heroism nominations go to the Executive Officer."},{"t":"p","text":"So what do Advisors get out of all this? Nothing material. As the Handbook puts it: \"The rewards of life can't be counted in honors or dollars, but rather in the eyes of those you have served!\""},{"t":"ref","text":"Complete list of Advisor roles and duties","page":"64"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"What is the minimum composition of an Advisory Council?","options":["At least 3 Master Masons and 5 Advisors total","At least 5 Master Masons and 3 Advisors total","At least 2 Master Masons and 4 Advisors total","Any number of adults, as long as there's a Chairman"],"correct":0,"explain":"The required base is at least 3 Master Masons in good standing, and DeMolay International requires a minimum of 5 Advisors in total."},{"q":"Who officially appoints the Advisors?","options":["The Chapter's Sponsoring Body","The Jurisdiction's Executive Officer","The Master Councilor with a Chapter vote","DeMolay International directly"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Sponsoring Body may recommend candidates, but appointments are always made by the Executive Officer."},{"q":"How long is an Advisor's term of office?","options":["1 year, renewed each year","2 fixed years","Until they decide to step down","5 years, with a mid-term review"],"correct":0,"explain":"The term is 1 year and must be renewed annually through the recertification approved by the Executive Officer."},{"q":"By what date must the annual certification for continuing Advisors be completed?","options":["September 30","December 31","November 30","March 1"],"correct":2,"explain":"The Continuing Advisor Certification must be received online at the Service & Leadership Center before November 30 — otherwise no current-year card is issued."},{"q":"At a social event with 15 active members present, what's the minimum number of Advisors required?","options":["2","3","6","15"],"correct":2,"explain":"The rule is at least 2 Advisors for every 5 active members: with 15 members, that's a minimum of 6 Advisors."},{"q":"How often must the Advisory Council meet, at minimum?","options":["Once a week","At least once a month","Once per term","Only when there are disciplinary matters"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Council must meet at least once a month and keep a full written record of every meeting."},{"q":"What special requirement applies to the Chairman of the Advisory Council?","options":["He must be a Senior DeMolay","He must be at least 30 years old","He must be the longest-serving Advisor","He must be a Mason"],"correct":3,"explain":"When organizing, the Council selects a Chairman who must be a Mason; he's the Executive Officer's primary contact with the Council."},{"q":"Under the rules the Ritual Advisor enforces, how must degree work be presented?","options":["Entirely from memory, as the Bylaws of DeMolay International direct","Read aloud, to avoid mistakes in the ceremonies","From memory only for the leading parts","However each officer prefers"],"correct":0,"explain":"All degree work must be given from memory; elective officers must also prove proficiency in their part before being installed."}]},"planificacion":{"title":"Plan the Year: Program, Budget, and Obligatory Days","subtitle":"How to build your Chapter's annual program step by step, with numbers that add up and zero guesswork.","minutes":13,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"The Program Planning Committee: No Winging It","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A successful Chapter doesn't hit December wondering what it will do next year — it already has it in writing. The annual program is the Chapter's **blueprint for action**: it kills guesswork, adds stability, and gives every term a direction. And the more people who pitch in ideas — Officers, Members, and Advisors — the broader and more exciting the program becomes."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Next DeMolay year's program should be finalized **by the first of December**. It is built by the **Program Planning Committee**: the Master Councilor, Senior Councilor, Junior Councilor, and Chapter Advisor."},{"t":"p","text":"Why those four? The incoming Master Councilor is the one who will run the program that gets adopted; the Senior and Junior Councilors will most likely be the next Master Councilors, so the Chapter's future is their business too; and the Chapter Advisor brings DeMolay experience and serves as the liaison between the Chapter and the Advisory Council."},{"t":"h","text":"Before You Sit Down to Plan"},{"t":"steps","items":["Survey the Members with the **Members' Interest Survey**: a sheet with six categories — Athletics, Civic Service, Entertainment, Social, Fundraising, and Miscellaneous — where everyone checks what interests them and adds their own suggestions. Run it at a regular meeting and mail it to anyone absent.","The Master Councilor appoints **special committees** by area (Athletics, Civic Service, Entertainment, Fundraising, and Social are suggested), and the Advisory Council Chairman assigns an Advisor to work with each one.","Each special committee analyzes the survey and recommends activities with a tentative month and a cost breakdown. Recommendations must be well rounded, cover the entire year (January through December), and be within the Chapter's physical and financial ability.","Meanwhile, the Program Planning Committee gathers information: Member data from **eScribe**, school and community dates, the Obligatory Days, leadership camps and conferences, deadlines (Annual Report, International and Jurisdictional competitions), the Conclave, and area Masonic family events.","A general meeting brings together the three Councilors, the special committee chairmen, and the Chapter Advisor to present ideas and iron out conflicts between recommendations."]},{"t":"p","text":"Then comes the **actual planning session**, attended only by the four committee members. It produces three deliverables: the year's program, a detailed Term Program Plan, and a preliminary budget for both the term and the year."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full Members' Interest Survey template is in the Handbook","page":"87"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"The 6 Steps to Complete the Program","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"With the survey processed and the facts on the table, the committee builds the annual calendar by following six concrete steps."},{"t":"steps","items":["List everything required and annual on your calendar: the **seven Obligatory Days**, the officer election date, the Installation, known Jurisdictional dates (Conclave, etc.), mid-level dates, the Chapter's annual events, and the Advisory Council's monthly meetings.","Add the membership plans: prospect parties and other membership drive events, linked to the scheduled Initiatory and DeMolay Degree dates.","Add the events the special committees recommended and budgeted, plus the Miscellaneous survey items that earn a spot. Here you'll have to select, shuffle, or eliminate — some months will overflow.","Develop each month day by day on monthly calendars: pick the date for each activity while steering clear of school events, community events, and holidays.","Evaluate the program as a whole: months that are thin or overloaded, the number and variety of activities, and the program's cost against the Chapter's income.","Transfer the monthly events from the calendars to a list — but keep the calendars. That visual picture will help you all year long."]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"At step 5, check that your program meets the requirements for the **Past Master Councilor's Meritorious Service Award (PMC-MSA)** and add any activities you're missing."},{"t":"p","text":"With the year locked in, you draft the first term's plan. Fixed rule: a detailed program for **each term is developed at least two months before that term begins**."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Term Planning: One Sheet per Month","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The term plan brings the annual program down to earth. You work with **one 8½ x 11-inch sheet per month**, leaving ample space between activities, and you lock in the final date for each event — once again dodging school and community conflicts."},{"t":"steps","items":["Transfer each activity from the year's program to its monthly sheet and assign it a date.","Under each meeting night, list everything that must happen that evening: committee reports, committee appointments, other known business, and the entertainment or program (which builds interest and boosts attendance).","Do basic planning on all the other events with as much detail as you have, review the whole picture, and adjust. Every term gets programmed the same way."]},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Progress report","text":"At the meetings ahead of the final report: how the event prep is coming along."},{"title":"Final report","text":"At the meeting just before the event: everything confirmed and ready to execute."},{"title":"Post report","text":"After the event: evaluation, accounting, and feedback for the future."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Before each meeting, add the list of new and old business so the agenda runs smoothly — no surprises."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"The Budget: Make the Numbers Work","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Planning without budgeting is only half the job. The committee's final phase is estimating the expenses and income of every activity, month by month, for both the term and the full year."},{"t":"steps","items":["List the cost of every program item, month by month, without forgetting the **fixed expenses**: monthly rent, office supplies, the newsletter (if your Chapter has one), the Installation (flowers, PMC pin), and awards and honors (merit bars, etc.).","List the income you expect: fundraising, event income, new members, interest on a savings account, and donations. Itemize and total every month — each month has to pay for itself.","Add up total expenses and total income and check that the budget balances. If it doesn't: increase income (add fundraisers, raise prices) or decrease expenses (substitute cheaper events, or cut some entirely)."]},{"t":"h","text":"A Real November, in Numbers"},{"t":"table","headers":["Item","Expense","Income"],"rows":[["Rent for November","$50.00","—"],["Office expenses (including postage)","$7.00","—"],["Flowers for the Flower Talk (50¢ each)","$5.00","—"],["Candidates: 6 x $60 = $360, less ISC fee via eScribe ($35 each = $210) and Trust Account deposit for Life Fees ($20 each = $120)","—","$30.00 to the Current Operating Account"],["Frank S. Land Memorial Day program (Chapter's share of refreshments)","$16.00","—"],["Chapter newsletter (paper and ink)","$4.00","—"],["Fundraising: Christmas candy sale (2 days, 200 boxes, 40% profit)","—","$80.00"],["Prize for the winning team (four $2 hockey tickets)","$8.00","—"],["TOTAL","$90.00","$110.00"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Each candidate's **$60 fee** splits like this: **$35 to the ISC fee via eScribe, $20 to the Trust Account for Life Fees**, and the remaining $5 stays in the Chapter's Current Operating Account."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full sample budget is in the Handbook","page":"93"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"The Seven Obligatory Days","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook fixes these as special ceremonial days whose observance \"is made obligatory on all Members of DeMolay unless prevented by unavoidable circumstances.\" There are seven, each with its own date window and an officer who usually leads the planning."},{"t":"table","headers":["Day","When","Who Runs It"],"rows":[["Devotional Day","A day during the week that includes March 18th","Chaplain"],["Patriots' Day","A convenient day in February","Standard Bearer"],["Day of Comfort","Between November 15th and December 31st","Almoner"],["Educational Day","A convenient day in September","Junior and Senior Stewards"],["Parents' Day","Between May 1st and June 21st","Preceptors"],["My Government Day","During July","Orator and Marshal"],["Frank S. Land Memorial Day","A day near November 8th","The Chapter (no officer assigned)"]]},{"t":"p","text":"An Executive Officer (the top DeMolay authority in your jurisdiction) may set a different month or day for an observance to better fit local or jurisdictional customs — the Bylaws of DeMolay International allow it."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Ideas from the Handbook: on Devotional Day, perform the Flower Talk during the service; on Patriots' Day, pay tribute to living veterans; on Frank S. Land Memorial Day, run a special fundraiser and donate the proceeds to a DeMolay charity."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full activity suggestions for each day","page":"105"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Organizing a Project in 5 Steps","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"We've all seen it: a great idea comes up at a meeting, everyone gets fired up... and the event never happens. It happens thousands of times in DeMolay Chapters and everywhere else. To keep your project alive, follow this five-step sequence."},{"t":"steps","items":["Get **general support from the membership**: the Chapter must approve the idea in principle first, or the support you'll need later won't be there.","The Master Councilor appoints a **committee and its chairman**. The committee drafts tentative plans and gathers the facts needed to decide, with duties delegated: publicity, refreshments, program and speaker, transportation.","The chairman takes the preliminary plans back to the Chapter for its **approval**.","**Execute**: confirm arrangements, print and mail invitations well in advance, get the degree coaches working. The chairman runs a chronological countdown so he knows when each job is due, supervises without doing all the work himself, nudges some and praises others.","**Evaluate and report**: hold a follow-up meeting with everyone involved, give a final report to the Chapter, and keep a copy in the Chapter files so the next committee can profit from the experience."]},{"t":"p","text":"The Advisor works **behind the scenes**, guiding the chairman: the visible leader is always a DeMolay, never the adult. And the Advisor is the one who remembers the details young people tend to forget — the prep before the event and the evaluation after it, not just the big day."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Straight from the Handbook: advance ticket sales for a car wash usually **double the profit** compared with selling only on the day of the event."}]},{"id":"l7","title":"The Year in Action: Model Program and the Scribe's Calendar","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Here is what the year-round plan of a genuinely active Chapter looks like, condensed month by month. Notice how every month mixes membership, fun, service, and fundraising — and how the Obligatory Days always land in their windows:"},{"t":"table","headers":["Month","Highlights"],"rows":[["January","Officer Installation and awards night; submit the Annual Report; DeMolay Week planning begins"],["February","Patriots' Day; Valentine Ball with the Chapter Sweetheart election; Father-Son banquet"],["March","DeMolay Week (the week March 18 falls in); Devotional Day; Founders Class initiation"],["April","Teenage safety awareness campaign; fundraising sales; plans for a prospect party"],["May","Parents' Day; prospect event; summer sports get rolling"],["June","Outdoor Initiation; officer Installation; practice for Conclave competitions"],["July","My Government Day; a 2-3 day road trip; barbecue with prospects invited"],["August","Jurisdictional Conclave; final push for applications for the September initiation"],["September","Initiation; Educational Day; canned food drive at every meeting until Thanksgiving"],["October","Frank S. Land Day plans; Halloween party; RD Forms to all eligible Members"],["November","Frank S. Land Memorial Day (November 8th); food baskets for needy families; Christmas tree orders"],["December","Day of Comfort; Initiation to close out the yearly membership goal; make sure every new Member is reported on eScribe"]]},{"t":"h","text":"The Scribe's Calendar"},{"t":"p","text":"The Scribe (the Chapter's secretary) keeps the administrative machine running all year. Every month he completes the monthly financial reports, plus a set of fixed milestones:"},{"t":"list","items":["January: complete the yearly financial report and the **Annual Report**, print Senior DeMolay Certificates for Members turning 21 that year, and notify the Advisory Council of the Chapter's membership standing.","Send the notices for each Obligatory Day in its month: Patriots' Day in February, Devotional Day in March, Parents' Day in May, My Government Day in July, Educational Day in September, Frank S. Land Memorial Day in October, and Day of Comfort in November.","April and May: remind the Treasurer about the **IRS 990** and complete the IRS Form 990 (United States Chapters).","October: check and order Merit Bars, the Blue Honor Key, the White Honor Key, and Scribe's Efficiency Certificates.","November: restock forms and supplies: applications for membership, transfer certificates, obligation cards, receipts, and checks.","December: complete the inventory of Chapter property to submit to the Advisory Council."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"When you retire as Scribe, hand the new Scribe a copy of the calendar and all forms received from DeMolay International. Administrative continuity is part of the plan too."}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"Who makes up the Program Planning Committee?","options":["The three Councilors and the Scribe","The full Advisory Council plus the Master Councilor","Master Councilor, Senior Councilor, Junior Councilor, and Chapter Advisor","The Master Councilor and the special committee chairmen"],"correct":2,"explain":"The three Councilors will live with the program they adopt, and the Chapter Advisor brings experience and serves as liaison with the Advisory Council."},{"q":"By what date should next year's program be ready?","options":["By the first of December","By the first of January","Before the officer Installation","Before March 18th"],"correct":0,"explain":"The Handbook sets the first of December as the point when a successful Chapter finalizes and polishes next year's program."},{"q":"What are the three types of committee reports in term planning?","options":["Initial, Monthly, and Annual","Progress, Final, and Post","Draft, Review, and Approval","Budget, Program, and Evaluation"],"correct":1,"explain":"Progress reports at the meetings in advance, the Final report at the meeting just before the event, and the Post report for evaluation, accounting, and feedback."},{"q":"In the sample budget, out of each candidate's $60 fee, how much goes to the ISC fee via eScribe?","options":["$20","$30","$60","$35"],"correct":3,"explain":"Each $60 splits into $35 for the ISC fee, $20 deposited in the Trust Account for Life Fees, and the remainder goes to the Current Operating Account."},{"q":"When is Devotional Day observed, and who usually runs it?","options":["During the week that includes March 18th; the Chaplain","The first Sunday of March; the Orator","The week of November 8th; the Almoner","In September; the Stewards"],"correct":0,"explain":"The Chapter attends a place of worship as a group during the week of March 18th, with the Chaplain in charge of the arrangements."},{"q":"Between which dates must the Day of Comfort be held?","options":["Between May 1st and June 21st","November 1st through 30th","Between November 15th and December 31st","Any day in December"],"correct":2,"explain":"That is the Handbook's fixed window; the Almoner plans it, and the duty is to visit and comfort the sick."},{"q":"According to the 5 steps for organizing a project, what is step one?","options":["Appoint the committee and its chairman","Get general support from the membership","Build the event budget","Mail the invitations early"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Chapter must approve the idea in principle first; otherwise the support you need later will not be forthcoming."},{"q":"How far in advance should each term's detailed program be developed?","options":["One week before the Installation","Six months ahead","During the term's first meeting","At least two months before the term begins"],"correct":3,"explain":"The Handbook calls for a detailed term program at least two months before the term starts, worked out one sheet per month."}]},"actividades":{"title":"Activities: The Engine of Your Chapter","subtitle":"How to plan civic, social, athletic, and fundraising activities that keep your Chapter alive.","minutes":12,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"A Living Chapter Is Measured by Its Activities","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Activities are the sustaining life of any Chapter. Bored members drop out as fast as new ones come in, and the only way to stop that leak is to offer **something that hooks every member**. But watch out: a hundred mediocre activities are worthless. Quality beats quantity."},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook gives two requirements for any activity to succeed: first, make reasonably sure there are **enough interested members** (just ask at a meeting or run a questionnaire); second, have it **well organized and planned**. The smart move is a permanent committee for each major activity category, with an Advisor assigned to assist each committee."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Civic","text":"Community service: the biggest builder of public goodwill."},{"title":"Fund-Raising","text":"Raising the money your Chapter runs on."},{"title":"Social","text":"Dances, parties, and outings that make belonging fun."},{"title":"Athletic","text":"A year-round sports program."},{"title":"Obligatory Days","text":"The required observances on the DeMolay calendar."},{"title":"Others","text":"Music, drama, publications, public ceremonies, gaming, and more."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Minimum standard: a Chapter is not living up to its obligations unless it holds **at least 3 activities in each category per term** and observes **every Obligatory Day** throughout the year."},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook's ideas are suggestions, not a closed list: your members' interests, finances, available facilities, and local circumstances decide which activities make the cut."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Civic Activities: Your Chapter's Public Face","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Civic activities are any project of service to the community, state or province, nation, or a charitable cause. They are **your most important activities for creating goodwill**: people judge an organization by its deeds, and a dance or a ballgame won't change a neighbor's life — but a Chapter that serves its community will."},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook lists **21 civic activity ideas**. Some of the strongest:"},{"t":"list","items":["Sponsor a blood donor program.","Build or help maintain a public playground (repair, paint, clean up).","Plant trees in parks, school playgrounds, or other public lands.","Take down campaign posters after an election.","Give baskets of food and presents to needy families (Thanksgiving, Christmas, Easter).","Volunteer with the Red Cross in times of disaster, or at a Special Olympics event.","Purchase a needed piece of equipment for a local hospital or school."]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Helping with charity drives is the most frequent civic activity Chapters take on. It pays to adopt set causes and help them every year — it becomes a tradition the community recognizes."},{"t":"p","text":"Whatever you pick, **diversify** your civic activities and spread them out across the whole year."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full list of 21 civic activities","page":"98"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Fundraising: Money to Keep the Chapter Running","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Practically every Chapter depends on a number of fundraising activities each year. Success comes down to two ingredients: **proper planning and adequate publicity**. The only limit is your Chapter's imagination — plus state, province, and local law and Masonic rules, which no project may conflict with."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Rule from the Bylaws of DeMolay International: before **soliciting funds from anyone outside the Chapter's membership**, you must obtain the permission of the **Executive Officer** of the Jurisdiction."},{"t":"list","items":["Pick an activity that fits the season of the year.","Make sure it doesn't conflict with any other important event.","Allow plenty of time to publicize: **a minimum of one month** in all cases.","Inject novelty — it sets your event apart from similar competing activities.","Use every available channel: local newspapers, radio, DeMolay publications, flyers, posters.","Make sure every member knows the event's purpose and is spreading the word; tell other Chapters and family too."]},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook suggests more than two dozen ideas: candy and nut sales, Christmas trees and decorations, calendars, carwashes, auctions, rummage sales, a talent show, novelty dinners and pancake breakfasts, a booth at the county fair, a Back to School Dance with admission, and more."},{"t":"p","text":"Special mention for **Restaurant Take-Overs**: the Chapter serves and clears tables at a local restaurant and collects a percentage of the day's sales. No cash outlay, no risk, excellent publicity — and with matching shirts bearing the DeMolay emblem, the group becomes a walking billboard for the Order."},{"t":"p","text":"When a fundraiser proves very successful, **keep it on an annual basis**: profitable traditions are worth protecting."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Social Activities: Dances, Parties, and the Golden Rule","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Being social is part of DeMolay's DNA — bringing young people together is one of the things we do best. If the Masonic family youth groups and friends in your community look forward to your Chapter's events, that energy also keeps your own DeMolays active."},{"t":"p","text":"**Dances** are the most common social event, so make them unique with a theme: the **Food Dance** (every attendee brings a food item for baskets for needy families), the **Pigskin Prom** during football season, a Halloween costume dance, or variants like the Hobo Hop and Hard Times. Avoid expensive favors and decorations except on very special occasions."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Golden rule: possessing or using **alcohol before, during, or after** a dance — or any DeMolay activity — means **immediate expulsion from the event** and later consideration as un-DeMolay conduct."},{"t":"p","text":"Parties come in every flavor: the **Backwards Party** (everything reversed, invitations included), the **Progressive Games Party** (games run from easy to hard until one winner remains), **White Elephant**, theater outings, skating, beach parties — plus father-and-son events with bowling, ping pong, or softball between dad-and-son teams. Other popular picks: ski trips, treasure hunts, barbecues, hayrides, laser tag."},{"t":"p","text":"Surveys of young men show **outdoor activities are the most popular type**, with swimming, camping, baseball, and basketball as favorites. Keep your list updated with what your members ask for in the Members Interest Surveys."}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Athletics: A Year-Round Program and Signed Paperwork","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A Chapter needs an athletic program that runs **all year round**. And pay attention to members who claim no interest in sports: often they simply never had a place to learn, and the Chapter can be their first team in an atmosphere that supports instead of demands. Sports teach cooperation, patience, and how to work with other people."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Mandatory requirement: the Chapter must collect from each member participating in athletic events a signed **medical release** and **liability waiver**, also signed by **parents or guardian** (all active members are under 21), unless the Executive Officer of your Jurisdiction has additional policies."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Eligibility","text":"DeMolay in good standing, physically capable; check whether being on a school team in that sport matters."},{"title":"Facilities","text":"Options, cost, availability, and traveling distance."},{"title":"Equipment","text":"Who furnishes it (member or Chapter) and making sure it's adequate for safety."},{"title":"Officiating","text":"Enough officials (Advisors, parents, local coaches) well versed in the proper rules."},{"title":"Scheduling","text":"Convenient time and place, notifying everyone, bad-weather backup plans, travel arrangements."},{"title":"Awards","text":"Suitable recognition for winners (trophies or prizes) and the financing for it."}]},{"t":"p","text":"There are over 30 possible sports, from basketball and soccer to corn hole, archery, and frisbee. Competitions can run within the Chapter, against other Chapters, or at the Jurisdictional level. Two limits always apply: observe **state and local academic rules** so no member's scholastic athletic standing is endangered, and keep **sportsmanship** second to none in every sport."},{"t":"ref","text":"The six athletic planning categories in detail","page":"102"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Other Activities and Career Guidance","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The \"Others\" category covers everything outside regular meetings: a **choir or quartet** for installations, hospitals, and holiday programs; an orchestra or dance combo for Chapter dances; a **Drama Club** with skits and plays for entertainment or fundraising; and **speech groups** for public speaking and debate."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Every Chapter publication (newsletter, website, social media, email) must carry the official allegiance statement: \"This publication acknowledges authority and yields allegiance to DeMolay International, of which Frank S. Land was Founder.\""},{"t":"list","items":["**Newsletter/website/social media:** informing members is the primary purpose; be accurate, easy to access, cover every phase of Chapter activity, and get a copy to every member and Advisor. Put your writers and cartoonists to work.","**Summer camp:** if you have access to a camp, plan an outing every summer, with unique outdoor degrees by campfire or lantern. Always on a **cost basis only** — never for profit.","**Senior DeMolay Night:** a tribute to your alumni, planned **at least six months ahead**. Track down Senior DeMolays through every possible source, prepare your Chapter's history, and recognize any \"50-year DeMolay\" with a pin from the DeMolay Service & Leadership Center.","**Chapter Anniversary:** every anniversary deserves a special observance; it can be combined with Senior DeMolay Night, the Awards Ceremony, or the Installation of Officers."]},{"t":"p","text":"**Career Guidance** is not a fill-in program: the question \"what am I going to do with my life?\" matters to everyone. Survey your Chapter's interests, pick a member to represent Career Guidance on the Program Committee, and have the Advisory Council and Officers organize a **Career Education Committee** of community adults to line up speakers and field trips."},{"t":"p","text":"Vary the format: a speaker who can sell their profession with zeal (not necessarily the most successful person — check their speaking ability first), a video, a field trip to an industrial plant or hospital, round-table discussions after meetings. And since not everyone will go to college, give proportionate emphasis to **trades, apprenticeships, and night school programs**."}]},{"id":"l7","title":"Philanthropy: Fundraising with Purpose","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Before you raise a dollar, define **what it's for**. There are two big purposes: raising funds so the Chapter can operate (rent, events, pizza at the prospect party) and raising funds to help others. If the Chapter is engaged with the purpose, members, parents, and Advisors will jump in on their own."},{"t":"table","headers":["Charity","Philanthropy"],"rows":[["Relieves the pain of a specific problem","Works at the root of the issue to solve it"],["Working at a food bank, donating to a shelter","Building with Habitat for Humanity"],["Clothing for a family whose home burned","Funding a community vegetable garden in an impoverished neighborhood"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"\"Brotherhood begins after the bills are paid.\" Your Chapter cannot survive without funding, and learning to meet financial commitments is a life lesson DeMolay helps you build."},{"t":"steps","items":["Define the why of your event: pay bills, help others, have fun, meet people. There's always one primary reason.","Verify that the organization you want to help is a **nonprofit, tax-deductible cause** (if you don't know, ask for their tax status; outside the US, learn their mission).","Set a concrete goal: \"we're going to raise $10,000\" inspires far more than \"a bunch of money.\" Set a term goal, a goal per event, and maybe a multi-year goal.","For a small $500 to $1,000 event you might get away with improvising, but for a large event start planning **at least six months out** — a full year of lead time is even better.","Cover the critical components: who, what, when, where, why, how; promotion/PR; registration; and budgeting (yes, plan to make money!)."]},{"t":"p","text":"Don't underestimate **direct mail**: a personal letter asking for support still works. Expect about **5-10%** of recipients to donate. Your \"case for support\" should say why the cause matters to you, tell a real personal story, and make clear where to send the funds. Even $1 counts: if a stamp costs $.55, you've already doubled your investment."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Key tax fact: donors giving **more than $25 in a single contribution** to a tax-exempt nonprofit need a written **acknowledgment letter** (the donation \"receipt\") to claim the deduction on their income tax return. Say thank you, say it often, and say it with meaning."},{"t":"p","text":"After the event: take pictures, share the results, document what worked and what didn't for next year's team — and **celebrate** with a wrap party. Celebrating small wins builds Chapter morale."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full Philanthropy guide","page":"115"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"What is the minimum activity standard the Handbook sets for a Chapter?","options":["1 activity per category per term","3 activities in each category per term, plus observing every Obligatory Day","5 activities total per year","3 activities per year, in any category"],"correct":1,"explain":"A Chapter is not living up to its obligations unless it holds at least 3 activities in each category during a term and observes every Obligatory Day throughout the year."},{"q":"According to the Handbook, which activity category is the most important for creating goodwill and favorable public relations?","options":["Fundraising","Social","Civic","Athletic"],"correct":2,"explain":"People judge an organization by its deeds: community service is what most shapes public opinion of DeMolay."},{"q":"What does a Chapter need before soliciting funds from anyone outside its membership?","options":["A unanimous Chapter vote","Permission from the Executive Officer of the Jurisdiction","A signed note from the Master Councilor","Nothing, as long as the money goes to charity"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Bylaws of DeMolay International require the Executive Officer's permission before any solicitation of funds outside the Chapter's membership."},{"q":"A member shows up with alcohol at a Chapter dance. What does the Handbook call for?","options":["A verbal warning on the record","Asking him to leave it outside and stay at the event","Immediate expulsion from the event and later consideration as un-DeMolay conduct","An automatic one-year suspension"],"correct":2,"explain":"Possessing or using alcohol before, during, or after any DeMolay activity requires immediate expulsion from the event, with later consideration as un-DeMolay conduct."},{"q":"What signed documents must every member participating in Chapter athletic events turn in?","options":["Just verbal permission from his parents","A medical release and liability waiver, also signed by parents or guardian","His obligation card","A medical certificate from his school"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Chapter must collect a signed medical release and liability waiver from each participant; since all actives are under 21, parents or guardian must also sign."},{"q":"What must every Chapter publication (newsletter, website, social media, email) include?","options":["The term budget","The allegiance statement to DeMolay International","The full membership roster","The Executive Officer's signature"],"correct":1,"explain":"Every publication must carry the allegiance statement acknowledging the authority of DeMolay International, of which Frank S. Land was Founder."},{"q":"Above what amount does a donor need a written acknowledgment letter to claim a tax deduction?","options":["More than $10","More than $25 in a single contribution","More than $100","Any amount, no minimum"],"correct":1,"explain":"Donations of more than $25 in a single contribution to a tax-exempt nonprofit require a written acknowledgment for the donor to claim the deduction."},{"q":"What is the difference between charity and philanthropy according to the Handbook?","options":["They are exact synonyms","Charity relieves the pain of a specific problem; philanthropy works at the root to solve it","Charity means donating money; philanthropy means only volunteering time","Philanthropy is reserved for large organizations"],"correct":1,"explain":"Charity aims to relieve a particular problem (like working at a food bank); philanthropy takes private initiatives for the public good and targets the root of the issue."}]},"reclutamiento":{"title":"Recruitment: Grow Your Chapter or Watch It Fade","subtitle":"How to find candidates, run a Friendship Night that actually works, and close the deal so no eligible young man is left out for lack of an invitation.","minutes":11,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Why Recruiting Is Not Optional","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Nobody stays in DeMolay forever. Active membership lasts **9 years** at most, but in practice the average is **3 to 4 years**: a guy who joins at 14 graduates high school at 18 and, between college and work, is no longer around for the Chapter."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Plan on the assumption that **practically the entire Chapter membership turns over every 3 years**. If you are not recruiting today, there is no Chapter in three years."},{"t":"p","text":"That is why, beyond living the teachings of DeMolay, every member takes on a concrete pledge: bring in a **minimum of 2 new members per year**. One replaces your own departure (which comes sooner or later), and the other makes the Chapter grow. Just replacing losses is not enough — to grow, you have to offer the opportunity to every eligible young man in your community."},{"t":"list","items":["**Who can join:** any young man past his **12th birthday** who has not yet reached his **21st**, of good moral character, recommended by an active DeMolay, a Senior DeMolay, or a Master Mason.","Membership is **NOT** limited to the sons or relatives of Masons.","The Membership Application is filled out online, includes the consent of parents or guardians, and requires the recommendation of at least one Chapter member, Senior DeMolay, or Master Mason."]},{"t":"p","text":"This is not hit-and-miss work: the **Membership Committee** is one of the standing committees that the Rules & Regulations of DeMolay International require of every Chapter. And there is one simple measure of success: no eligible young man in your area should ever be able to answer \"no one asked me\" when asked why he is not a DeMolay."},{"t":"ref","text":"The foundations of Chapter growth, in detail","page":"6"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Where the Candidates Are (and How Many)","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Recruiting by guesswork does not work. Step one is building, systematically, a list of **every** eligible young man in your area. These are the sources the Handbook recommends working:"},{"t":"list","items":["Middle and senior high school principals (including charter schools) and school yearbooks","Church Youth Directors and Sunday School officials and teachers","Master Masons and secretaries of local Masonic bodies (they can review their membership rolls for members with DeMolay-age sons)","Scoutmasters, YMCA secretaries and youth directors, directors of boys' clubs","Squires Manor: Squires who age out should naturally progress into DeMolay… but it still takes someone to ask them","New members (right after joining, have them write down all their eligible friends), older members, Senior DeMolays, parents, and word of mouth"]},{"t":"p","text":"Three tricks with exact numbers: every time the Chapter exemplifies a Degree, ask each Mason present to write down a **minimum of 2 names** with contact info; Chapter Advisors can repeat that request **every 6 months** in their Masonic organizations; and **every 3 or 4 months**, at a Chapter meeting, have everyone write down a potential member list. Do not skip **10- and 11-year-olds**: note them as future Squires or to contact when they turn 12."},{"t":"h","text":"Doing the Pool Math"},{"t":"p","text":"\"DeMolay isn't for everyone\"? Run the Handbook's numbers: an average public school of **500** students → half are guys: **250** → cut the half who won't fit (sports, jobs, just not a match): **125** → cut that in half one more time, just for the heck of it: **62.5**. You are left with **62 guys to talk to about DeMolay in a single school**. If 10% show up, that is 6.2 people at your event; even at 5%, it is 3.1 potential new members."},{"t":"p","text":"Now take out your phone. Write down **every** non-DeMolay guy aged **10 to 20** in your contacts — not just the ones you think might join. All of them. As Wayne Gretzky put it, quoted in the Handbook itself: \"You miss 100% of the shots you never take.\" If you never ask, the answer is already no."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Expect a lot of no's — that is fine, it is part of the process. Every no gets you closer to the next yes."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Friendship Night: The Method That Works","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Call it **Friendship Night**, Get Acquainted Night, Guys Night Out, or Game Night — the potential member event remains **the most effective way for DeMolay to gain new members**. It gets the whole Chapter working toward a common goal and concentrates your recruiting energy into set dates, leaving time for the rest of your program."},{"t":"p","text":"The membership program is outlined a year ahead, with specific dates scheduled for each class of new members: **a minimum of 2 months between classes and a maximum of 3 or 4**. That rhythm leaves enough time to develop the class and vote on the applications without letting the campaign drag and the candidates lose enthusiasm."},{"t":"h","text":"Two Months Out"},{"t":"steps","items":["Hold a Membership Committee meeting **about 2 months before** the event date.","Decide where and when the event will be held.","Plan the advance publicity.","Agree on the method for securing names of potential members and friends.","Plan the event program, including sending the invitations.","Download the \"Open House\" PowerPoint presentation from the DeMolay International website and fill in your Chapter's specifics."]},{"t":"p","text":"Invitations go out **2 weeks before** the event, ideally with a DeMolay International promotional pamphlet enclosed. A few days later, call: did he get the invitation? Is he coming? Does he need a ride? If parents will attend, prepare a similar letter for them."},{"t":"h","text":"On the Day of the Event"},{"t":"p","text":"V.I.P. treatment from start to finish: a member greets each guest at the door and serves as his host for the night, name tags for every guest, a quick tour, introductions to members and Advisors, and food if at all possible. After the welcome, split the group: **parents move to another room for their own program**, because what they need to hear is not the same as what interests the guys."},{"t":"table","headers":["For the Parents","For the Candidates"],"rows":[["DeMolay's value to them and their sons","How to join, step by step"],["The ideals and purposes of the Order","Friends, food, and fun — what DeMolay offers"],["The Chapter's programs, the cost to join, and scholarships","Chapter activities that match their interests"],["Youth protection and answers to all their questions","Filling out the Membership Application right there"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**DO NOT invite a candidate to a stated meeting** (the formal business meeting) as his first DeMolay experience. Show him DeMolay is fun first. The Handbook says it twice because it matters that much."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full step-by-step for the Membership Event","page":"10"}]},{"id":"l4","title":"The Model Letters and the 3-5 Day Visit","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook includes two model letters. The **letter to the candidate** invites him to the event with date, time, and place, tells him that **a Chapter member personally recommended him**, mentions the sponsoring body (the Masonic institution backing the Chapter) and the social, athletic, and service activities. It carries RSVP details and the signatures of the **Master Councilor** (the Chapter's elected youth leader) and the **Membership Chairman**."},{"t":"p","text":"The **letter to the parents** is signed by the **Chapter Advisor**. It speaks of the three fundamental freedoms DeMolay defends — **Religion** (the Holy Book of their choice), **Civil** (their National Flag), and **Intellectual** (Scholar Books) — and explains the cost of **lifetime membership**: paid once, with no other dues ever collected. One caution: on its own it is a soft sell; it works far better alongside personal contact and followed by a phone call. Also, after the initial call to the candidate, have an Advisor call his parents with informational material."},{"t":"h","text":"The Follow-Up That Closes"},{"t":"p","text":"Whether he signed up at the event or not, every candidate fills out an **information card**: name, address, age, telephone number, email, and a space for special remarks. That card is your guide for the follow-up."},{"t":"steps","items":["Review the information card and anything the Chapter picked up during his visit.","Within **3 to 5 days** after the event, visit him at his home.","Go in **teams of 2** — be courteous and dress neatly.","Bring Membership Applications and materials: brochures, the term plan (the term's activity calendar), the Chapter phone list, and anything else that helps encourage him to join."]},{"t":"p","text":"Another proven route is the **appreciation class**: a special membership class honoring Masonry or a Masonic leader (the head of the Sponsoring Body, the Grand Master of the Grand Lodge), with a realistic numeric goal and team competition with tangible prizes for the best application-getters. Those who did not apply go on a follow-up list to contact again in the future — today's name can be next year's member."}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Your Elevator Pitch and the Five Fs","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Someone sees your shirt and asks, \"what is Deemolly?\" If you launch into the textbook definition — \"a leadership and character-building organization for young men…\" — you lost him. Your **elevator pitch** lasts as long as a short elevator ride: **20 to 30 seconds**. Tell a true, fun story about your Chapter: \"DeMolay is where a group of friends gets together and hosts events like…\" Because everyone tunes in to the same radio station: **WIIFM** (What's In It For Me). Everything else is filtered out as noise."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"If you get even a slight nod of interest, **get his contact info before he steps off the elevator**. And when you invite him, be specific: day, time, and place. Never for today or within the hour — give him time to get a parent's permission. Remind him a few days out and offer a ride."},{"t":"h","text":"The Five Fs of Conversation"},{"t":"p","text":"Talking to someone you just met is not easy. Start by sticking your hand out and saying your name: 99% of the time he will shake it and say his. **Remember his name and repeat it back** in conversation (\"You know, Jack, I like that too\"). Then work through the five Fs:"},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"From","text":"Everyone is from somewhere and has a story about their hometown. Don't stop at \"oh, cool\" — ask and follow up."},{"title":"Favorites","text":"This topic can run for hours. Pizza at the bowling alley? Ask his favorite pizza, favorite toppings, and why."},{"title":"Friends/Family","text":"Family is familiar ground: how many siblings, where do they go to school, are they into sports? And again — follow up."},{"title":"Firsts","text":"Use the scene you're in: \"When was the first time you went bowling?\" \"Do you remember your first strike?\""},{"title":"Fun","text":"The golden closer: \"So, what do you do for fun?\" It opens up movies, games, interests and more. Roll with it and have fun yourself."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Never ask about \"firsts\" that are not relevant to the conversation or the social situation you are in. It lands terribly."},{"t":"p","text":"These are conversation starters, not the whole conversation — the goal is to get him comfortable talking. And they work with anyone: candidates, parents, guests, or future volunteers."},{"t":"ref","text":"Member Recruitment: pitch, pool, and Five Fs","page":"80"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Ask Him to Join (and Don't Drop Him After)","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"You got him to the event, and he is having a great time with your group. Now what? **Close the deal: ask him to join.** If you don't ask the question, you never get an answer. To gauge where he stands, use open-ended trial closing questions: \"How do you feel about that?\" \"What are your thoughts at this point?\""},{"t":"list","items":["**He asks you directly** → ask him to join.","**He asks what membership costs** → ask him to join.","**He wants more information** → ask him to join.","**He genuinely shows interest in the program** → ask him to join."]},{"t":"p","text":"When he says yes, the **most important stage begins: follow up, follow up, follow up**. Once his Membership Application is submitted, track it closely — months must not go by without the interview or the vote. If the process drags, keep him in the loop: that is what keeps him interested. And remind him of his **Initiatory Degree** (his initiation ceremony) weeks and days ahead, offer a ride… just do not forget about him!"},{"t":"h","text":"The Membership Checklist"},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook provides a complete checklist so nothing is left to chance:"},{"t":"table","headers":["Area","What You Make Sure Of"],"rows":[["Organization","Review the Membership chapter in the DeMolay Handbook, meet with the Membership Committee (if it is not active, check with the Chapter Advisor and Master Councilor about reactivating it), and inventory supplies: applications, brochures, marketing materials."],["The Event","A specific new-member goal, invitation letters to as many potential members as possible with a follow-up schedule (the second contact should be personal), a step-by-step event schedule, and a post-event evaluation session to improve the next one."],["After the Event","Contact within a few days everyone who did not complete an application, present all applications promptly and properly, and plan the Induction Ceremony with as little delay as possible to keep interest high."],["Orientation & Always","A solid New Member Orientation Program (vital to quality membership), making sure everyone knows the available Membership Awards and incentives, and staying membership-conscious all year long."]]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The checklist closes with two words in capital letters: **BE ENTHUSIASTIC!** Your Chapter's enthusiasm is the best sales pitch there is."},{"t":"ref","text":"The complete Membership Checklist","page":"22"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"According to the Handbook, how often does practically the entire Chapter membership turn over?","options":["Every year","Every 3 years","Every 5 years","Every 9 years"],"correct":1,"explain":"Nine years is the individual maximum, but the average member who joins at 14 stays active 3-4 years, so the whole Chapter turns over in about 3 years."},{"q":"What recruiting pledge does every DeMolay member take on?","options":["Bring in 1 new member per year","Bring in a minimum of 2 new members per year","Bring in 3 new members before leaving","Bring in 5 new members over his whole membership"],"correct":1,"explain":"A minimum of 2 per year: one to replace his own eventual departure, and one to make the Chapter grow."},{"q":"How far in advance should the Membership Committee meet to plan the Membership Event?","options":["1 week before","2 weeks before","1 month before","2 months before"],"correct":3,"explain":"The planning meeting happens about 2 months out: that is where venue, date, publicity, the method for gathering names, and the program get set."},{"q":"When should the invitations to the potential member event be sent?","options":["2 days before","1 week before","2 weeks before","1 month before"],"correct":2,"explain":"Invitations go out 2 weeks in advance of the event, with a promotional pamphlet, and are confirmed with a phone call a few days later."},{"q":"What does the follow-up visit after the Membership Event look like?","options":["Within 24 hours, one member alone","Within 3-5 days, in teams of 2","Within 2 weeks, in teams of 3","Within a month, with the whole Chapter"],"correct":1,"explain":"If possible, within 3-5 days after the event you visit him at home, in teams of 2, neatly dressed, carrying applications and materials."},{"q":"How long should your DeMolay elevator pitch last?","options":["5 to 10 seconds","20 to 30 seconds","Exactly 1 minute","2 to 3 minutes"],"correct":1,"explain":"As long as a short elevator ride: 20 to 30 seconds, telling a fun, true story — not a textbook definition."},{"q":"In the Handbook's pool exercise, a school of 500 students leaves you roughly how many candidates to talk to?","options":["25","62","125","250"],"correct":1,"explain":"500 → 250 guys → 125 after the first cut → 62.5 after halving once more: about 62 candidates in a single school."},{"q":"Which of these is NOT one of the Five Fs of Conversation?","options":["From","Favorites","Future","Firsts"],"correct":2,"explain":"The Five Fs are From, Favorites, Friends/Family, Firsts, and Fun. \"Future\" is not on the list."}]},"imagen":{"title":"Public Image: Get Everyone Talking (Well) About Your Chapter","subtitle":"Public relations, press coverage, and Celebrate DeMolay Week — how to show your Chapter to the world.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Everything You Do Speaks for DeMolay","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Public relations isn't just sending out press releases. The Handbook defines it as the art of creating a **favorable impression** of a group or idea in the public's mind. Here's the catch: **everything you do as a DeMolay**, wherever you are, either builds up or tears down the image of your Chapter and of DeMolay as a whole."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"One bad act can cancel out as many as **ten good deeds**. It's human nature: people remember the one bad thing over all the good ones. Living the DeMolay teachings every day is your first public relations job."},{"t":"p","text":"Every Chapter activity, from a business meeting to a game night, is part of your PR effort. The Handbook's strategy: break the public down into **four segments** and work each one with its own playbook."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Youth","text":"Young men of DeMolay age (9 to 21): your future members."},{"title":"Parents","text":"Of current and potential members: their support opens doors."},{"title":"Masons","text":"Without their sponsorship, your Chapter might not exist."},{"title":"General public","text":"The whole community: the largest segment of all."}]},{"t":"ref","text":"The full Public Relations section starts on","page":"149"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"The Four Publics, One by One","blocks":[{"t":"h","text":"Youth: the best salesman is you"},{"t":"p","text":"The individual member is DeMolay's best salesman to other young people, especially if he's seen as a leader at school. Host a **buddy night** (a special meeting for potential new members), invite non-DeMolays to social events and every public ceremony, wear your DeMolay pin and gear as often as you can, and bring your friends along to Chapter activities."},{"t":"h","text":"Parents: the team you need"},{"t":"p","text":"Keep them fully informed and invite them to every public event. The Handbook puts it plainly: nothing sells mothers on DeMolay like the **Flower Talk**, the public ceremony honoring mothers — one performance and they're firmly behind the Chapter. Add father-son and mother-son breakfasts, family potlucks, Certificates of Appreciation, and official thank-yous when they help out."},{"t":"h","text":"Masons: your sponsors"},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"DeMolay is **NOT a junior Masonic organization**. It is Masonic inspired, with close ties to Masonry but an identity of its own. Keep that crystal clear whenever you talk to the press or the public."},{"t":"p","text":"Without the **Sponsoring Body** (the Masonic group that sponsors your Chapter), your Chapter might not exist. Show your appreciation: a membership class named for the Grand Master or the Sponsoring Body's presiding officer, a Masonic Night featuring a Degree or public ceremony, joint church services, ushering at Masonic functions, and flawless behavior inside the Masonic building."},{"t":"h","text":"The general public: the biggest audience"},{"t":"p","text":"The formula has two steps: **(1)** do things that prove the value of having a DeMolay Chapter in town, and **(2)** make sure people actually hear about them. A DeMolay Day at the fair, a float in the parade, safety programs with the police or fire department, litter bags printed with the Chapter's name, and a fresh public social media presence showcasing the Chapter's good works. Selling DeMolay is a week-in, week-out, year-round job."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Getting Publicity: Think Like an Editor","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"News media run **news** only: the unusual happening to ordinary people, or the ordinary happening to unusual people. Working in your favor: the smaller the community, the better your odds of getting published."},{"t":"list","items":["Get to know your local news editors in person, including online blogs and community TV stations.","When you can, hand the story over personally: a well-prepared piece and **one great quality picture**. Don't overstay — editors are busy.","Notice which kinds of DeMolay stories they never run, and stop flooding them with those.","Learn each outlet's deadlines and deliver releases as far in advance as possible."]},{"t":"steps","items":["Submit the article **by email**, identifying the source: name, email, and cell number of whoever prepared it.","At the top, state when to run it: for immediate release, or with an exact date and time.","Pack the essentials into the first paragraph: **who, what, when, where, why, and how** (the 5 W's + H).","Double-check the spelling of every proper name and address. You can add Names and addresses verified in the upper left corner — it impresses editors.","Check every figure, run spell check, and have someone else proofread it.","Go easy on adjectives and never stretch a story: stick to the simple facts.","Keep paragraphs short and newsy; never run a paragraph over to a second page.","Skip the insider jargon: some readers have never heard of DeMolay before."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Golden writing rule: sentences should **not average over 15 words**. The first sentence of a story is usually the longest."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full writing rules and the 6 points for every story on","page":"154"}]},{"id":"l4","title":"The 6 Facts Every Story Must Carry","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook asks you to work these six points into **every story** about DeMolay, usually in the closing paragraphs. Why? Because repetition stamps them into the general public's mind."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"1. Founding","text":"DeMolay was founded in Kansas City, Missouri, in 1919."},{"title":"2. Goal","text":"Its goal is \"Building Better Citizens and Young Men of Character\"."},{"title":"3. Reach","text":"There are over 3 million DeMolays (active and alumni), with Chapters in 26 countries and four independent territories."},{"title":"4. Membership","text":"Open to young men 9 to 21, of all races, creeds, and faiths."},{"title":"5. Values","text":"DeMolay teaches its core values: love of parents, reverence, courtesy, comradeship, fidelity, cleanness, and patriotism."},{"title":"6. Leadership","text":"DeMolay prepares youth for leadership in industry, government, the military, business, and the professions. Senior DeMolays leading in those fields prove it."}]},{"t":"h","text":"What counts as news?"},{"t":"list","items":["Special meetings: public Installation of Officers, Chevalier and Legion of Honor Investitures, award presentations, Majority Service.","Social and athletic events: dances, banquets, competitions in any sport.","Community service projects: charity drives, civic clean-ups, safety programs.","Money-raising projects, especially the unusual ones.","District, Regional, or Jurisdictional events: conclaves, camps, competitions.","Even an editorial about DeMolay: talk to the editor and hand over the facts."]}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Photos, Release Models, and Timing","blocks":[{"t":"h","text":"Photos editors actually want"},{"t":"list","items":["More than three people: shoot against a dark or neutral background; head and shoulders if it's a portrait.","Two or three people in action: enough distance to show detail without cluttering the scene; side auxiliary light if possible.","A group of 3 to 5 (say, award winners): one person hands the award to another who looks at it, and everyone else watches that action. **Nobody stares into the camera.**","Always identify the people in the photo and describe the event."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"For anyone under 21, use **first names only** when naming people in stories and photos. Be generous with local names — editors love them — but stick to this rule."},{"t":"h","text":"The news release models"},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook includes ready-to-adapt models. The **election** release: who was elected Master Councilor (the Chapter's presiding officer), his school and activities, the list of other elected Officers, and a closing with DeMolay's history. The **social event** release: what's happening, when and where, how many new members the Chapter is gaining, and a quote from the Master Councilor. Follow the 5 W's + H and your story will usually be acceptable. And cover what's **going to happen**, not just what already did."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"When the event is over, **get the story out the same day** — or that same night. News is only news while it's fresh: 3 or 4 days later, it's dead. Doubly true for sports."},{"t":"p","text":"Don't pass up **feature stories** on the youth page, the society page, or the paper's magazine section. And if you're planning a big event and can't find enough help, ask your **Executive Officer**, the top DeMolay authority in your jurisdiction."}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Radio and TV: The Clock Rules","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A newspaper can add pages; radio and TV can't stretch airtime. That makes the competition for broadcast time **far more intense** than for newspaper space. Study your local stations: what kinds of stories they feature, how many facts fit into each one — then tailor-make your release to match."},{"t":"list","items":["A release for radio or TV should rarely fill more than **one side of an 8½ x 11 sheet**.","Go after interviews and shows that feature local organizations, like the classic Community Bulletin Board many stations run daily.","Many stations air brief editorials: DeMolay can be the subject, either as a worthwhile youth organization or for a specific project."]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Landed an on-air interview for your Chapter? Choose the people who will represent DeMolay very carefully — in that moment, they are the face of the whole organization."},{"t":"p","text":"The guidelines for preparing copy are the same as for newspapers, with one difference: **briefer**."}]},{"id":"l7","title":"Celebrate DeMolay Week (or Month)","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every year, Chapters worldwide celebrate DeMolay's founding during **the week when March 18th falls**, or throughout March. It's the PR opportunity of the year, and the goal is clear: aim your activities at people **outside** the organization. With every Chapter celebrating at once, the public impact multiplies."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Obtain an **official proclamation**: from the Mayor, the Chamber of Commerce President, or another high-ranking municipal official. At the Jurisdictional level, from the state's **governor** or equivalent."},{"t":"p","text":"The core idea: dedicate **one day (or stretch of the month) to each of the seven Cardinal Virtues**, with matching activities. And to make it visible at school, wear a DeMolay shirt several days that week."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Filial Love","text":"Tributes, outings, and dinners with parents; father-son tournaments."},{"title":"Reverence","text":"Attend church services as a group and help out as ushers or with the music."},{"title":"Courtesy","text":"Visits and donations to hospitals and nursing homes; benefit events; washing city vehicles and fire trucks."},{"title":"Comradeship","text":"Social and athletic events with other Chapters and youth groups; a large-scale dance."},{"title":"Fidelity","text":"A Founder's Day Class honoring Frank S. Land; tributes and recognition for Masonry."},{"title":"Cleanness","text":"Clean-living forums open to the public; cleaning the Masonic building and its grounds."},{"title":"Patriotism","text":"Honoring the flag, veterans, and schools; debates and oratorical contests on patriotic themes."}]},{"t":"steps","items":["Set up the committee structure: the **Executive Committee** (the three Councilors, the Chapter Advisor, and any special Advisors) sets overall policy; the **Operation Committee**, with the Master Councilor as general chairman, coordinates the chairmen of the special committees (Publicity, Church Services, Membership, Civic Projects, and more).","Contact every publicity outlet in advance and lay the groundwork before the first materials go out.","Order promotional supplies from **DeMolay International** well ahead of the dates you'll need them.","Keep every Chapter member fully informed, well in advance, and involve each one as much as possible."]},{"t":"table","headers":["Publicity action","Minimum lead time"],"rows":[["News release to the media","2 to 3 days before you want it to appear"],["Special feature in the Sunday supplement","6 weeks ahead, talking to the supplement's editor"],["Radio and TV spot announcements (10 to 30 seconds)","1 week ahead, to the program director, each on its own 8½ x 11 sheet"],["Store window display","1 month ahead, with the store manager"]]},{"t":"p","text":"The Handbook includes a **check-off list** so nothing slips: committees appointed, supplies ordered, one event assigned per day, and every publicity piece (videos, spots, billboards, posters, proclamation, website, and social media) with an owner and a date. When it's over, send **thank-you notes** to every person and organization that helped: it's good manners, and it keeps the door open for next year."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full Celebrate DeMolay section, with the model proclamation and check-off list, starting on","page":"157"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"According to the Handbook, which four segments should the Chapter break the public into for its public relations?","options":["Youth of DeMolay age, parents, Masons, and the general public","Schools, churches, service clubs, and the press","Members, Advisors, Senior DeMolays, and parents","Newspapers, radio, TV, and social media"],"correct":0,"explain":"The Handbook breaks the public into (1) youth of DeMolay age, (2) parents, (3) Masons, and (4) the general public of the community, each with its own tactics."},{"q":"How does the Handbook describe the relationship between DeMolay and Masonry?","options":["DeMolay is the official youth branch of Masonry","DeMolay is NOT a junior Masonic organization, though it is Masonic inspired","DeMolay has no connection to Masonry at all","DeMolay is a program run directly by the Grand Lodge"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Handbook states it outright: DeMolay is NOT a junior Masonic organization, but it has always been Masonic inspired and keeps a close tie with Masonry."},{"q":"What is the Handbook's rule on sentence length in a news release?","options":["No more than 10 words per sentence, no exceptions","No more than 20 words, headlines included","Sentences should not average over 15 words","There's no rule: it depends on each editor's style"],"correct":2,"explain":"Sentences must be short and to the point: they should not average over 15 words. The first sentence of a story is usually the longest."},{"q":"In a story or press photo, how do you identify a member who is under 21?","options":["With full name and address","With initials only","He can't be named at all","With his first name only"],"correct":3,"explain":"The Handbook says to be generous with names because editors love them — but for anyone under 21, use first names only."},{"q":"A Chapter event just ended. When do you deliver the story to the media?","options":["The same day, or that same night if possible","Within the next 3 or 4 days","The following week, once the photos are edited","Whenever the editor asks for it"],"correct":0,"explain":"News is only news while it's fresh: deliver it immediately, the same day or night. Waiting 3 or 4 days kills the story, especially for sports."},{"q":"According to the 6 facts every story must carry, where and when was DeMolay founded?","options":["In St. Louis, Missouri, in 1919","In Kansas City, Missouri, in 1919","In Kansas City, Missouri, in 1929","In Chicago, Illinois, in 1919"],"correct":1,"explain":"It's the first of the 6 facts to repeat in every story: DeMolay was founded in Kansas City, Missouri, in 1919."},{"q":"When is Celebrate DeMolay Week held?","options":["The week when June 24th falls","The first week of the school year","The week when March 18th falls (or throughout March, as a month)","The week of Frank S. Land's birthday"],"correct":2,"explain":"Chapters celebrate DeMolay's founding during the week when March 18th falls, or throughout March if the Chapter goes with the month format."},{"q":"Who should your Chapter ask for the Celebrate DeMolay proclamation at the local level?","options":["The Grand Master of the Grand Lodge","The jurisdiction's Executive Officer","The editor of the city's biggest newspaper","The Mayor, the Chamber of Commerce President, or another high-ranking municipal official"],"correct":3,"explain":"At the Chapter level, the proclamation comes from the Mayor or another high-ranking municipal official; at the Jurisdictional level, from the governor or equivalent."}]},"seguridad":{"title":"Protection and Safety: The Rules That Don't Bend","subtitle":"Youth Protection, insurance, risk management, and what to do when something goes wrong.","minutes":12,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Youth Protection: Priority Number One","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay exists so you can grow, lead, and have a great time — but none of that works unless the environment is **safe**. That's why Youth Protection is the strictest set of rules in the entire organization: no gray areas, no exceptions."},{"t":"p","text":"The approach is multi-layered: local selection of adult volunteers backed by DeMolay International, education and training, clear policies (no **one-on-one** activities between an adult and a youth), and immediate reporting of any concern."},{"t":"h","text":"The Scouting BSA Videos"},{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay partnered with **Scouting BSA** to provide two videos, each with a facilitator's guide. The first, \"It Happened to Me\", is for the Squires Program (ages 9 to 11) and teaches the **Four Rules of Personal Safety**. The second has two modules: \"A Time To Tell\" for audiences 14 and younger, and \"Personal Safety Awareness\" for ages 15 and up."},{"t":"list","items":["Four Rules of Personal Safety — 1) Check first with a parent or other trusted adult before changing plans, going anywhere, or accepting anything from anyone.","2) Go with a friend — it's safer and more fun.","3) My body is mine: I have the right to say no to anyone who tries to touch me in places covered by my swimsuit or do things I think are wrong.","4) Tell a trusted adult anytime I am hurt, scared, or made to feel uncomfortable."]},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Recognize","text":"Recognize situations that put youth at risk of abuse and how molesters operate — anyone could be one."},{"title":"Resist","text":"Resist unwanted and inappropriate attention. Resistance stops most attempts at molestation."},{"title":"Report","text":"Report attempted or actual abuse or inappropriate behavior to an Advisor, parent, or other trusted adult. That stops further abuse and protects other youth."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"The videos must be shown **at least twice per year** (the Squires video also at each induction of a new member). Every Chapter certifies compliance each year in its mandatory Annual Report to DeMolay International via eScribe."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Numbers That Are Non-Negotiable","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Three numeric rules hold up the entire supervision system. Learn them cold — you'll plan every event around them for your whole DeMolay career."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Two-Deep Leadership","text":"At least **2 registered Advisors** at ALL DeMolay trips, outings, and Chapter activities. Always. The presence of parents does not replace this requirement."},{"title":"Rule of Four","text":"Every DeMolay activity needs at least **4 individuals**, including at least **2 adults**. If someone gets hurt, one person stays with them while the other two go for help."},{"title":"Advisor-to-Youth Ratio","text":"Up to **10 youth**: 2 Advisors. More than 10: add **1 adult** (Advisor, adult volunteer, or parent) for every **5 additional youth**."}]},{"t":"p","text":"Quick example: an outing with 20 youth needs at least 4 adults (2 Advisors for the first 10, plus 2 more for the extra 10). And depending on the activity, you may need more — run a risk assessment for every planned event."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**No one-on-one. Ever.** An adult must never be isolated with a single youth. If a conversation needs privacy, hold it where it can't be overheard but **can be seen**: an open outdoor area or a windowed room with the door open. Never closed rooms, tents, motorhomes, or vehicles with no visual access."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Absolute Prohibitions","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Some behaviors are banned at every DeMolay activity, whether by an adult or a youth. These aren't suggestions — they're international policy."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**Hoodwinks and blindfolds are prohibited in ALL DeMolay ceremonies.** No exceptions."},{"t":"list","items":["**Hazing and bullying**: any intentional behavior meant to harm, intimidate, humiliate, or isolate. This includes forced consumption of any substance, physical force, brutality, confinement, exposure to the elements, sleep deprivation, and online humiliation.","**Unauthorized ceremonies**: only ceremonies published in the DeMolay Ritual or the Monitor of Ceremonies may be performed. No secret activities or unofficial organizations.","**Drugs and alcohol**: prohibited for adults and youth alike during DeMolay activities, including misuse of over-the-counter or prescription drugs. Some Jurisdictions also restrict energy drinks.","**Tobacco and nicotine**: cigarettes, cigars, vapes, e-cigarettes, smokeless tobacco, and hookah — banned for everyone during any DeMolay activity.","**Illicit media**: sexually oriented, violent, or racially charged content has no place at any activity.","**Physical violence and contact**: slapping, spanking, corporal punishment, and weapons are prohibited. Adults must avoid unnecessary physical contact with Members."]},{"t":"h","text":"Privacy, Sleeping Arrangements, and Rides"},{"t":"p","text":"Adults change clothes, shower, and sleep **separately** from youth, and never share a sleeping room with youth who are not their own children. Overnight trips require **written approval** from each youth's parent or legal guardian plus a **medical release form**, and they are never held at the home of an Advisor or adult volunteer."},{"t":"p","text":"Activities in private homes need prior approval from the Chapter's **Advisory Council** (the adult body that supervises your Chapter), the **Executive Officer** (the top adult leader of your Jurisdiction), and written permission from all parents. And one telling transportation rule: when an adult drives Members home and drops off the second-to-last youth, the last youth calls his parents to share his expected arrival time."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"If You Suspect Abuse: Act","blocks":[{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Making a report only requires **suspicion — not proof**. You're not an investigator, and it's not your job to confirm anything. Reporting is always the right call."},{"t":"p","text":"If a youth says anything suggesting an inappropriate experience with an adult or another youth, take it **seriously** — even if he doesn't describe it in adult-like terms. Two adults the youth is comfortable with interview him to understand the concern, and the information goes to the event contact and the **Advisory Council Chairman**, who notifies the Executive Officer and the parents."},{"t":"h","text":"When Abuse Is Disclosed, Suspected, or Occurs"},{"t":"steps","items":["The Advisor who identified the situation notifies the **event contact** (the person responsible for the event).","Call **911** or notify the local child protection agency.","Notify the parents or legal guardians of all youth involved, as directed by the authorities.","Notify the Jurisdiction's **Executive Officer** within **24 hours**, with a written report documenting the facts, allegations, and actions taken."]},{"t":"p","text":"The Executive Officer then notifies the Executive Director of DeMolay International and, if the alleged perpetrator is an Advisor or adult volunteer, places them on **leave** from all DeMolay programs and activities pending the investigation. If the parties need to be separated during an event, it's done discreetly."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full Youth Protection policy, with every definition","page":"128"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Insurance and Risk Management","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay International's medical insurance is **secondary**: your family's insurance is always expected to cover you first. DI also carries comprehensive general liability insurance that covers **accidents only** — never intentional injury or property destruction — and it does not insure Chapter property or cover automobile accidents."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Coverage applies only to **DeMolay events documented in the minutes** of the Chapter or Advisory Council, including start time, end time, and a list of participants. If the event isn't in the minutes, the insurance carrier doesn't see it as a DeMolay event."},{"t":"list","items":["**Certificate of Insurance** (proof of coverage that universities and other venues often require): request it online at demolay.org/insurance at least **15 business days** before the event.","If the venue asks to be listed as **additionally insured** or wants an **endorsement**: submit at least **30 days** before the event — and it may incur a cost.","The insurance carries a **deductible**, and DI recommends volunteers add a **Personal Umbrella Policy** to their homeowners or renters insurance.","Nobody drives without their own auto insurance: DeMolay policies do not cover automobile accident damage."]},{"t":"h","text":"Risk Management in 4 Steps"},{"t":"steps","items":["**Identify the Risks**: spot what could go wrong at the activity.","**Analyze the Risks**: weigh how likely and how serious each one is.","**Deal with the Risks**: take action to eliminate or reduce them.","**Monitor the Results**: review how it went and adjust for next time."]},{"t":"p","text":"Habits that lower risk: definite start and end times, parents kept informed and invited, everything recorded in the minutes, age-appropriate activities (what works for a 19-year-old isn't always right for a 13-year-old), a signed **Release and Consent form**, adequate supervision, and every adult registered on eScribe with youth protection training, references, and a background check."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full insurance and risk management details","page":"122"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"When Something Happens: Incidents and Reporting","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Even with solid prevention, accidents happen. When they do, the order of operations matters."},{"t":"steps","items":["**Take care of any injuries first** — DeMolay, Advisor, guest, or third party. Get medical help, notify the authorities, or both.","**Notify the authorities** where appropriate, following the laws of your state or jurisdiction.","**Gather the basic facts**: when it happened, where, what happened (property damage? injury?), who was involved, whether law enforcement was called, and take photos.","**Complete an incident report form** with facts only. If anyone wants your opinions, they'll ask later."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**Never admit liability at the scene.** That something happened doesn't mean DeMolay is liable — fault is an opinion, not a fact. Resist any statement suggesting DeMolay will automatically take care of it."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Any occurrence where potential bodily injury or property damage exceeds **$100** is a **reportable occurrence**."},{"t":"table","headers":["Who","Reports to"],"rows":[["Members, Advisors, and Advisory Council members","Advisory Council Chairman or Chapter Advisor (if unavailable, the Executive Officer)"],["Advisory Council Chairman / Chapter Advisor","Executive Officer"],["Executive Officer","DeMolay International Service and Leadership Center"],["Service and Leadership Center","The national liability insurance carrier"]]},{"t":"p","text":"For **major property damage, serious injury, or death**, notify the Executive Officer immediately. If unavailable, contact their designated individual; failing that, go straight to the Service and Leadership Center in Kansas City: phone **816-891-8333**, fax **816-891-9062**, or email executivedirector@demolay.org."},{"t":"p","text":"Three final details: if the occurrence happens on Masonic property, the Advisory Council Chairman gives **oral notification** to that Masonic body and records the date, time, and who was told. Keep a **copy of every document**. And if an insurance investigator contacts you or you're served with any legal document, talk to your **Executive Officer first** before responding."},{"t":"ref","text":"The complete incident reporting procedure","page":"125"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"What's the minimum number of registered Advisors required at EVERY DeMolay activity?","options":["One, as long as it's the Chapter Advisor","Two","Three","It depends on the type of activity"],"correct":1,"explain":"Two-Deep Leadership: at least 2 Advisors at all DeMolay trips, outings, and Chapter activities — no exceptions. Even parents being present doesn't replace this."},{"q":"Your Chapter plans an outing with 20 youth. What's the minimum number of adults required?","options":["2","3","4","6"],"correct":2,"explain":"2 Advisors cover up to 10 youth; add 1 adult for every 5 additional youth. With 20 youth: 2 + 2 = 4 adults."},{"q":"Why does the Rule of Four exist?","options":["So Chapter votes never end in a tie","So that if someone gets hurt, one person stays with them while two go for help","To split event costs among more people","To guarantee quorum at meetings"],"correct":1,"explain":"At least 4 individuals (including at least 2 adults) at every activity: if an incident occurs, one stays with the injured party and the other two go for help."},{"q":"What are the three R's of Youth Protection?","options":["Respect, Respond, Report","Recognize, Resist, Report","Recognize, React, Rescue","Refuse, Resist, Reply"],"correct":1,"explain":"Recognize risky situations, Resist unwanted or inappropriate attention, and Report to an Advisor, parent, or other trusted adult."},{"q":"You suspect a youth has been abused, but you have no proof. What should you do?","options":["Wait until you gather proof before saying anything","Investigate on your own until you can confirm it","Report anyway — suspicion is enough. Call 911 or the local agency and notify the Executive Officer within 24 hours","Discuss it only with the youth involved"],"correct":2,"explain":"Making a report only requires suspicion, not proof. Call 911 or the local child protection agency, and notify the Executive Officer within 24 hours with a written report."},{"q":"How does DeMolay International's medical insurance work?","options":["It's each member's primary insurance","It's secondary: the member's family insurance covers first","It covers any accident, whether or not the event was documented","It also covers Advisors' cars"],"correct":1,"explain":"DI's medical insurance is always secondary — the family's insurance is expected to cover first. And it only applies to DeMolay events documented in the minutes."},{"q":"How far in advance must a Certificate of Insurance be requested?","options":["48 hours","5 business days","15 business days","30 calendar days"],"correct":2,"explain":"Request it online at demolay.org/insurance at least 15 business days before the event. Additionally insured or endorsement requests need at least 30 days."},{"q":"Above what amount of potential damage must an incident always be reported?","options":["$50","More than $100","$500","$1,000"],"correct":1,"explain":"Any occurrence where potential bodily injury or property damage exceeds $100 must be reported up the chain: Chairman/Chapter Advisor, Executive Officer, and the Service and Leadership Center."}]},"ritual":{"title":"Ritual: the Heart of DeMolay","subtitle":"Why Ritual puts DeMolay in a class by itself, and how to deliver it the way it deserves.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Why Ritual Is Everything","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Ritual is what sets DeMolay apart from every other youth organization and keeps it in a class by itself. **Frank A. Marshall** wrote it in 1919, and it has remained almost unchanged ever since: the words you speak in your Chapter today are essentially the same ones the first DeMolays heard more than a century ago."},{"t":"p","text":"That Ritual has held the Order together since its founding and inspired thousands: state governors, flag-rank officers in the U.S. Armed Services, teachers, pastors, business owners, and community leaders. More than **5,000** DeMolays went on to become 33rd Degree Scottish Rite Masons."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Zero deviation. In the Initiatory Degree, the DeMolay Degree, the Flower Talk, and the Ceremony of Light, no deviation is allowed — not even the slightest. The latest edition of the Ritual is followed to the letter, always."},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Never read it. All ritual work is delivered **from memory**, every time: a Degree, the funeral service for a fallen Brother, or a presentation to a visiting Mason. Reading from the Ritual leaves a terrible impression of the Order."},{"t":"p","text":"There is a structure to keep quality high: every Jurisdiction should have a **Ritual Director**, and every Chapter a **Ritual Advisor**. Each Jurisdiction should also run an annual competition to crown champion Initiatory and DeMolay Degree teams, and push the **Ritual Merit Bar** to keep interest in Ritual alive and growing."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"How to Present a Degree","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The beauty of ritual lies in how it is presented. Settings, lighting, and robes help, but unless the words come out slowly, concisely, naturally, emotionally, and gracefully, the whole thing turns mechanical. Speak in a full, loud voice, look straight into the candidate's eyes, and deliver every line as if it came «from the heart» — your job is to impart the message of DeMolay, not to parrot it."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Initiatory Degree","text":"Won through **earnestness and sincerity**, not dramatic or fake acting. Speak slowly, calmly, and loudly enough for every word to land: a word unheard is a message lost. Over-acting is just as serious a fault as underacting."},{"title":"DeMolay Degree","text":"Written in a very different vein: it is meant to be **dramatic and elaborate** within reasonable limits. It cannot be delivered in a conversational tone, yet it is just as easily ruined by overacting. A room with a stage or a large open area is ideal, but it works in any Chapter room with a solid plan and firm direction."}]},{"t":"p","text":"Small details make the big result: a robe with the collar sitting just right, neatly combed hair, dignified and unhurried entrances and exits, sitting upright with feet flat on the floor, and proper square corners on the floor. Sideliners notice everything."},{"t":"h","text":"Degree Teams and Rehearsals"},{"t":"p","text":"Building the Degree team is a major call for the **Master Councilor**: personal friendships stay out of it — selection is based on interest, enthusiasm, and ability. And no one should be trusted with a part unless he feels that interpreting it is an honor."},{"t":"list","items":["Schedule regular rehearsals and set a standard every Member must meet and maintain.","Find coaches: Advisory Council members, Senior DeMolays, ritualists from Masonic Family organizations, high school drama teachers, or relatives with public-speaking experience.","Keep at least one alternate for every part.","If your Chapter is large enough, build a full second Degree team and use it every so often.","Robes are not required, but they lift the work enormously — and they do not have to be expensive."]}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Rules of the Room","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Chapter room is the stage for the Ritual, and that stage comes with fixed rules you should know by heart."},{"t":"list","items":["The altar is always draped with a **large white altar cover**, hung in large folds for beautiful lines; flowers may be placed on and around it.","**Seven candlesticks** form a shield about and in front of the altar; placement diagrams are in the Ritual book.","Preceptor stands can be purchased or built by someone handy with woodworking."]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Never pass between the altar and the East unless the floor work in the Ritual requires it. To reach the other side of the room, always go by way of the **West**."},{"t":"list","items":["No one enters or leaves the Chapter room during the Opening and Closing ceremonies.","A latecomer waits until the Chapter has opened; once admitted, he goes to the altar and gives the proper sign — same procedure if he needs to be excused before closing.","To speak, rise, wait to be called on, and address the MC as **Brother Master Councilor**, without any salute."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The **Nine O'clock Interpolation** is given at EVERY meeting, public or private, at the proper time, with all lights dimmed if possible or with only candles lighted."},{"t":"p","text":"For the obligation, the ideal is to take all candidates to the altar and have them kneel. If the class is too large, you may seat all but a few for everything — except the obligation. And the priority rule is clear: manner of presentation first; costumes, lighting, and setting second."},{"t":"ref","text":"Diagrams, full Degree work guidelines, and the late-arrival procedure","page":"138"}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Obligations, the Obligation Card, and Music","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every Member of the Chapter must commit the obligations of the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees to memory. Making that happen is the **Junior Councilor's** job: he sets a time and place to coach the new initiates and keeps a running tally book with the names of those who have not yet complied."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"No **obligation card**, no rights: you cannot vote in the election of Officers, vote on membership applications, or hold office."},{"t":"list","items":["Signed by the Chapter Advisor and bearing the seal of the Chapter.","Recorded on **eScribe** in the Member's permanent record.","Issued as certification that you have proven proficient in reciting the obligations from memory.","Only **one card** per Member; a duplicate is issued only if the original is lost, and at the Chapter Advisor's discretion."]},{"t":"h","text":"Music"},{"t":"p","text":"Music has a definite place in all ritualistic work — as a background that enhances, never over-dramatic or loud enough to drown the Degree. The secret is the handoff: when a spoken sentence ends, the music comes in without a pause, and when the music closes, the next speaker begins immediately, with no awkward gaps. The Ritual of Secret Work marks several spots in the Initiatory Degree where music fits best, and many Chapters use pre-recorded tracks keyed to the length of the Degree with excellent results."}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Public Ceremonies: Flower Talk, Ceremony of Light, and More","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Public ceremonies are your best showcase: every presentation before parents, Masons, or the community is a chance to put DeMolay's best foot forward. Many Chapters invite the public in after an induction for a Welcoming Talk (ideally given by a Past Master Councilor), the Flower Talk, and the Nine O'clock Interpolation, then close with refreshments."},{"t":"h","text":"Flower Talk"},{"t":"p","text":"It is one of the best-received messages DeMolay has, and it has a captivating effect on mothers. It is given after conferring the Initiatory or DeMolay Degree — it is not an official part of either Degree — or at other appropriate public ceremonies. An Active DeMolay with a pleasing, mature voice presents it, **from memory**, dressed in formal attire."},{"t":"list","items":["**Red and white flowers** on the altar, placed there before the ceremony begins; short-stemmed roses or carnations are preferable, though less expensive flowers work.","At least one flower for every candidate, and a **white flower for each candidate whose mother has passed away**.","The Marshal conducts the new Members to the west side of the altar; the speaker takes the east side, in the same position the MC takes when giving the obligation."]},{"t":"h","text":"Ceremony of Light"},{"t":"p","text":"A brief ceremony designed as a public relations tool that sums up DeMolay's basic teachings: **seven candles are lit to symbolize the seven cardinal virtues** — the Order's core values — explained as symbols of all that is good and right with the world. An Active DeMolay gives it, and with the Executive Officer's permission it may be divided among multiple speakers. Required paraphernalia: a Holy Bible open on the altar, schoolbooks on the northeast corner of the altar, and the seven candlesticks with candles **already lighted**, arranged per Diagram One in the Monitor of Ceremonies, with all other lights dimmed or extinguished."},{"t":"p","text":"The **Historical Lecture** is a short, informative talk about Jacques DeMolay, the Order's namesake: fitting for the public, Masonic or service groups, history classes, or candidates, with no required paraphernalia. The texts of the Flower Talk, the Ceremony of Light, and the Historical Lecture are available at demolay.org/open-ceremonies, and the Monitor of Public Ceremonies collects all the official public ceremonies."},{"t":"ref","text":"Welcoming Talk text and details for every public ceremony","page":"142"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Open Installations: Your Chapter in Front of the Community","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The Open Installation of Officers is one of the few times the community walks in, watches, and forms a definite opinion of DeMolay and of your Chapter. Everything has to run smoothly — and that comes from planning ahead."},{"t":"steps","items":["Select the Installing Officers well in advance so they have time to prepare and agree on the order of events.","Make sure the Officers to be installed know exactly when and where to be, and have substitutes ready: empty Officer chairs leave the impression that things are not going well for the Chapter.","Print a program for every guest: the order of events, the Installing Officers, the Officers to be installed, the Advisors with their titles, the Sponsoring Body and its presiding officer, the Parents' Club Officers, the Chapter Sweetheart or Sorority, the Squires Officers and Advisors, acknowledgments, and the Executive Officer with his district representative.","Line up an organist or pianist, or use quality pre-recorded music: music adds a great deal, as long as it suits the ceremony and the audience.","Work the publicity: an advance story in local media stating that the public is invited, plus a photo of the new Officers for the newspaper and social media.","Send personal invitations (printed card, letter, or phone call) to Masonic leaders, civic officials, and school superintendents and principals, and advertise to nearby Chapters, youth groups, and the Masonic Family with a social media event or at minimum an emailed flyer.","Have the room ready before the first guest arrives, seating the earliest guests as close to the East as possible so latecomers can be seated with minimum confusion."]},{"t":"p","text":"Introductions of guests are carried out with speed and accuracy, following your Jurisdiction's order of protocol — which the MC must know cold: from Active DeMolays and DeMolay leaders to Masonic dignitaries (including the Grand Master of the Grand Lodge), visiting Masons, the parents of the principal Chapter Officers, and visiting delegations from Rainbow, Job's Daughters, and other youth groups."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Always add something extra to the program: the Flower Talk, a Representative DeMolay Presentation, the Majority Service, or presentations of Merit Bars and Blue Honor Keys. Rotate the extras at each Installation so it never gets repetitive."}]},{"id":"l7","title":"How Ritual Competitions Are Judged","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Ritual competitions are among the most popular activities in every Jurisdiction. What follows is the Service & Leadership Center's suggested framework: each Jurisdiction may run its own system, and everything is subject to the final approval and authority of the **Executive Officer**."},{"t":"table","headers":["Area","What it covers","Weight"],"rows":[["Memory Work","Reciting the exact words of the most current editions of the DeMolay Ritual and Monitor of Public Ceremonies","One-half of all points"],["Performance","Delivery, Floor Work, Deportment, and Supplementary Items","The other half"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Memory is worth **one-half of all available points**. A dedicated judge follows the official Ritual and marks every omission, transposition, or error: in many systems the ceremony's word count is a perfect score, each wrong word subtracts 1 point, and prompting or another serious error can cost **25 or 50 points**."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Delivery","text":"Audibility, clarity, enunciation, tone, tempo, and expression. Misplaced emphasis, mispronounced words, speaking too fast or too slow, and lack of forcefulness all draw penalty points. Sincerity of expression counts too."},{"title":"Floor Work","text":"The characters' movements exactly as outlined in the Ritual, plus physical properties, lighting, and setting (properties weigh less than movements). Judges here must be thoroughly familiar with the correct procedure."},{"title":"Deportment","text":"Posture and general bearing: how the characters move from position to position, how they sit, and the impression their presence leaves."},{"title":"Supplementary Items","text":"Music (using it well earns positive credit), dress, and overall impression. What's judged is not how much the costumes cost but how they are worn: a wristwatch on a 14th-century character is an authenticity error."}]},{"t":"p","text":"One judge can usually handle Memory Work, but many systems use two judges per category and average their scores. Judges must have no ties to the competing teams, must hold every team to the same standard, and it is good practice to stipulate a specific dictionary edition as the standard reference for pronunciation. Any ritual questions? Your Jurisdictional Ritual Advisor or Executive Officer is the contact."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full suggested judging system","page":"198"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"In which ceremonies is not even the slightest deviation from the Ritual allowed?","options":["Only the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees","The Initiatory Degree, the DeMolay Degree, the Flower Talk, and the Ceremony of Light","Only the public ceremonies in the Monitor","The Historical Lecture and Open Installations"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Handbook demands zero deviation in those four: both Degrees, the Flower Talk, and the Ceremony of Light — always per the latest edition of the Ritual."},{"q":"What is the right way to present the Initiatory Degree?","options":["With drama and elaborate gestures","With earnestness and sincerity, no fake acting","Reading from the Ritual with good diction","In a quick, relaxed conversational tone"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Initiatory impresses through sincerity; the dramatic one (within limits) is the DeMolay Degree. And reading from the Ritual is never allowed."},{"q":"During a meeting you need to reach the other side of the Chapter room. What do you do?","options":["Cross between the altar and the East if no one is speaking","Go by way of the West","Wait until the meeting ends","Tell the Sentinel and cut through the middle"],"correct":1,"explain":"No one passes between the altar and the East unless the Ritual's floor work requires it. You always cross by way of the West."},{"q":"When is the Nine O'clock Interpolation given?","options":["Only at private meetings","Only when candidates are present","At every meeting, public or private","Only when the Executive Officer authorizes it"],"correct":2,"explain":"It is required at all meetings, at the proper time, with lights dimmed if possible or with only candles lighted."},{"q":"What can a Member NOT do until he holds his obligation card?","options":["Attend Chapter meetings","Vote in elections, vote on membership applications, or hold office","Take part in sports events","Invite friends to a public ceremony"],"correct":1,"explain":"The obligation card certifies you memorized the obligations; without it you cannot vote for Officers or on applications, or hold office."},{"q":"In the Flower Talk, what does a white flower on the altar indicate?","options":["That a candidate's mother has passed away","The purity of DeMolay's teachings","That the candidate is a Past Master Councilor","Peace among the Brothers of the Chapter"],"correct":0,"explain":"There must be at least one flower per candidate, and a white one for each candidate whose mother has passed away."},{"q":"What do the seven candles in the Ceremony of Light symbolize?","options":["The Chapter's seven Preceptors","The seven cardinal virtues of DeMolay","The seven principal Officers","The seven centuries since Jacques DeMolay"],"correct":1,"explain":"The seven candles are lit to symbolize the seven cardinal virtues, or core values, presented as symbols of all that is good and right with the world."},{"q":"In a ritual competition, how much is Memory Work worth?","options":["One quarter of the score","One third of the score","One-half of all the points","It depends on each judge"],"correct":2,"explain":"Scoring systems agree that memory counts for half of all points; the other half is Performance. Prompting can cost 25 or 50 points."}]},"organizacion":{"title":"How DeMolay Is Governed","subtitle":"From the International Supreme Council down to your Chapter: who decides what, and where you fit in.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"From Kansas City to the World: DeMolay Gets a Government","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"When the Kansas City Chapter (later renamed the **Mother Chapter**) took off in fall 1919 and early 1920, requests for information and for authority to start new Chapters came pouring in. Somebody had to govern all of that. A temporary body called **The Grand Council of the Order of DeMolay for Boys** was formed: it prepared the Constitution and Statutes, printed rituals and forms, and handled the details out of Frank S. Land's office in the Scottish Rite building."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"On March 7, 1921, at the Scottish Rite Temple in Kansas City, the Grand Council held its first annual session. Thirteen people took part, electing Alexander G. Cochran as the first Grand Master Councilor and Frank S. Land as Grand Scribe."},{"t":"list","items":["The Constitution and Statutes prepared by the formation committee were adopted, capping the Grand Council at 50 members.","Frank Land presented 52 Chapters requesting their charter (the document that officially authorizes a Chapter); all were already up and running, with 3,336 active members as of January 31, 1921.","Charter No. 1 went to the Mother Chapter; No. 2 to Huron Chapter (Kansas City, Kansas) and No. 3 to Pittsburg Chapter (Pittsburg, Kansas).","The five original Obligatory Days were adopted: Patriots Day, Parents Day, DeMolay Day of Comfort, Devotional Day, and Educational Day."]},{"t":"p","text":"Growth was explosive: by the 1922 session there were already **404 Chapters** across 27 states plus Manitoba, Puerto Rico, and the Philippines. By the end of 1922 there were **667 Chapters with 68,629 DeMolays**, and by March 1923 there were Chapters in every U.S. state except Maine, Vermont, and Rhode Island."},{"t":"p","text":"That international growth drove a formal rename: on **March 1, 1954**, the Grand Council became the **International Supreme Council** (ISC) of the Order of DeMolay."},{"t":"ref","text":"The full history of the Supreme Council, with every name and date","page":"182"}]},{"id":"l2","title":"The International Supreme Council Today","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The ISC is DeMolay International's **supreme authority**: it regulates and controls laws, statutes, Chapters, Advisory Councils, members, charters, finances, rituals, disputes, appeals, and officers. Its members are Masons from all over the world who have already proven their leadership in other walks of life and now give DeMolay the benefit of their experience and counsel."},{"t":"p","text":"The **Grand Master** presides, elected along with **four other officers** at the Council's annual meeting each spring. Since Louis A. Watres in 1936, Grand Masters have served for one year only."},{"t":"table","headers":["Year","Council membership cap"],"rows":[["1921","50 (original Constitution)"],["c. 1930","125"],["1956","150"],["1958","250"],["2012","No more than 150 Class 1 members, exclusive of Past Grand Masters and Executive Officers"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"ISC members receive no compensation: their only reward is the satisfaction and pride of sustaining the organization."},{"t":"p","text":"Fun fact: there have been three honorary Grand Masters in history: **Franklin D. Roosevelt** (1933), **Harry S. Truman** (1945), and **John G. Diefenbaker**, Prime Minister of Canada (March 7, 1958). And Congressman Walter C. Ploeser was the first Senior DeMolay elected Grand Master, serving in 1952-53. Yes: a former DeMolay can end up running the whole thing."}]},{"id":"l3","title":"The Executive Officer and the Chain of Command","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay is divided into **Jurisdictions**: entire or partial states, provinces, territories, or countries. Each one is supervised by an **Executive Officer** (EO), the Supreme Council's official representative in all DeMolay affairs in that Jurisdiction. The title was adopted at the 1957 ISC session to distinguish members in charge of a Jurisdiction from At-Large Members (members without an assigned Jurisdiction)."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Golden rule: in your Jurisdiction, everything goes through the Executive Officer. Any plan, event, or organization not covered by the Rules & Regulations needs his sanction and approval."},{"t":"list","items":["New or reinstated Chapters","The appointment of all Advisory Council members","Additions to Chapter by-laws to govern local conditions","Recommendations for the granting of charters","Changes in sponsoring bodies, Chapter names, and Chapter locations","Legion of Honor Preceptories, Chevalier Courts, Jurisdictional DeMolay Chapters, Priories of the Order of Knighthood, and Jurisdictional Conclaves/Conventions"]},{"t":"p","text":"The EO may also appoint **mid-level Deputies or Directors** at his discretion, to boost leadership and cut down on travel. They supervise the Chapters of a county or other small subdivision and are required to visit and inspect them at regular intervals. Heads up: they are in no way connected to the Supreme Council; they serve as the EO's personal representatives."},{"t":"steps","items":["DeMolay International (ISC): the supreme authority and the global rules","Jurisdiction: the Executive Officer as the ISC's official representative","Mid-level (district, region, or division): the Deputies and Directors the EO appoints","Chapter: where you live DeMolay every single week"]}]},{"id":"l4","title":"The Service & Leadership Center in Kansas City","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The day-to-day of DeMolay International runs through the **Service & Leadership Center** in Kansas City. The **Grand Secretary** is responsible for its operation and for the general extension and promotion of DeMolay; the staff implements the ISC's programs and policies daily. It serves in four capacities:"},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Central Office of Record","text":"Keeps the records of all active and Senior DeMolays, Chevaliers, Legion of Honor members, Advisors, and awards; processes Annual Reports and new member reports; and issues Patents and Letters Temporary (the initial authorization for a new Chapter)."},{"title":"Agent for Service","text":"Helps Executive Officers, their Jurisdictions, and their Chapters: membership program ideas, how to raise money, speeches on DeMolay, civic projects, ritual improvement, plus the forms and supplies needed to run a Chapter."},{"title":"Agency for Promotion","text":"Promotes the program nonstop: securing new members, keeping activities balanced to hold older members, and cultivating appreciation among sponsoring bodies and the general public."},{"title":"Source of Unification","text":"It is the nerve center that keeps DeMolay the same no matter where in the world a Chapter is located: one strong, cohesive worldwide brotherhood."}]},{"t":"p","text":"How is DeMolay International financed? Mainly through the **initiation fee** paid by every new member; the rest comes from the sale of supplies, investment income, donations, and contributions. It runs on one of the smallest staffs and budgets of any similar movement in the world, largely because DeMolay's leaders give their time freely, often at considerable personal expense."},{"t":"ref","text":"The four functions of the Service & Leadership Center, in detail","page":"199"}]},{"id":"l5","title":"The International DeMolay Congress: The Members' Voice","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"In 1966, members of the ISC wanted DeMolay's young men themselves to lead the organization by collaborating on improvements and sharing ideas. The proposal was championed by George A. Newbury (Sovereign Grand Commander of the Scottish Rite, Northern Masonic Jurisdiction) and Walter C. Ploeser, and the **first International DeMolay Congress was held in 1967**, gathering **two leading DeMolays from each Jurisdiction**."},{"t":"p","text":"It quickly became clear the Congress needed leadership of its own. In 1968, **Roderick S. Coy**, State Master Councilor of Michigan, was elected the first **International Master Councilor** (IMC), the position that ensures the entire Congress's voice is heard by the ISC and the Service & Leadership Center. Soon after, the **International Congress Secretary** (ICS) was created as his partner to organize the Congress and appoint committees. The IMC and ICS lead it together to this day."},{"t":"p","text":"The ISC also voted to add **two active DeMolays to its Board of Directors**, seats traditionally held by the IMC and ICS. The international officers travel widely representing the organization, and the Congress committees work alongside them to produce and promote new programs."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"The Congress is primarily funded by the Scottish Rite Northern Masonic Jurisdiction, and it attracts the best and the brightest to lead DeMolay International."}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Level Up: DLC, Workshops, Conclaves, and the LCC","blocks":[{"t":"h","text":"DeMolay Leadership Conference (DLC)"},{"t":"p","text":"Each summer, Regions and Jurisdictions sponsor **week-long** leadership conferences (also known as Leadership Training Conference, or LTC), open both to DeMolays already in leadership positions and to potential leaders. Their three purposes: develop leadership qualities, educate on basic DeMolay programs, and build friendships among DeMolays from many jurisdictions. Attendees are divided into chapters of **15 people or less** so everyone gets to contribute, and the cost published each year covers food, lodging, the Leadership Conference Notebook, and a t-shirt. Leadership Camps were all the rage in the late twenties and early thirties, and the ISC revived the Leadership Conference program in 1963."},{"t":"p","text":"At the Jurisdictional level, **workshops** train the people who are about to reach the top posts: Junior and Senior Councilors, Scribes, Treasurers, and Advisors; the Master Councilor is left out on purpose, because the whole point is preparing whoever comes next. The classic format runs 24 hours, noon to noon, with groups of 10 to 20 people. **Conclaves/Conventions** usually rotate sites each year, and the Service & Leadership Center has an extensive planning checklist available on request. At the district level, competitions (Degrees, Flower Talk, oratorical, athletic) select representatives for the jurisdictional competitions."},{"t":"h","text":"Leaders Correspondence Course (LCC)"},{"t":"list","items":["Online 24/7 at **BeADeMolay.org/lcc/**, completely free","**5 courses** taken in order, from 1 to 5, with true-false, multiple-choice, and fill-in-the-blank questions","The only reference you need: the current edition of the DHB (DeMolay Handbook)","Auto-graded: pass and you print a certificate and earn a digital badge for your social media; fall short and you retake that course until you pass"]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"The system does NOT save your progress: until eScribe is upgraded, once you start a course you have to finish it in that same sitting."},{"t":"p","text":"Show each completed certificate to your Awards Advisor so they can order the matching **Merit Bar**. And once you finish all five courses, you are eligible to wear the **Lamp of Knowledge** pin."},{"t":"ref","text":"Everything about the Leaders Correspondence Course","page":"195"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"When and where was the first annual session of DeMolay's Grand Council held?","options":["March 7, 1921, at the Scottish Rite Temple in Kansas City","March 1, 1954, in St. Louis","March 7, 1958, in Baltimore","January 31, 1920, in Kansas City"],"correct":0,"explain":"That day, 13 people adopted the Constitution and Statutes, elected officers, and received charter requests from 52 Chapters that were already operating."},{"q":"What happened on March 1, 1954?","options":["The Executive Officer title was created","The Grand Council was renamed the International Supreme Council","The first International DeMolay Congress was held","The Council's membership cap was raised to 250"],"correct":1,"explain":"DeMolay's international growth drove the formal name change. The Executive Officer title was adopted in 1957, and the first Congress came in 1967."},{"q":"Under the 2012 redefinition, what is the ISC's membership cap?","options":["50 members total","125 members total","No more than 150 Class 1 members, exclusive of Past Grand Masters and Executive Officers","250 members with no exceptions"],"correct":2,"explain":"The cap changed over time (50, 125, 150, 250) until 2012, when it was redefined as 150 Class 1 members, excluding Past Grand Masters and Executive Officers."},{"q":"Who must approve a new Chapter, Advisory Council appointments, and Conclaves in your Jurisdiction?","options":["The Grand Master directly","The International Master Councilor","The Jurisdiction's Executive Officer","The Advisory Council of the oldest Chapter"],"correct":2,"explain":"The Executive Officer is the Supreme Council's official representative in his Jurisdiction: everything that happens there needs his sanction and approval."},{"q":"What is DeMolay International's main source of funding?","options":["An annual fee paid by every Chapter","The initiation fee paid by each new member","State government grants","Ticket sales at Conclaves"],"correct":1,"explain":"The initiation fee from new members is the base; the rest comes from supply sales, investment income, donations, and contributions."},{"q":"In what year was the first International DeMolay Congress held?","options":["1921","1957","1963","1967"],"correct":3,"explain":"The idea was born within the ISC in 1966, and the first Congress took place in 1967, with two leading DeMolays from each Jurisdiction."},{"q":"Which two officers lead the International DeMolay Congress together?","options":["The Grand Master and the Grand Secretary","The International Master Councilor (IMC) and the International Congress Secretary (ICS)","The Executive Officer and his Deputy","Two Past Grand Masters elected by the ISC"],"correct":1,"explain":"The IMC (the first was Roderick S. Coy, in 1968) and the ICS run the Congress, and traditionally hold the two active-DeMolay seats on the Board of Directors."},{"q":"Before starting a Leaders Correspondence Course (LCC) course, what should you keep in mind?","options":["There is a fee for each course","The system does not save your progress: you have to finish the course in one sitting","Only Advisors may take it","You must pass an in-person final exam"],"correct":1,"explain":"Until eScribe is upgraded, the LCC will not remember where you left off. It is free, there are 5 online courses, and completing them makes you eligible for the Lamp of Knowledge pin."}]},"cuerpos":{"title":"Appendant Bodies: The DeMolay Family Beyond Your Chapter","subtitle":"Squires, Knighthood, Chevaliers, and the Legion of Honor — who they are, how they work, and where you fit in.","minutes":12,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"A Map of the Appendant Bodies","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay doesn't start or end at your Chapter. Around the Order, four **Appendant Bodies** are at work: organizations that welcome boys before age 12, keep DeMolays engaged after 17, and channel the service of those who have already earned the Order's highest honors."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Squires of the Round Table","text":"For boys aged 9 to 11, organized in **Manors**. It's the on-ramp to DeMolay: fun activities, simple ceremonies, and older brothers as role models."},{"title":"Order of Knighthood","text":"For active DeMolays aged 17 to 21, organized in **Priories**. A working body built around service — not an honorary award."},{"title":"Court of Chevaliers","text":"Brings together those who hold the **Degree of Chevalier** and confers that degree on new recipients named by the Supreme Council."},{"title":"Preceptories of the Legion of Honor","text":"Unite the **Legionnaires** — accomplished leaders shaped by DeMolay — so they can give their experience back to the Order."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Think of it as stages: Squires prepares you before you join, Knighthood keeps you active as an older member, and Chevaliers and the Legion of Honor organize the service of those who have been honored."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Squires of the Round Table: The Little Brothers","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The **Order of the Squires of the Round Table** lets boys aged **9 to 11** enjoy DeMolay-style activities and benefits without being overwhelmed by the age gap with older members. They have easy-to-learn opening and closing ceremonies that prepare them to become DeMolays. Every Squire belongs to a **Manor**, where he can hold office — always with Advisors present, and with parents welcome at every event."},{"t":"h","text":"Where the Name Comes From"},{"t":"p","text":"The Squires were established in **1995** in Vancouver, Washington, and formally adopted by DeMolay International in **2015**. In the Middle Ages, a Squire was a young man training to become a Knight; here, he's training to become a DeMolay. And Manors were the estates ruled by Knights and Nobles."},{"t":"list","items":["**The emblem** is a circle — the Round Table the Squires symbolically gather around — divided into four sections:","Upper left: the knight from the DeMolay emblem, because without DeMolay there would be no Squires.","Upper right: the gavel of justice, held by the Master Squire during meetings.","Lower left: the sword of truth, held by the Senior Squire.","Lower right: the schoolbooks of wisdom, held by the Junior Squire."]},{"t":"h","text":"How a Manor Runs"},{"t":"p","text":"A Manor has up to **7 officers**: three elected by their peers (**Master Squire, Senior Squire, and Junior Squire**) and four appointed (Squire Chaplain, Squire Marshal, Squire Recorder, and Squire Treasurer). Terms last **6 months**, and in each one the Master Squire must plan at least **one fun activity and one fundraising activity**, approved by the Dad/Mom Advisor. An Advisor from the Chapter Advisory Council must be present at every meeting and function. A Manor may also have a **Squire Mentor**: a DeMolay who acts as a \"big brother,\" appointed by the Master Councilor of the sponsoring Chapter and approved by the Advisory Council. He sits to the left of the Master Squire's station, and his term parallels the Chapter's."},{"t":"steps","items":["Review your Jurisdiction's guidelines and clear up any questions with the Executive Officer or the Director of Squires, if there is one.","Get a sponsor: a DeMolay Chapter Advisory Council or the Jurisdiction itself (the Advisory Council votes to sponsor).","Form the Manor Council with at least **2 registered DeMolay Advisors** from the sponsoring Advisory Council, plus the Squire Mentor as liaison with the Chapter.","Draft the Manor's Bylaws: name, meeting dates and place, officer terms, and membership fees.","File the **Declaration of Intent** along with the Bylaws with the Executive Officer, who decides whether to approve the founding.","Recruit members: each prospect must be between 9 and 11 years old, complete the Squires Membership Application, pay the fee, and be approved by the Manor.","Hold the first induction (in this case, Active DeMolays may perform the ritual) and report the new Squires on eScribe within **10 days**.","Elect the three elected officers by majority vote and hold the Installation — a public ceremony with the installing parts performed by Active DeMolays."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"Golden numbers: with **3 Squires** a Manor can operate on a temporary basis (that interim period should last no more than 6 months); with **5 members**, the Charter can be issued."},{"t":"p","text":"The **Master Squires Meritorious Service Award** is the medal the International Supreme Council gives a Master Squire who completes the full circuit: memorize his portion of the Ritual, print and distribute his program for the term, send a first letter of intent to the Executive Officer, see that all the Manor's ritual work is given from memory, confer an induction, run at least **3 activities** built around at least 2 of the categories **Justice, Truth, and Wisdom**, induct at least **3 new members**, and send the second letter (with a full recap, program analysis, and attendance report) within **10 days** after the term ends, countersigned by the Squire Mentor and the Manor Advisor."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full Squires section in the Handbook","page":"167"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"The Order of Knighthood: What It Is and Where It Came From","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The **Order of Knighthood** is the appendant body for older members: **active DeMolays aged 17 to 21**, organized into a unit called a **Priory** with its own officers and ritual. Its full official name is the **Chivalric Knights of the Holy Order of the Fellow-Soldiers of Jacques DeMolay**. Make no mistake: it's not an honorary degree or an award — it's a working body whose purpose is to extend fellowship and give service to DeMolay."},{"t":"list","items":["Extend and assist DeMolay International and its Chapters.","Maintain the active interest of older DeMolays in the Order.","Provide an exciting program for Priory members.","And above all, provide and maintain the proper example for all DeMolays."]},{"t":"h","text":"Nearly 80 Years of History"},{"t":"p","text":"Knighthood debuted in **1946**, when the ritual was exemplified before the Grand Council — now the International Supreme Council — and Priories were authorized to organize. At first, members had to be 18 to 21. The first Priory was started by Mother Chapter in Kansas City, Missouri: it received its Charter on **October 27, 1947**, and held its first investiture on **January 10, 1948**, at the Ivanhoe Masonic Building, with **Everett L. Davis** presiding as the first Illustrious Knight Commander. All of the first Sir Knights were Chevaliers of Mother Chapter. The idea took off: by March 1948 there were **34 Priories in 18 states with over 700 Sir Knights**. In **1973**, the Supreme Council approved an optional second degree: the **Order of Ebon**."},{"t":"h","text":"The 11 Officers of a Priory"},{"t":"list","items":["Illustrious Knight Commander","Sir Knight Squire Commander","Sir Knight Page Commander","Sir Knight Registrar","Sir Knight Senior Deacon","Sir Knight Junior Deacon","Sir Knight Prior","Sir Knight Preceptor","Sir Knight Sacristan","Sir Knight Standard Bearer","Sir Knight Sentinel"]},{"t":"p","text":"The first four (Illustrious Knight Commander, Squire Commander, Page Commander, and Registrar) are often **elected**; the rest are appointed by the Illustrious Knight Commander. The term of office is set in the Priory's Bylaws, always under the DeMolay International Statutes and Bylaws."},{"t":"steps","items":["Notify your Executive Officer that you want to form a Priory and obtain his sanction and approval (not all Jurisdictions have Knighthood Priories).","Submit a **Declaration of Intention** showing the sponsoring body, the Advisory Council, and at least **5 DeMolay members aged 17 but not past their 21st birthday**, and forward it to the Service & Leadership Center through the Executive Officer with the proper forms and fees.","Once approved, **Letters Temporary** are granted and the Priory may be formed; if it meets and operates successfully for **6 months**, a Charter may be issued.","Collect the application and fee before the Investiture, and enter the new Knights into eScribe within **10 days** so the patent can be issued."]},{"t":"ref","text":"Full Knighthood section in the Handbook","page":"172"}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Knighthood in Action: Program, Award, and Emblem","blocks":[{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"**Over half** of a Priory's program planning should involve service. The Knights of old were vowed to service — today's Knights find their whole purpose through it."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"DeMolay Service","text":"The headline area: form Installing Teams, confer the Majority Service or Memorial Service, fill in parts for Chapter Degrees, help judge ritual competitions, assist with workshops, and aid the Jurisdictional Master Councilor with his program."},{"title":"Social Programs","text":"Events pitched at the 17-to-21 crowd — while staying active in their own Chapter's social life. Always in compliance with DeMolay International's Youth Protection Policies and Risk Management Guidelines."},{"title":"Athletic Activities","text":"More than playing: serve as coaches, umpires, judges, or referees, and even organize an athletic league for a group of Chapters. Every Knight should support his own Chapter's athletic program."},{"title":"Masonic Service","text":"Looking toward the adult world: direct service to elderly Masons or their widows, donating blood to the credit of Masonic Homes or Shrine Burns Institutes, raising money for Masonic charities, and helping at Masonic functions."}]},{"t":"p","text":"Only Knights, Senior Knights, Advisors, and Master Masons may attend a **tiled** (closed-door) meeting of a Priory. And meetings aim to be much more than business sessions: programs on government, civic projects, current issues, college and careers, science, sports, or hobbies — often dinner meetings followed by a speaker."},{"t":"h","text":"The PIKC-MSA: The Illustrious Knight Commander's Medal"},{"t":"list","items":["Before the Installation: memorize the IKC's portion of the Ritual and print and distribute the program for the term to the entire membership and Advisors.","First letter to the Executive Officer at the start of the term: printed program, a statement that the ritual work is memorized, and the intent to qualify.","During the term: all ritual work from memory, confer the investiture, at least **3 activities** centered on at least 2 of the categories **Social, DeMolay Service, and Masonic Service**, induct his pro-rata share of the membership goal set by the Executive Officer, be the first-line signer on at least one application, have all officers' chairs filled at each investiture, and report new Knights on eScribe within 10 days.","Second letter within **10 days** after the term ends: a complete recap, program analysis, and attendance report, countersigned by the Priory Advisor and the Advisory Council Chairman."]},{"t":"h","text":"What the Knighthood Pin Says"},{"t":"table","headers":["Element","Meaning"],"rows":[["Crown of Youth","A reminder of our stewardship — when it is laid aside for the Crown of Manhood, it should be brightly shining."],["Crossed Swords","Justice, fortitude, and mercy: DeMolay's unceasing warfare against arrogance, despotism, and intolerance."],["Five-Armed Cross","Purity of intentions and DeMolay International's motto: \"No DeMolay shall fail as a citizen, as a leader or as a man.\""],["Picture of DeMolay","His last known portrait."],["Ring of 10 rubies","Honors the Founder and the nine young men who originally formed the Order — all ten have answered the final summons."],["Branch of oak leaves (left)","Steadfastness and devotion to service."],["Branch of laurel (right)","Honor and victory, qualities of virtue worthy of all manhood."]]}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Court of Chevaliers: Perpetual Service","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"A **Court of Chevaliers** may be formed under the authorization of the Executive Officer, at either the Jurisdictional or Chapter level. Except for the Advisor, **every member must be a Chevalier** — and they should be active ones: men who participated in their last observance and completed the required observance report."},{"t":"p","text":"Its core function is to **confer the Degree of Chevalier** on those named by the Supreme Council through the Executive Officer, and to help in every area where DeMolay can be furthered. In receiving the degree, every Chevalier was obligated to **perpetual service** to DeMolay — and that should drive everything the Court does. It may also offer its services to the Jurisdictional Master Councilor so his program runs more effectively."},{"t":"list","items":["Officers the Court may elect: **Commander, Commander in the West, Commander in the South, Marshal, Chaplain, and Secretary**."]},{"t":"list","items":["Sponsor and maintain an annual Chapter Membership Contest or similar competition.","Conduct Installations when needed.","Aid in a Jurisdictional membership program.","Assist in judging ritual competitions or similar contests.","Promote a better understanding of the Order through presentations of history and ideals at the Chapter level.","Be active in expansion: new Chapters and increased membership.","Assist and encourage visitations among DeMolay Chapters."]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"A smart move: plan an annual observance and invite every Chevalier in the Jurisdiction — they meet their obligation and get better acquainted in one go."},{"t":"ref","text":"Court of Chevaliers and Legion of Honor in the Handbook","page":"178"}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Legion of Honor: Leadership That Gives Back","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The **Legion of Honor** bands together a selected few out of the millions who have knelt at the altar of DeMolay and gone on to demonstrate outstanding leadership in some field — civic, professional, fraternal, or spiritual. They are men the Order can rely on, year after year, to help young men carry DeMolay's ideals into every walk of life."},{"t":"p","text":"**Legionnaires** are united in **Preceptories**. All members of a Preceptory must be Legionnaires, either active or honorary; an active Legionnaire is one who observed last **March 18th** and completed the required observance report."},{"t":"list","items":["Officers the Preceptory may elect: **Dean, Vice-Dean, Secretary, Treasurer, Chaplain, and Sergeant-at-Arms**."]},{"t":"p","text":"Its function is to assist the Executive Officer in conferring the **Legion of Honor Degree** on those elected by the Supreme Council, and to help in any other way needed. For any activity in support of DeMolay, clearance must first be obtained from the Executive Officer. Some of those activities:"},{"t":"list","items":["Serve as Advisors where needed and help the Executive Officer find additional Advisors.","Aid in all Chapters' membership programs.","Be DeMolay ambassadors to Masonic bodies.","Stay informed and up to date on all DeMolay programs.","Help DeMolays find summer or regular employment.","Attend DeMolay meetings as often as possible.","Sponsor and encourage DeMolays to attend annual Leadership Conferences, and aid in planning a successful Conclave/Convention in the Jurisdiction."]},{"t":"steps","items":["Gather a group of interested Legion of Honor members.","Request authorization to organize from the Executive Officer, noting those interested in joining.","Once authorized, elect the officers.","Plan a program of activities.","Keep the Executive Officer informed of the Preceptory's activities and its officers."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"A Preceptory's meeting schedule must include the **annual observance on March 18th**, which may be celebrated with a program and dinner."}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"What is the age range for the Order of the Squires of the Round Table?","options":["7 to 9 years old","9 to 11 years old","10 to 12 years old","12 to 14 years old"],"correct":1,"explain":"Squires are between 9 and 11 years old; once they turn 12 they're eligible to join DeMolay, which is exactly what the Manor prepares them for."},{"q":"When were the Squires established, and when did DeMolay International formally adopt them?","options":["1985 and 2005","1990 and 2010","1995 and 2015","2000 and 2020"],"correct":2,"explain":"The Squires were established in 1995 in Vancouver, Washington, and formally adopted by DeMolay International in 2015."},{"q":"How many officers can a Manor have, and how many of them are elected?","options":["Up to 5, with 2 elected","Up to 7, with 3 elected","Up to 9, with 4 elected","Up to 11, with 4 elected"],"correct":1,"explain":"A Manor has up to 7 officers: the Master, Senior, and Junior Squires are elected; the other four are appointed. Terms run 6 months."},{"q":"Who makes up a Priory of the Order of Knighthood?","options":["Senior DeMolays of any age","Active DeMolays aged 17 to 21","Young Master Masons","Chevaliers named by the Supreme Council"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Knighthood program is composed of active DeMolays between 17 and 21 years of age, organized into Priories."},{"q":"How much of a Priory's program should be devoted to service?","options":["A quarter","A third","Exactly half","More than half"],"correct":3,"explain":"The Handbook recommends that over half of a Priory's program planning involve service — it's the heart of Knighthood."},{"q":"What is the Order of Ebon, and when was it approved?","options":["The first Knighthood degree, in 1946","An optional second degree, approved in 1973","An award for Advisors, created in 1948","The Squires' opening ceremony, from 1995"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Order of Ebon is an optional second degree of Knighthood, approved by the Supreme Council at its 1973 session."},{"q":"What is the central function of a Court of Chevaliers?","options":["Electing new Chevaliers by its own vote","Conferring the Degree of Chevalier on those named by the Supreme Council","Managing the sponsoring Chapter's funds","Awarding the Legion of Honor Degree"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Court confers the Degree of Chevalier on those named by the Supreme Council through the Executive Officer — it doesn't pick the honorees itself."},{"q":"Which date do Legion of Honor Legionnaires observe every year?","options":["January 10th","March 18th","October 27th","June 1st"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Legion of Honor's annual observance is March 18th; participating and completing the report is what keeps a Legionnaire active."}]},"premios":{"title":"Honors & Awards","subtitle":"Everything a DeMolay can earn — and the honors you don't apply for, you deserve.","minutes":11,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Honor vs. Award: the key difference","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay recognizes effort in two very different ways, and understanding the difference comes first:"},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Award","text":"You work for it and you may apply for it. Meet the requirements, request it, receive it. Examples: Merit Bars, Blue Honor Key."},{"title":"Honor","text":"Never applied for: it is conferred without the recipient's knowledge, by unanimous vote of the International Supreme Council at its annual session. Examples: Chevalier, Legion of Honor."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"Campaigning for an Honor — or finding out about the nomination — can kill it. For the Legion of Honor confidentiality is strict: if it breaks, the nominee is not considered."},{"t":"p","text":"At Chapter level, the **Awards Advisor** keeps the records of efforts, hours and service, and the final call on every Merit Bar belongs to the **Advisory Council**. The Awards Advisor's rule: requirements met to the letter, no lowering the bar."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"Merit Bars: the bar system","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"**Merit Bars** are DeMolay's most common awards: bars earned through concrete work in different categories. Colors show how many times you've earned the same category:"},{"t":"p","text":"**White** (1st) → **Red** (2nd) → **Blue** (3rd) → **Purple** (4th) → **Gold** (5th and last). You wear **one bar per category**: when you move up a color, you turn in the previous one."},{"t":"table","headers":["Category","Requirement"],"rows":[["Athletics","1 year participating / 6 games"],["Attendance","1 year of perfect attendance"],["Civic Service","10 hours / 3 projects"],["Conclave","Attend 3 conclaves"],["Fine Arts","3 musical performances or 2 plays"],["Fundraising","3 projects / 20 hours"],["Installing","3 installation ceremonies"],["Journalism","6 published articles"],["Masonic Attendance","Attend with 3 Master Masons (1 bar/year)"],["Masonic Service","3 projects / 10 hours"],["Membership","3 applications as first-line signer"],["Merit","20 hours of work"],["Patriotism","1 year (JROTC, ROTC, Civil Air Patrol, armed forces)"],["Religion","30 religious services in a year"],["Ritual","125 points on the ISC scale"],["Safe Driver","1 year without traffic violations"],["Scholastics","B average (or equivalent) for 1 school year"],["Visitation","6 visits to another Chapter/Manor or 150 miles"]]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"The **Leaders Correspondence Course** earns one bar per lesson, and completing all five courses qualifies you for the **Lamp of Knowledge** pin."},{"t":"ref","text":"Full Merit Bar table and requirements","page":"205"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"Membership & service awards","blocks":[{"t":"list","items":["**Founder's Membership Award (FMA)**: be first-line signer on **5 applications**. No charge.","**Blue Honor Key**: **10 applications** as first-line signer. A star is added for every additional 10. The recruiter's classic.","**White Honor Key**: recruit **3 new Advisors**, registered and appointed by the Executive Officer.","**Hats Off Award**: decided by the Chapter through a vote of its Active Members to thank anyone — it cannot be applied for and there is no limit.","**Officer's Service Certificate**: certifies a term served in an office; requires the Chapter Advisor's recommendation.","**Zerubbabel Key**: for helping start a Chapter — up to 3 per new or reinstated Chapter, awarded within one year of institution."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"If you don't reach the number before turning 21, you can complete the Blue Honor Key as a Senior DeMolay — as long as you hold your Senior DeMolay Certificate."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"The big leadership recognitions","blocks":[{"t":"list","items":["**Past Master Councilor's Jewel**: the only gift a Chapter may pay for with its funds, for an outstanding outgoing MC. Hard requirement: having conferred **both Degrees from memory** at least once during his term.","**PMC Meritorious Service Award (PMC-MSA)**: DeMolay International's gold medal, free of charge. Requires a letter of intent within 10 days of installation, a printed term program, **at least 4 inductions** (or the Executive Officer's quota, whichever is greater), one activity of each type (social, civic, Masonic service, athletic and fundraising) and public observance of every Obligatory Day in the term.","**Distinguished Service Award (DeMolay of the Year)**: since 1959; evaluates school, home, place of worship, community, country and DeMolay, with recommendation letters per area. Jurisdictional winners and a single international winner.","**Medal of Heroism**: created in 1925, requires having voluntarily risked your own life. Fewer than **50** awarded in a century.","**Medal of Valor**: for saving or attempting to save a life, without the self-risk requirement."]}]},{"id":"l5","title":"Representative DeMolay: your best self","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The **Representative DeMolay Award (RD)** is the highest **self-achievement** distinction: you compete against no one but yourself. Born in 1924 as a competition, since **1935** it has been a self-evaluation across **four fields of development**: mental, physical, socio-economic and spiritual."},{"t":"steps","items":["Have at least **6 months of membership** when you submit the form.","Complete the RD Evaluation Form carefully — neatness, spelling and grammar are graded too.","Get the signatures of the Chapter Advisor and the Advisory Council Chairman (or RD Advisor).","The form goes to the Executive Officer; once approved, you receive pin, riband, certificate and card at a public presentation."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The program's motto says it all: \"EVERY DEMOLAY IS A REPRESENTATIVE DEMOLAY!\""}]},{"id":"l6","title":"Chevalier, Legion of Honor and adult honors","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"**Chevalier** is the highest honor an active DeMolay can receive: it requires being **at least 17** (the Executive Officer may lower it to 16), **2 years** of membership in good standing, and a **unanimous vote** of the Supreme Council. Its traditional observance is **November 8** (the anniversary of Dad Land's death)."},{"t":"p","text":"**Legion of Honor** is the great honor for Senior DeMolays: nominees must be **over 25**, elected by unanimous ISC vote under absolute confidentiality. Its traditional observance is **March 18**. A fee on acceptance covers the cordon and medallion."},{"t":"list","items":["**Cross of Honor**: highest honor for Advisors — at least 3 years of conspicuous meritorious service, voted by the Supreme Council.","**Advisor's Honor Key**: only one per Chapter per year; requires the Annual Report on time, net membership growth and inductions equal to or better than the previous year.","**Guild of the Leather Apron**: the \"Advisor of the Year,\" at the Executive Officer's discretion.","**Medal of Appreciation**: for anyone — man or woman, no Masonic affiliation needed — with unusual service to the Chapter.","**Grand Cross**: up to 2 individuals per Grand Master's term."]},{"t":"ref","text":"Complete honors catalog by eligibility category","page":"207"}]},{"id":"l7","title":"The official pin and regalia","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"DeMolay's **official pin**, introduced in **1949** and designed by Dad Land himself, condenses the Order's identity. Only DeMolays, Senior DeMolays and Advisors may wear it."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"Crown of Youth","text":"The crown of youth, bearing the seven precepts."},{"title":"10 precious stones","text":"Dad Land and the 9 founders. Rubies for the deceased, pearls for the living — today all rubies."},{"title":"Helmet","text":"Chivalry."},{"title":"Crescent","text":"The secrecy of the Order."},{"title":"Five-armed white cross","text":"Purity, and the motto: \"No DeMolay shall fail as a citizen, as a leader, and as a man.\""},{"title":"Crossed swords","text":"Justice, fortitude and mercy; the war against arrogance, despotism and intolerance."}]},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"**ShopDeMolay.org** is the only authorized channel for DeMolay jewelry and regalia. There are also the **Majority Pin** (for Senior DeMolays) and the **Sweetheart Pin** (for sweethearts, mothers and sisters)."}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"What is the difference between an Honor and an Award in DeMolay?","options":["Honors are for adults, Awards for youth","An Award is earned and may be applied for; an Honor is conferred without the recipient knowing","The Chapter grants Honors and the Supreme Council grants Awards","They are synonyms"],"correct":1,"explain":"An Award is worked for and requested (like the Blue Honor Key); an Honor takes a unanimous ISC vote and is never applied for (like Chevalier)."},{"q":"What does the Blue Honor Key require?","options":["5 applications as first-line signer","Recruiting 3 advisors","10 applications as first-line signer","20 hours of service"],"correct":2,"explain":"The Blue Honor Key is earned with 10 applications as first-line signer, with a star for every additional 10."},{"q":"What is the Merit Bar color order?","options":["White → Red → Blue → Purple → Gold","Blue → White → Red → Gold → Purple","White → Blue → Red → Gold → Purple","Red → White → Blue → Purple → Gold"],"correct":0,"explain":"First bar White, then Red, Blue, Purple and Gold; after Gold there are no further awards in that category."},{"q":"What minimum age does the Chevalier honor require?","options":["21 years old","16, no exceptions","17 (the Executive Officer may lower it to 16)","25 years old"],"correct":2,"explain":"Chevalier requires age 17 (with a possible EO-authorized exception at 16) and 2 years of membership in good standing."},{"q":"When is the Legion of Honor's traditional observance?","options":["November 8","March 18","October 13","January 1"],"correct":1,"explain":"The Legion of Honor observes March 18; Chevalier observes November 8, the anniversary of Dad Land's death."},{"q":"What is the hard requirement for the PMC's Jewel?","options":["Having recruited 10 members","Having conferred both Degrees from memory at least once during his term","Having attended 3 conclaves","Holding a B average at school"],"correct":1,"explain":"The outgoing MC must have conferred the Initiatory and DeMolay Degrees from memory at least once during his term."},{"q":"What are the four fields of the Representative DeMolay?","options":["Academic, athletic, social and ritual","Mental, physical, socio-economic and spiritual","School, home, community and country","Leadership, service, brotherhood and faith"],"correct":1,"explain":"The RD is a self-evaluation across four fields of development: mental, physical, socio-economic and spiritual."},{"q":"What do the 10 stones on the official pin represent?","options":["The first 10 Chapters","The 10 precepts of DeMolay","Dad Land and the 9 original founders","The 10 years since founding"],"correct":2,"explain":"The ten stones honor Frank S. Land and the nine founding boys: rubies for the deceased, pearls for the living — today all rubies."}]},"fundar":{"title":"Starting or Reinstating a Chapter","subtitle":"The official 7-step procedure for bringing DeMolay where it isn't yet.","minutes":9,"lessons":[{"id":"l1","title":"Before you lift a finger","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"No Chapter in your community? Was there one that closed? Starting or reviving a Chapter is one of the greatest things you can do for DeMolay — but there is an official procedure, and it always starts in the same place."},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The **Executive Officer's** approval is **mandatory before any procedure begins**. He is DeMolay International's official representative in the Jurisdiction and usually works through personal representatives."},{"t":"cards","items":[{"title":"New Chapter","text":"Established where there has never been a Chapter, or where there has been none for at least 5 years."},{"title":"Reinstated Chapter","text":"Formed where a Chapter existed and operated within the previous 5 years."}]},{"t":"p","text":"Each Jurisdiction produces a **New Chapter Kit** with full details (the Executive Officer may add requirements of his own). Get it before you start — and visit other Chapters to see how they run."}]},{"id":"l2","title":"The 7 official steps","blocks":[{"t":"steps","items":["**The Sponsoring Body.** Secure an acceptable sponsor: (A) a chartered Masonic body — usually a Blue Lodge, also York Rite, Scottish Rite, Shrine or Grotto, and with EO approval even an Eastern Star Chapter or Amaranth Court; (B) a body composed exclusively of Freemasons; (C) an Advisory Council formed by the EO to act as sponsor; or (D) joint sponsorship by two or more groups. The sponsor passes a **Resolution of Sponsorship** and sends it to the EO with the fee.","**The Advisory Council.** The sponsor nominates at least **3 adults** (at least 3 Master Masons in good standing, all over 21). The Executive Officer appoints them — and may remove them — naming a **Chairman** (must be a Master Mason) and a **Chapter Advisor**. Before appointment, every Advisor completes the online training: application, background check, motor vehicle record check, and the DeMolay basics course with Youth Protection.","**Letters Temporary.** With the Council in place, the **Grand Master of DeMolay** orders the Letters Temporary issued: the provisional authority to elect the first members. The Chapter operates under them until it has **at least 15 Members** and shows the EO a high probability of success.","**The first members.** The Advisory Council votes on Applications (with minutes recording names and results). Age: past the 12th birthday and not yet 21. The star method: a public **Open House** for young men and their parents.","**The first meeting.** One or more visiting Chapters are needed to confer the Degrees. Invite the Sponsoring Body, parents and support groups. Initiates are reported in **eScribe** immediately — 10 days at most.","**The calendar.** New members MUST help build it. Ask the EO and other Chapters for sample Term Plans. A **public Installation** (ideally performed by another Chapter) introduces the Chapter to the community — and the 15-minute **Flower Talk** leaves a mark.","**Keep growing.** Not just in numbers: in the relationships between youth and Advisors, with the community and with supporting organizations."]},{"t":"ref","text":"The full procedure with all the forms","page":"247"}]},{"id":"l3","title":"What nobody tells you (but the handbook does)","blocks":[{"t":"callout","style":"warn","text":"**There is no \"Chapter in a Box.\"** DeMolay International provides training, materials and support — but it cannot ship ready-made Advisors or a group of boys who show up knowing the ritual."},{"t":"p","text":"What a successful start really takes: adults willing to give **time, talent and treasure**. Experience shows the most common cause of failure is adults who underestimated the commitment of mentoring."},{"t":"list","items":["**Dedication** — being present FOR the young men, not just in the building.","**Patience** — the first meetings are more about organizing chaos than memorizing ritual.","**Communication** — with the EO, the sponsor, parents and among Advisors.","**Willingness to try again** — always."]},{"t":"p","text":"When choosing where to start, look at the numbers: local population (typically **5,000 or more**), school population aged 12 to 18, and the factors limiting it. And make it clear in public: DeMolay is **not** limited to Masons' sons or relatives, and the joining ceremony contains **no hazing and no violence** of any kind."}]},{"id":"l4","title":"Bylaws, supplies and reinstatement","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"Every Chapter adopts **uniform bylaws** per the Bylaws of DeMolay International, approved by the Executive Officer. And to run properly it needs its **essential supplies**:"},{"t":"list","items":["10 to 15 **Rituals of Secret Work**","5 **Monitors of Ceremonies** (downloadable from the DeMolay website)","**Crown of Youth**, **Bible and School Books**, **Altar Cloth**","**Gavels**, **Ballot Box**, **Bell**, **Preceptor Stand Cloths**","7 **Candle Stands** (real or electric candles, per local rules)"]},{"t":"p","text":"**Reinstating?** The procedure mirrors a new Chapter's, but with a **reinstatement application** instead of the petition for Letters Temporary. If the Chapter was closed **less than 5 years** and is reinstated under the **same name and in the same area**, it pays only the basic supplies fee; if the name or location changes — or more than 5 years passed — it follows the new-Chapter path and fees."},{"t":"callout","style":"info","text":"Before reviving a Chapter, find out why the previous one closed. That history is your best map of what not to repeat."}]},{"id":"l5","title":"The official check-off list","blocks":[{"t":"p","text":"The handbook closes with a **17-step** check-off list, from talking to the Executive Officer to operating the Chapter under its bylaws. The key documentary milestones:"},{"t":"list","items":["Three documents travel together to the EO: the **Resolution to Sponsor**, the **Advisory Council Certification** and the **Petition for Letters Temporary** — plus the fee check.","If the EO approves, he forwards the papers to DeMolay International himself.","Before the recruiting event: set the Chapter's **membership fee**.","After the first class: report the new Members online, install the first officers and adopt the bylaws."]},{"t":"callout","style":"key","text":"The interactive version of the 17 steps lives in **Reference → Procedures**, so you can check items off as you go. Your progress is saved."},{"t":"ref","text":"Complete check-off list for organizing a new Chapter","page":"254"}]}],"quiz":[{"q":"What is required BEFORE starting any procedure to found a Chapter?","options":["Having 15 committed members","Buying the supplies","The Jurisdiction's Executive Officer's approval","A willing Blue Lodge"],"correct":2,"explain":"Nothing starts without the Executive Officer's approval — he is DeMolay International's official representative in the Jurisdiction."},{"q":"When is a Chapter considered \"new\" rather than \"reinstated\"?","options":["When there was never a Chapter, or none for at least 5 years","When the previous one closed 2 years ago","When the Sponsoring Body changes","When it has fewer than 15 members"],"correct":0,"explain":"New Chapter: a community that never had one or has had none for at least 5 years. Reinstated: one operated within the previous 5 years."},{"q":"Who orders the issuance of the Letters Temporary?","options":["The Executive Officer","The Sponsoring Body","The Grand Master of DeMolay","The Advisory Council"],"correct":2,"explain":"Once the Resolution of Sponsorship and the Advisory Council are complete, the Grand Master of DeMolay orders the Letters Temporary issued."},{"q":"How long does a Chapter operate under Letters Temporary?","options":["Until 6 months pass","Until it has at least 15 Members and shows a high probability of success","Until the first Installation","Until it adopts its bylaws"],"correct":1,"explain":"Letters Temporary govern until the Chapter reaches at least 15 Members and demonstrates a high probability of success to the EO."},{"q":"What is the minimum for the initial Advisory Council?","options":["5 adults, all Masons","3 adults, with at least 3 Master Masons in good standing","2 registered Advisors","10 community adults"],"correct":1,"explain":"The sponsor nominates at least 3 adults (no maximum); at least 3 must be Master Masons in good standing, all over 21."},{"q":"How soon must initiates be reported in eScribe?","options":["30 days","Immediately, and never more than 10 days","One week","At the end of the term"],"correct":1,"explain":"New members are reported to DeMolay International via eScribe immediately — within 10 days of initiation at most."},{"q":"What rule governs Chapter names?","options":["They must use the city name, no exceptions","They cannot bear the name of a living person","They must honor a local Mason","DeMolay International assigns them"],"correct":1,"explain":"No Chapter may be named after a living person; the usual choice is the city or area, or distinguished deceased figures."},{"q":"How many steps does the official check-off list have?","options":["7","12","17","21"],"correct":2,"explain":"The handbook's check-off list (p. 254) has 17 steps, from first contact with the EO to operating under the Chapter's own bylaws."}]}},"reference":{"glossary":[{"term":"Active DeMolay","def":"A member in activity, from initiation until age 21. Membership is for life: afterwards he becomes a Senior DeMolay.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Advisory Council","def":"The certified adult body overseeing the Chapter: minimum 5 advisors, with at least 3 Master Masons in good standing. Appointed by the Executive Officer.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Almoner","def":"Appointed officer in charge of the Chapter's charity; responsible for the Day of Comfort.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Ambassador (The)","def":"DeMolay International's official newsletter: information, inspiration and unification. Every Chapter should have a reporter.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Annual Report","def":"The Chapter's yearly report, prepared in January by the Scribe and the Chairman via eScribe. The Grand Secretary's only source of information.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Appendant Bodies","def":"DeMolay's allied bodies: Squires (ages 9-11), Order of Knighthood (17-21), Court of Chevaliers and Preceptories of the Legion of Honor.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Award","def":"Recognition earned by meeting requirements and which may be applied for (unlike an Honor). Examples: Merit Bars, Blue Honor Key.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Ballot","def":"The secret vote with white balls and black cubes: 0-1 black cube elects, 2 makes the application lie over, 3 or more reject it.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Big Brother","def":"An older member assigned by the Master Councilor to guide each new member through orientation.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Blue Honor Key","def":"Recruiting award: 10 Membership Applications as first-line signer; a star for every additional 10.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Bylaws","def":"The Chapter's rules, uniform per the Bylaws of DeMolay International and approved by the Executive Officer. The Scribe keeps the original.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Ceremony of Light","def":"Public ceremony with seven candles representing the seven cardinal virtues. Zero deviation from the official text allowed.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Chaplain","def":"Appointed officer who leads the Chapter's prayers; responsible for Devotional Day.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Chapter","def":"DeMolay's local unit: young men aged 12 to 21 led by their own officers and advised by an Advisory Council.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Chapter Advisor","def":"The Chapter's lead adult mentor, appointed by the Executive Officer. Chooses the Word of the Day and signs obligation cards.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Charter","def":"A Chapter's permanent constitutive document, earned after operating successfully under Letters Temporary (at least 15 members).","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Chevalier","def":"The highest honor for an active DeMolay: age 17+, 2 years of membership, unanimous ISC vote. Never applied for. Observance: November 8.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Conclave","def":"A Jurisdiction's annual convention: ritual competitions, sports, elections and brotherhood.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Court of Chevaliers","def":"A body composed only of Chevaliers that confers the Degree of Chevalier on those named by the Supreme Council.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Cross of Honor","def":"The highest honor for Advisors: at least 3 years of conspicuous meritorious service, voted by the Supreme Council.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Crown of Youth","def":"The crown of youth: the central symbol of the DeMolay emblem and a required ritual item in the Chapter room.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Day of Comfort","def":"The Obligatory Day of charity: between November 15 and December 31, led by the Almoner.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"DeMolay Degree","def":"DeMolay's second degree: the drama of Jacques DeMolay's loyalty. Conferred from memory, ideally on a stage.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"DeMolay International","def":"The worldwide organization, headquartered at the Service & Leadership Center in Kansas City, governed by the International Supreme Council.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"DeMolay Week","def":"The celebration week including March 18, with an official proclamation and ideally one event per day.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Devotional Day","def":"The religious Obligatory Day in the week of March 18 (anniversary of Jacques DeMolay's martyrdom), led by the Chaplain.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Distinguished Service Award","def":"The \"DeMolay of the Year\": evaluates school, home, worship, community, country and DeMolay. Jurisdictional winners and one international.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Educational Day","def":"The Obligatory Day of education, usually in September, led by the Junior and Senior Stewards.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"eScribe","def":"DeMolay International's online portal for reporting members, awards, certificates and the Annual Report. Unreported members aren't registered.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Executive Officer (EO)","def":"DeMolay International's official representative in a Jurisdiction. His approval is needed for almost everything: Chapters, advisors, bylaws, outside fundraising.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"First-line signer","def":"The first recommender signing a Membership Application. What counts toward the Blue Honor Key and the FMA.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Flower Talk","def":"A ~15-minute public ceremony about a mother's love: red and white flowers (white for a deceased mother). From memory; not part of the degree.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Founder's Membership Award (FMA)","def":"Award for being first-line signer on 5 Membership Applications. No charge.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Frank S. Land","def":"\"Dad\" Land (1890-1959), DeMolay's Founder and Secretary-General from 1919 until his death on November 8, 1959.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Grand Master","def":"DeMolay International's highest authority, elected annually by the International Supreme Council.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Hats Off Award","def":"Recognition the Chapter votes to thank anyone. Cannot be applied for and has no limit.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Honor","def":"Recognition that is NEVER applied for: conferred without the recipient's knowledge by unanimous ISC vote (Chevalier, Legion of Honor).","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Initiatory Degree","def":"DeMolay's first degree: teaches the seven virtues. Conferred with sincerity, no dramatics, always from memory.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"International Supreme Council (ISC)","def":"DeMolay International's governing body of adult Masons. Born as the Grand Council in 1921; current name since 1954.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Jacques DeMolay","def":"Last Grand Master of the Knights Templar (1244-1314), burned at the stake on March 18, 1314, for refusing to betray his companions.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Jurisdiction","def":"DeMolay's administrative territory (state, province or country) under an Executive Officer.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Lamp of Knowledge","def":"The pin earned by completing all five Leaders Correspondence Course lessons.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Leaders Correspondence Course (LCC)","def":"The online leadership course at BeADeMolay.org/lcc: 5 lessons, free, 24/7. Each lesson earns a Merit Bar.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Legion of Honor","def":"The great honor for Senior DeMolays over 25: unanimous ISC vote under strict confidentiality. Observance: March 18.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Letters Temporary","def":"A new Chapter's provisional authority, issued by order of the Grand Master, until it reaches 15 members and earns its Charter.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Life Membership","def":"The prepaid lifetime membership included in the initiation fee. Each Life Membership plan requires the Executive Officer's approval.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Majority / Majority Service","def":"Becoming a Senior DeMolay at 21, and the ceremony celebrating it. The certificate is created in eScribe.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Manor","def":"The local unit of the Squires of the Round Table, sponsored by an Advisory Council or a Jurisdiction.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Marshal","def":"Appointed officer who conducts floor movements and helps tabulate votes; co-responsible for My Government Day.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Master Councilor (MC)","def":"The Chapter's president, elected by the members. Presides from the East, appoints committees and builds the term program.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Medal of Heroism","def":"Honor for voluntarily risking one's own life. Created in 1925; fewer than 50 awarded since.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Membership Application","def":"The formal joining request, with parent/guardian consent. Presented at a stated meeting at least 1 week before the ballot.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Merit Bars","def":"The most common awards: bars per work category (White → Red → Blue → Purple → Gold). The Advisory Council has the final say.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Monitor of Ceremonies","def":"The Chapter's public-ceremony manual, downloadable from the DeMolay website.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Mother Chapter","def":"The original Kansas City Chapter, founded in 1919; holder of Charter No. 1.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"My Government Day","def":"July's civic Obligatory Day, led by the Orator and the Marshal.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Nine O'clock Interpolation","def":"A brief ceremony required at EVERY DeMolay meeting, public or private: at nine o'clock, the remembrance of mothers and fathers.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Obligation","def":"Each degree's ritual commitment. Memorizing both Obligations is the proficiency requirement for voting and holding office.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Obligation Card","def":"The card signed by the Chapter Advisor proving your approved Obligations. Without it you cannot vote or hold office.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Obligatory Days","def":"The seven mandatory yearly observances: Devotional, Patriots', Parents', My Government, Educational, Frank S. Land Memorial and Day of Comfort.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Order of Knighthood","def":"The appendant body for active DeMolays aged 17 to 21, organized in Priories. Over half its program must be service.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Orientation","def":"The 3-session program guiding a new member from his application until he recites the DeMolay Degree Obligation.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Parents' Day","def":"The parents' Obligatory Day, between May 1 and June 21, led by the seven Preceptors.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Patent","def":"The official membership certificate, issued by the Service & Leadership Center once both Degrees are reported and paid.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Patriots' Day","def":"February's patriotic Obligatory Day, led by the Standard Bearer.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"PMC's Jewel","def":"The jewel for an outstanding Past Master Councilor: the only gift a Chapter may pay for. Requires both Degrees conferred from memory.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"PMC-MSA","def":"The Past Master Councilor's Meritorious Service Award: DI's gold medal for an outstanding term as MC, with strict requirements.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Preceptor","def":"Each of the seven officers representing the cardinal virtues with their candles. Responsible for Parents' Day.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Priory","def":"The local unit of the Order of Knighthood, led by the Illustrious Knight Commander.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Proficiency","def":"The examination on both degrees' Obligations, conducted by the Senior Deacon in open Chapter and decided by Chapter vote.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Representative DeMolay (RD)","def":"The highest self-achievement distinction: a self-evaluation across 4 fields (mental, physical, socio-economic, spiritual). Since 1935.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Ritual","def":"DeMolay's ceremonial text, written by Frank A. Marshall in 1919. All degree work is delivered from memory, with no deviation.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Ritual of Secret Work","def":"The Chapter's reserved ritual book. It is DeMolay International's property and must be returned on demand.","cat":"documento"},{"term":"Scribe","def":"The Chapter's secretary, appointed by the Advisory Council: minutes, eScribe, reports and the Annual Report. The third most important office.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Senior DeMolay","def":"Any DeMolay who has turned 21. Membership is for life: he may return as an Advisor or join the Alumni Association.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Sentinel","def":"The keeper of the Chapter door: receives the Word of the Day and admits no one during the opening.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Service & Leadership Center","def":"DeMolay International's headquarters in Kansas City (the Henry E. \"Hank\" Stickney Center): records, service, promotion and unification.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Seven Cardinal Virtues","def":"The seven core values: love of parents, reverence, courtesy, comradeship, fidelity, cleanness and patriotism.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Sponsoring Body","def":"The organization (usually Masonic) sponsoring the Chapter: it provides a meeting place and sustains its Advisory Council.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Squires of the Round Table","def":"The program for boys aged 9 to 11, organized in Manors. Established in 1995 and adopted by DeMolay International in 2015.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Standard Bearer","def":"The officer who carries the flag; responsible for Patriots' Day.","cat":"cargo"},{"term":"Stated meeting","def":"The Chapter's regular business meeting, fixed in its Bylaws.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Sweetheart","def":"The young woman chosen as the Chapter's representative and companion of honor, traditionally crowned at a ball.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Two-Deep Leadership","def":"Youth Protection's golden rule: at least 2 registered Advisors present at every activity, no exceptions.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"White Honor Key","def":"Award for recruiting 3 new registered Advisors; stars for every additional 3.","cat":"premio"},{"term":"Word of the Day","def":"The meeting password, chosen by the Chapter Advisor and given to the Sentinel.","cat":"ceremonia"},{"term":"Youth Protection","def":"DeMolay's youth protection program: Two-Deep Leadership, Rule of Four, supervision ratios, hazing prohibition and mandatory reporting.","cat":"organizacion"},{"term":"Zerubbabel Key","def":"Award for helping found a Chapter: up to 3 per new Chapter, granted within a year of institution.","cat":"premio"}],"awards":{"items":[{"id":"merit-bars","name":"Merit Bars","type":"award","eligible":["active"],"req":"Per work category (Athletics, Civic Service, Fundraising, Membership, Ritual, etc.), each with its numeric requirement — e.g. Civic Service: 10 hrs/3 projects; Membership: 3 applications as first-line signer; Ritual: 125 points. Colors by repetition: White → Red → Blue → Purple → Gold.","cost":"Purchased at ShopDeMolay (the Membership bar comes from DI)","by":"Advisory Council (final say)","notes":"One bar worn per category; moving up a color means turning in the previous one."},{"id":"lamp-of-knowledge","name":"Lamp of Knowledge","type":"award","eligible":["active"],"req":"Complete all five Leaders Correspondence Course lessons (BeADeMolay.org/lcc). Each lesson also earns a Merit Bar.","cost":"Pin purchased at ShopDeMolay","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"Show the LCC certificate to the Awards Advisor to order each bar."},{"id":"fma","name":"Founder's Membership Award (FMA)","type":"award","eligible":["active","senior"],"req":"Be first-line signer on 5 Membership Applications.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"Senior DeMolays eligible with a Majority Certificate."},{"id":"blue-honor-key","name":"Blue Honor Key","type":"award","eligible":["active","senior"],"req":"Be first-line signer on 10 Membership Applications. A star for every additional 10.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"If you fall short before 21, you may finish it as a Senior DeMolay with your certificate."},{"id":"white-honor-key","name":"White Honor Key","type":"award","eligible":["active","senior","advisor","mason"],"req":"Recruit 3 new Advisors, registered and appointed by the Executive Officer. Stars for each multiple of 3.","cost":"No charge","by":"Supreme Council","notes":""},{"id":"green-honor-key","name":"Green Honor Key","type":"award","eligible":["priory","senior"],"req":"Be first-line signer on 10 Priory applications. Stars for each multiple of 10.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"For active Priory members or Senior Knights with a certificate."},{"id":"pink-honor-key","name":"Pink Honor Key","type":"award","eligible":["anyone"],"req":"Recruiting done by women (young or adult); policies and multiples set by the Executive Officer.","cost":"Per Jurisdiction","by":"Executive Officer","notes":""},{"id":"hats-off","name":"Hats Off Award","type":"award","eligible":["anyone"],"req":"Service to the Chapter that the Active Members choose to recognize by election. Cannot be applied for.","cost":"Pin + card + certificate (paid by the Chapter)","by":"The Chapter (Active Members' vote)","notes":"No limit; the Chapter is the sole judge."},{"id":"officers-cert","name":"Officer's Service Certificate","type":"award","eligible":["active"],"req":"Having served a term in a Chapter office, with the Chapter Advisor's recommendation.","cost":"Ordered via the Scribe from the Service & Leadership Center","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"States office, term, year and Chapter."},{"id":"zerubbabel-key","name":"Zerubbabel Key","type":"award","eligible":["active","senior","advisor","mason"],"req":"Decisive work in founding or reinstating a Chapter. Up to 3 per Chapter, within a year of institution.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International, with the Executive Officer's approval","notes":""},{"id":"medal-heroism","name":"Medal of Heroism","type":"honor","eligible":["active"],"req":"Voluntarily risking one's own life or performing a heroic act of sacrifice.","cost":"No charge","by":"Supreme Council","notes":"Created in 1925; fewer than 50 awarded. Nomination: Advisory Council → Executive Officer → Grand Secretary."},{"id":"medal-valor","name":"Medal of Valor","type":"honor","eligible":["active"],"req":"Saving or attempting to save a life (without the self-risk requirement).","cost":"No charge","by":"Supreme Council","notes":"Same nomination path as the Medal of Heroism."},{"id":"pmc-jewel","name":"Past Master Councilor's Jewel","type":"award","eligible":["active"],"req":"An outstanding, blameless term as Master Councilor + having conferred both Degrees FROM MEMORY at least once during the term + one initiation in the term.","cost":"Paid by the Chapter (the sole exception to the gift rule)","by":"The Chapter, with Advisory Council approval","notes":"Military exception: an MC called to armed service is considered in full compliance."},{"id":"pmc-msa","name":"PMC Meritorious Service Award (PMC-MSA)","type":"award","eligible":["active"],"req":"Letter of intent within 10 days of installation; printed, distributed program; at least 4 inductions (or the EO's quota, whichever is greater); 1 social + 1 civic + 1 Masonic service + 1 athletic + 1 fundraising activity; public observance of every Obligatory Day; final recap letter.","cost":"No charge (gold medal)","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"Only for service as Master Councilor."},{"id":"dsa","name":"Distinguished Service Award (DeMolay of the Year)","type":"honor","eligible":["active"],"req":"Excellence in 6 areas: school, home, place of worship, community, country and DeMolay, with recommendation letters from adult leaders (one per area).","cost":"No charge","by":"Executive Officer (jurisdictional) / DeMolay International (international)","notes":"Established in 1959. Up to 2 actives per year per Jurisdiction; leads to DeMolay International Member of the Year."},{"id":"rd-award","name":"Representative DeMolay Award (RD)","type":"award","eligible":["active","senior"],"req":"Self-evaluation across 4 fields (mental, physical, socio-economic, spiritual) with at least 6 months of membership; form signed by the Chapter Advisor and the Chairman (or RD Advisor).","cost":"No charge","by":"Executive Officer","notes":"\"EVERY DEMOLAY IS A REPRESENTATIVE DEMOLAY!\" — the highest self-achievement distinction. Seniors eligible with certificate and activity."},{"id":"chevalier","name":"Chevalier","type":"honor","eligible":["active","senior"],"req":"Age 17 (the EO may authorize 16) + 2 years of active membership in good standing + unanimous Supreme Council vote. Posthumous election possible within 12 months.","cost":"Patent and cordon at cost; ring optional","by":"International Supreme Council","notes":"The highest honor for an active DeMolay. Annual observance: November 8. Cannot be applied for."},{"id":"squire-honor","name":"Squire Honor Award","type":"award","eligible":["squire"],"req":"Proficiency in the Squire obligation + 6 Manor meetings + 2 social functions + 2 Squire Applications as first-line signer + 2 community service events.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"Retroactive to 2015 (creation of Class 9 membership)."},{"id":"ms-msa","name":"Master Squire's Meritorious Service Award","type":"award","eligible":["squire"],"req":"Letter of intent with an approved plan; Manor ritual from memory; confer one induction; conduct 3 meetings; induct 3 new members; 1 social + 1 with another DeMolay entity + 1 community event (separate); final letter within 10 days.","cost":"No charge","by":"International Supreme Council","notes":"Certification countersigned by the Squire Mentor and the Manor Advisor."},{"id":"pikc-msa","name":"Past Illustrious Knight Commander's MSA","type":"award","eligible":["priory"],"req":"Five stages mirroring the Master Squire's: letters, ritual, at least 3 activities across 2+ categories (Social, DeMolay Service, Masonic Service), the EO's membership quota, first-line signer on 1+ application, full officer chairs at every investiture, eScribe within 10 days.","cost":"No charge","by":"International Supreme Council","notes":"Certification countersigned by the Priory Advisor and the Advisory Council Chairman."},{"id":"legion-honor","name":"Legion of Honor","type":"honor","eligible":["senior","mason"],"req":"Over 25 by the first day of the annual session + unanimous International Supreme Council vote. Strict confidentiality: if broken, the nominee is not considered.","cost":"Fee on acceptance (covers cordon and medallion); ring optional","by":"International Supreme Council","notes":"Annual observance: March 18. Online nomination via eScribe with Advisory Council vote and EO approval."},{"id":"honorary-loh","name":"Honorary Legion of Honor","type":"honor","eligible":["mason"],"req":"A Master Mason over 30 with outstanding service to youth; no self-nomination; annual deadlines in eScribe.","cost":"Fee on acceptance","by":"International Supreme Council","notes":"For Masons who were not DeMolays."},{"id":"anniversary","name":"Senior DeMolay Anniversary Awards","type":"award","eligible":["senior"],"req":"Pins for induction anniversaries: 10, 25, 50, 60, 65, 70 and 75 years.","cost":"Pin at cost (the 50-year pin is purchased from the Service & Leadership Center)","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"Best presented at public Chapter events."},{"id":"medal-appreciation","name":"Medal of Appreciation","type":"award","eligible":["anyone"],"req":"Unusual service to the Chapter by anyone over 21, man or woman, no Masonic affiliation needed.","cost":"Paid by the Chapter","by":"Executive Officer (approval)","notes":""},{"id":"advisors-honor-key","name":"Advisor's Honor Key","type":"award","eligible":["advisor"],"req":"4 yearly requirements: Annual Report on time via eScribe + net membership above the prior year + inductions equal or better + recommendation form via eScribe.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International","notes":"Only one per Chapter per DeMolay year; stars for successive keys. Most common cause of loss: a late Annual Report."},{"id":"cross-honor","name":"Cross of Honor","type":"honor","eligible":["advisor"],"req":"At least 3 years of conspicuous meritorious service as an Advisor + Supreme Council vote at the annual session.","cost":"No charge","by":"International Supreme Council","notes":"The highest honor for Advisors. Never applied for."},{"id":"advisors-cert","name":"Advisor's Service Certificate","type":"award","eligible":["advisor"],"req":"From 10 years of service as an Advisor, then in 5-year increments.","cost":"No charge","by":"DeMolay International","notes":""},{"id":"guild-leather-apron","name":"Guild of the Leather Apron","type":"honor","eligible":["advisor"],"req":"Being the Jurisdiction's \"Advisor of the Year,\" at the Executive Officer's discretion.","cost":"No charge","by":"Executive Officer","notes":""},{"id":"founders-cross","name":"Founder's Cross","type":"honor","eligible":["anyone"],"req":"Officially retired: only 135 were personally presented by Dad Land before his death (November 8, 1959).","cost":"—","by":"Frank S. Land (historic)","notes":"Established June 1937. Today a piece of DeMolay history."},{"id":"grand-cross","name":"Grand Cross","type":"honor","eligible":["anyone"],"req":"Extraordinary service to DeMolay; up to 2 individuals per Grand Master's term.","cost":"No charge","by":"The Grand Master of DeMolay International","notes":"Past Grand Masters are ex-officio holders."}]},"offices":{"groups":[{"name":"Elected by the members","items":[{"name":"Master Councilor","duties":["Presides over the Chapter from the East and runs every meeting","Builds his term program: degree dates, at least 1 social, 1 civic and 1 fundraising activity, visitations and Obligatory Days","Appoints every committee (minimum 3 members; the first named is chairman) and is an ex-officio, non-voting member of all of them","Must achieve at least one initiation per term, and is the only one who may read an application and investigation report in a meeting","Calls special meetings when needed"],"notes":"Requirement: prior service as Senior or Junior Councilor (exceptions via the Advisory Council or in a new Chapter). When absent, the next officer in rank presides."},{"name":"Senior Councilor","duties":["Second in command, from the West; presides in the MC's absence and automatically moves up if the office becomes vacant","Oversees half of the Chapter's committees","The handbook's suggested special duty: member attendance","His mission in one phrase: lighten the MC's workload"]},{"name":"Junior Councilor","duties":["Third in line, from the South","His only duty defined in the Bylaws: coaching new members for their Obligation certifications","Suggested duty: running new-member orientation — neglecting it breeds inactivity within a year","Oversees the other half of the committees"]}]},{"name":"Appointed by the Advisory Council","items":[{"name":"Scribe","duties":["Keeps the minutes of every meeting (full motions, with mover and seconder; no jokes, no opinions)","Reports EVERYTHING in eScribe: initiates (10 days max), awards, Chapter data — unreported members don't officially exist","Prepares the Annual Report with the Advisory Council Chairman (January)","Collects fees and hands them immediately to the Treasurer against a receipt","Inventories Chapter property at least once a year"],"notes":"May be an active DeMolay, a Senior DeMolay or an Advisor; typical 1-year (calendar) term. The handbook calls it the third most important position: \"So goes the Scribe, so goes the Chapter.\""},{"name":"Treasurer","duties":["Guards the funds: the Chapter account kept separate from DeMolay International funds (which are untouchable)","Receives money from the Scribe and issues a receipt","Checks: his signature or the MC's + countersignature of an Advisory Council member; cash payments prohibited","Monthly report to the Advisory Council and an annual report at the year's last meeting"],"notes":"Must be a legal adult and an Advisory Council member. Term: January 1 to December 31."}]},{"name":"Appointed by the Master Councilor","items":[{"name":"Senior Deacon","duties":["Examines each voter's obligation card during ballots, standing between the altar and the SC's station","Conducts new members' proficiency examinations","Assists in conducting candidates during the degrees"]},{"name":"Junior Deacon","duties":["Assists at the Chapter door","Relieves the Sentinel during ballots so he can vote"]},{"name":"Senior Steward & Junior Steward","duties":["Prepare the candidates for the degrees","Responsible for planning Educational Day (September)"]},{"name":"Chaplain","duties":["Leads the Chapter's prayers (members kneeling on the left knee; everyone answers \"Amen\")","Responsible for Devotional Day (the week of March 18)"]},{"name":"Almoner","duties":["The Chapter's officer of charity","Responsible for the DeMolay Day of Comfort (November 15 to December 31)"]},{"name":"Marshal","duties":["Conducts floor movements and presentations","Assists in tabulating votes at elections","Co-responsible for My Government Day (July)"]},{"name":"Standard Bearer","duties":["Carries and honors the national flag","Responsible for Patriots' Day (February)"]},{"name":"Orator","duties":["Delivers the orations the Ritual assigns him","Co-responsible for My Government Day (July)"]},{"name":"The seven Preceptors","duties":["Represent the seven cardinal virtues, each with his candle","Many Chapters assign them the room setup (property committee)","Responsible for Parents' Day (May 1 to June 21)"]},{"name":"Sentinel","duties":["Guards the Chapter door","Receives the Word of the Day from the Chapter Advisor before the meeting","Admits no one while the Chapter is opening in either degree"]},{"name":"Organist","duties":["Provides the Chapter's music","The Ritual of Secret Work marks the places for music in the Initiatory Degree"]}]},{"name":"Key adult roles","items":[{"name":"Advisory Council Chairman","duties":["Must be a Master Mason; the Executive Officer's primary contact with the Council","Prepares the Annual Report in eScribe with the Chapter Advisor, Treasurer and Scribe","Responsible for the Advisors' ongoing training","Gives the oral notification to the Masonic body if an incident occurs on Masonic property"]},{"name":"Chapter Advisor","duties":["The Chapter's lead mentor for its young officers","Chooses the Word of the Day and passes it to the Sentinel","Signs the obligation cards (with the Chapter seal)","Plans the program with the MC: 1 year in general, 1 term in detail"],"notes":"The handbook recommends rotating the role every 1-2 years to avoid burnout and the \"one-person Chapter.\""}]}]},"calendar":{"obligatory":[{"name":"Devotional Day","when":"The week including March 18","responsible":"Chapter Chaplain","ideas":"Group attendance at a religious service in memory of Jacques DeMolay; many Chapters observe it on the Sunday nearest the 18th."},{"name":"Patriots' Day","when":"A convenient day in February","responsible":"Standard Bearer","ideas":"Honor patriots and the flag: a civic ceremony, a memorial visit, inviting veterans."},{"name":"Parents' Day","when":"Between May 1 and June 21","responsible":"The seven Preceptors","ideas":"A banquet or gathering with parents as guests of honor; the Flower Talk fits this date perfectly."},{"name":"My Government Day","when":"A convenient day in July","responsible":"Orator and Marshal","ideas":"Visit city hall or the legislature, host an official, run a youth mock government."},{"name":"Educational Day","when":"Usually in September","responsible":"Junior and Senior Stewards","ideas":"Recognize teachers and schools; a career guidance talk or an educational visit."},{"name":"Frank S. Land Memorial Day","when":"A day near November 8","responsible":"The Chapter (no assigned officer)","ideas":"Honor the Founder; a fundraiser for a DeMolay charity is encouraged."},{"name":"DeMolay Day of Comfort","when":"Between November 15 and December 31","responsible":"Almoner","ideas":"Bring comfort where it is needed: hospital or care home visits, donations, supporting families."}],"annual":[{"month":"January","items":["Scribe and Chairman prepare and file the **Annual Report** (the Grand Secretary's only source of information)","Treasurer's annual financial report","Create **Senior DeMolay Certificates** for members turning 21","Installation of officers for the new term (typical model)"]},{"month":"February","items":["**Patriots' Day** (Standard Bearer)","Valentine Ball: election and coronation of the Chapter Sweetheart (typical tradition)"]},{"month":"March","items":["**DeMolay Week**: the week of March 18, with a mayoral proclamation and one event per day","**Devotional Day** (Sunday nearest the 18th)","Founder's Day Class: an initiation honoring Frank S. Land","Legion of Honor observance (March 18)"]},{"month":"April","items":["**IRS Form 990** reminder (US Chapters only)","Planning for the mid-year term"]},{"month":"May","items":["Complete and file IRS Form 990 (US)","**Parents' Day** window opens (May 1 to June 21)"]},{"month":"June","items":["Parents' Day window closes (June 21)","Installation of officers for the new term (model)","Outdoor initiation (typical tradition)"]},{"month":"July","items":["**My Government Day** (Orator and Marshal)","DeMolay Leadership Conference / summer camps (per Jurisdiction)"]},{"month":"August","items":["**Jurisdictional Conclave** (typical model)","Prepare the back-to-school membership campaign"]},{"month":"September","items":["**Educational Day** (Junior and Senior Stewards)","Fall initiation (model)"]},{"month":"October","items":["Order the year's awards: **Merit Bars, Blue Honor Key, White Honor Key, Scribe's Efficiency Certificate**","Send Frank S. Land Memorial Day notices"]},{"month":"November","items":["**Frank S. Land Memorial Day** (near November 8) — Chevalier observance","**Day of Comfort** begins (November 15)","Annual Advisor recertification deadline: **November 30**","Jurisdictional winter sports tournament (model)"]},{"month":"December","items":["**Day of Comfort** (through December 31)","Chapter property inventory for the Advisory Council","Verify ALL of the year's new Members are reported in eScribe","Caroling or another joint activity with Job's Daughters and Rainbow (typical tradition)","Fiscal year ends (December 31)"]}]},"procedures":{"items":[{"id":"elegir-miembro","title":"Electing a new member","intro":"The full path from application to vote, per the Bylaws.","steps":["Check eligibility: a young man past his 12th birthday and not yet 21, of good character, recommended by at least 1 Chapter member or a certified Senior DeMolay.","The Membership Application is presented at a stated meeting, at least 1 week before being voted on (unless the Executive Officer authorizes otherwise).","The Master Councilor appoints a 3-member committee of investigation (or the Chapter Advisor / an Advisory Council member investigates instead).","The committee investigates 4 areas: home life, social life and reputation, school record and employment record — ideally with a home visit.","The report is submitted IN WRITING at or before the next stated meeting. The application cannot be balloted without the complete report.","The vote is taken by secret ballot (see the balloting procedure).","Once elected, no election is final without the Advisory Council's approval."],"notes":["The committee's report may be announced but is NOT entered in the minutes.","If the committee fails to report, the MC may continue it or appoint a new one."],"checklist":false,"page":"29"},{"id":"balotaje","title":"The ballot (white balls / black cubes)","intro":"\"White balls elect, black cubes reject.\" The exact rules of the secret vote.","steps":["The Senior Deacon inspects each voter's obligation card, standing between the altar and the Senior Councilor's station. No card, no vote.","Voting order: MC, SC, JC, Senior Deacon, then the members starting from the Scribe — south side first, then north side, from the West.","The Junior Deacon relieves the Sentinel so he can vote too.","Result: 0 or 1 black cube = elected · 2 black cubes = the application lies over to the next stated meeting · 3 or more = rejected.","On the second ballot (after a lie-over): elected unless 3 or more black balls appear.","With several applicants a collective ballot is allowed; if black balls appear, each application is balloted separately."],"notes":["The vote is private and balloting should be brisk; the presiding officer cannot stop an ordered ballot on a private request (it takes a motion voted by the Chapter).","Objection after election and before the Degree: written, signed by 3 members; if sustained by 1/3 of those present, the candidate is rejected.","After a Degree is received, objections proceed only via regular trial before the Advisory Council.","A rejected ballot is referred to the Advisory Council for further consideration."],"checklist":false,"page":"31"},{"id":"elegir-oficiales","title":"Electing & installing officers","intro":"MC, SC and JC are elected by ballot; Scribe and Treasurer are appointed by the Advisory Council.","steps":["Check requirements: an active candidate with a qualified Obligation Card; for MC, prior service as SC or JC (exceptions via the Advisory Council or in a new Chapter).","Vote by paper ballot, prepared before the meeting; a majority wins, blank votes don't count.","The Deacons hand out and collect ballots only from brothers presenting their obligations; the Marshal assists with tabulation.","Tie or no majority = revote.","Installation happens at the same meeting or within 30 days.","MC vacancy: the SC moves up, then the JC; the remaining office is filled by election with 2 weeks' written notice."],"notes":["3 consecutive unexcused absences = automatic vacancy.","Forced removal of an officer: a resolution at a regular meeting + a 3/4 vote of those present at the next one + the Executive Officer's approval."],"checklist":false,"page":"33"},{"id":"dinero","title":"Handling Chapter money","intro":"The financial rules that are not negotiable.","steps":["Keep TWO separate sets of books: Chapter funds and DeMolay International funds (the latter are untouchable and need no vote to be paid).","The Scribe collects; the Treasurer receives and gives the Scribe a receipt.","Every Chapter expense (except to DI) requires a vote at a regular business meeting.","Checks: signed by the Treasurer or the MC + countersigned by an Advisory Council member.","Electronic payments: every approver gets online viewing access or automatic copies.","Cash payments are prohibited, and lending Chapter funds is prohibited.","Investing surplus: a Chapter vote + 2/3 of the ENTIRE Advisory Council for each investment.","The Treasurer's and Scribe's books are audited at each new MC's installation."],"notes":["The only gift Chapter funds may buy: the PMC's Jewel.","Soliciting funds from non-members requires the Executive Officer's prior permission.","Reports 3 months overdue = automatic temporary suspension of the Chapter."],"checklist":false,"page":"57"},{"id":"incidente","title":"Reporting an incident","intro":"What to do when something goes wrong at a DeMolay event.","steps":["People first; for major damage, serious injury or death, notify the Executive Officer IMMEDIATELY.","Reporting threshold: any occurrence with potential for bodily injury or property damage over $100.","Record the facts: WHEN, WHERE, WHAT (damage/injury), WHO, whether police were called — and take photos.","Reporting chain: Chapter → Advisory Council Chairman / Chapter Advisor → Executive Officer → Service and Leadership Center → insurer.","On Masonic property: the Chairman gives ORAL notification to the Masonic body, recording date, time and recipient.","Complete the incident report form and keep copies of every document."],"notes":["Do NOT make statements of responsibility at the scene or encourage claims: facts only, no opinions.","If insurance investigators call: contact the Executive Officer BEFORE talking.","DeMolay's insurance is SECONDARY to family insurance and only covers events documented in the minutes."],"checklist":false,"page":"125"},{"id":"abuso","title":"Reporting suspected abuse","intro":"Suspicion is enough to report — no proof needed. Protection comes first.","steps":["Ensure the young person's immediate safety.","Call 911 or the local child protection agency.","Notify the Jurisdictional Executive Officer within 24 hours, with a written report.","If the alleged perpetrator is a program adult: he is placed on leave until the investigation ends.","Cooperate with authorities and preserve all information."],"notes":["Standing rule: Two-Deep Leadership (minimum 2 registered Advisors) and no one-on-one activities.","Medical Release and Photo Release forms live at beademolay.org/resources."],"checklist":false,"page":"133"},{"id":"fundar-chapter","title":"Starting a Chapter: the official check-off list (17 steps)","intro":"The handbook's complete checklist for organizing a new Chapter. Check items off as you go — your progress is saved on this device.","steps":["Talk to the Executive Officer (or his personal representative) about establishing a Chapter.","Find other interested Masons (set up an informational program).","Secure a Sponsoring Body and have it pass a Resolution to Sponsor.","Select an Advisory Council and have it complete the online training.","Choose the Chapter name (no living person's name allowed).","Complete the Petition for Letters Temporary.","Send the Executive Officer: Resolution to Sponsor + Advisory Council Certification + Petition for Letters Temporary + the fee check.","Receive the Letters Temporary from the Executive Officer.","Review the materials received and order any additional supplies needed.","Set the Chapter's membership fee.","Organize the membership event for the initial class.","Record and approve the applications for membership.","Induct the initial class (with one or more visiting Chapters for the Degrees).","Report the new Members to DeMolay International online (10 days max).","Select and install the first group of Chapter officers.","Adopt the set of Chapter Bylaws (approved by the Executive Officer).","Operate the Chapter per its bylaws, regulations and jurisdictional policies."],"notes":["The Chapter operates under Letters Temporary until it has at least 15 Members.","To reinstate a closed Chapter: same procedure, but with a reinstatement application instead of the Petition for Letters Temporary."],"checklist":true,"page":"254"}]},"facts":{"groups":[{"title":"Fees & money","facts":[{"k":"Initiation fee (minimum)","v":"$35.00 — set by DeMolay International; includes prepaid lifetime membership and the Patent"},{"k":"Affiliation fee (minimum)","v":"$20.00 — Chapters may set higher amounts by amending their Bylaws"},{"k":"Reporting the initiation fee","v":"The Scribe remits it via eScribe within 10 days of the Initiatory Degree being conferred"},{"k":"DeMolay fiscal year","v":"January 1 to December 31"},{"k":"Chapter checks","v":"Signed by the Treasurer or Master Councilor + countersigned by an Advisory Council member, with prior authorization at a regular meeting"},{"k":"Cash","v":"Using cash for Chapter payments is prohibited"},{"k":"DeMolay International funds","v":"Separate, untouchable account; paying them requires no Chapter vote"},{"k":"Gifts with Chapter funds","v":"Prohibited — sole exception: the PMC's Jewel approved by the Advisory Council"},{"k":"Fundraising outside the Chapter","v":"Requires prior permission from the Jurisdiction's Executive Officer"}]},{"title":"Key deadlines","facts":[{"k":"Reporting new initiates","v":"In eScribe, immediately and never more than 10 days after initiation"},{"k":"Annual Advisor recertification","v":"By November 30 each year (Continuing Advisor Certification in eScribe)"},{"k":"Overdue reports","v":"3 months past the deadline = automatic temporary suspension; 3 months suspended for non-payment = the Charter may be voided"},{"k":"Insurance certificate for an event","v":"Request online at least 15 business days ahead (30 days for additionally-insured requests)"},{"k":"Reporting suspected abuse","v":"Notify the Executive Officer within 24 hours, with a written report"},{"k":"Officer absences","v":"3 consecutive unexcused absences = automatic vacancy of the office"},{"k":"Application before the ballot","v":"Presented at a stated meeting at least 1 week before being voted on (unless the EO authorizes otherwise)"},{"k":"PMC-MSA letter of intent","v":"Within 10 days of the Master Councilor's installation"}]},{"title":"Minimums & ratios","facts":[{"k":"Membership age","v":"Past the 12th birthday and not yet 21; at 21 you become a Senior DeMolay"},{"k":"Advisors at every event","v":"Minimum 2 registered Advisors, ALWAYS (Two-Deep Leadership)"},{"k":"Supervision ratio","v":"2 Advisors for up to 10 youth; +1 adult for every 5 additional youth"},{"k":"Advisory Council","v":"Minimum 5 Advisors (DeMolay International); core minimum of 3 Master Masons in good standing"},{"k":"Chaperones at social events","v":"At least 2 Advisors for every 5 active members present"},{"k":"Members for the Charter","v":"A new Chapter operates under Letters Temporary until it has at least 15 Members"},{"k":"Activities per term","v":"Minimum 3 per category (civic, social, athletic, fundraising) + every Obligatory Day"},{"k":"Committees","v":"Minimum 3 members; the first named is chairman; only the Membership Committee is mandatory"},{"k":"Balloting","v":"0-1 black cubes = elected · 2 = lies over · 3 or more = rejected"}]},{"title":"Official contacts","facts":[{"k":"DeMolay International","v":"Henry E. \"Hank\" Stickney Service & Leadership Center — 10200 NW Ambassador Drive, Kansas City, MO 64153, USA"},{"k":"Toll-free phone","v":"1-800-DEMOLAY (1-800-336-6529)"},{"k":"Local phone","v":"(816) 891-8333 · Fax: (816) 891-9062"},{"k":"General email","v":"demolay@demolay.org"},{"k":"Office hours","v":"Monday-Friday, 8:30 AM-5:00 PM (US Central Time)"},{"k":"Handbook feedback","v":"DHBinput@demolay.org"}]},{"title":"Official links","facts":[{"k":"Main site","v":"demolay.org"},{"k":"eScribe (reports & records)","v":"eScribe.DeMolay.org"},{"k":"Official store (regalia & jewelry)","v":"ShopDeMolay.org — the only authorized channel"},{"k":"Leaders Correspondence Course","v":"BeADeMolay.org/lcc — 5 online courses, free, 24/7"},{"k":"Insurance & certificates","v":"demolay.org/insurance"},{"k":"Public ceremony texts","v":"demolay.org/open-ceremonies"},{"k":"Forms (medical/photo release)","v":"beademolay.org/resources"}]}]}},"flashcards":[{"id":"virtudes","title":"The 7 Cardinal Virtues","desc":"The core values behind the whole DeMolay program.","cards":[{"f":"Love of Parents (Filial Love)","b":"Honoring and respecting your parents and being a better son every day. The first of the virtues."},{"f":"Reverence","b":"Reverence for sacred things: respect for God and for everyone's beliefs."},{"f":"Courtesy","b":"Respectful, chivalrous treatment of all people."},{"f":"Comradeship","b":"The brotherhood that binds DeMolays together — loyalty among brothers."},{"f":"Fidelity","b":"Faithfulness to your word, your friends and your commitments — like Jacques DeMolay."},{"f":"Cleanness","b":"Cleanness in mind, body and speech."},{"f":"Patriotism","b":"Love of and service to your country, in peace as well as in war."}]},{"id":"dias","title":"The 7 Obligatory Days","desc":"The mandatory observances of the DeMolay year.","cards":[{"f":"Devotional Day","b":"The week including March 18. Responsible: Chapter Chaplain. Commemorates Jacques DeMolay's martyrdom (1314)."},{"f":"Patriots' Day","b":"February. Responsible: Standard Bearer."},{"f":"Parents' Day","b":"Between May 1 and June 21. Responsible: the seven Preceptors."},{"f":"My Government Day","b":"July. Responsible: Orator and Marshal."},{"f":"Educational Day","b":"Usually September. Responsible: Junior and Senior Stewards."},{"f":"Frank S. Land Memorial Day","b":"Near November 8 (Dad Land's death, 1959). A fundraiser for a DeMolay charity is encouraged."},{"f":"DeMolay Day of Comfort","b":"Between November 15 and December 31. Responsible: Almoner."}]},{"id":"cargos","title":"The Chapter offices","desc":"Who's who in the Chapter room.","cards":[{"f":"Master Councilor","b":"Presides over the Chapter from the East. Elected. Appoints committees, builds the term program, must achieve at least one initiation."},{"f":"Senior Councilor","b":"Second in command, in the West. Elected. Oversees half the committees and presides when the MC is absent."},{"f":"Junior Councilor","b":"Third in line, in the South. Elected. His defined duty: coaching new members on the Obligations."},{"f":"Scribe","b":"Appointed by the Advisory Council. Minutes, eScribe reports, the Annual Report, inventory. \"So goes the Scribe, so goes the Chapter.\""},{"f":"Treasurer","b":"An adult from the Advisory Council. Guards the funds: separate accounts, countersigned checks, never cash."},{"f":"Senior Deacon","b":"Examines voters' obligation cards during ballots and conducts proficiency examinations."},{"f":"Junior Deacon","b":"Assists at the door and relieves the Sentinel so he can vote."},{"f":"Chaplain","b":"Leads prayer (members kneeling on the left knee). Responsible for Devotional Day."},{"f":"Almoner","b":"The officer of charity. Responsible for the Day of Comfort."},{"f":"Marshal","b":"Conducts floor movements and helps tabulate votes. Co-responsible for My Government Day."},{"f":"Standard Bearer","b":"Carries the flag. Responsible for Patriots' Day."},{"f":"Orator","b":"The Chapter's speaker. Co-responsible for My Government Day."},{"f":"Senior & Junior Stewards","b":"Prepare the candidates. Responsible for Educational Day."},{"f":"The 7 Preceptors","b":"Represent the seven virtues with their candles. Often set up the room and are responsible for Parents' Day."},{"f":"Sentinel","b":"Guards the door: receives the Word of the Day and admits no one while the Chapter is opening."},{"f":"Organist","b":"The Chapter's music; the Ritual marks where it plays."}]},{"id":"simbolos","title":"The official pin's symbolism","desc":"Every element of the emblem (1949) has a meaning.","cards":[{"f":"Crown of Youth","b":"The crown of youth, bearing DeMolay's seven precepts."},{"f":"The 10 precious stones","b":"Dad Land and the 9 original founders. Rubies for the deceased, pearls for the living — today all rubies."},{"f":"The Helmet","b":"Chivalry."},{"f":"The Crescent","b":"The secrecy of the Order."},{"f":"The five-armed white cross","b":"Purity, and the motto: \"No DeMolay shall fail as a citizen, as a leader, and as a man.\""},{"f":"The crossed swords","b":"Justice, fortitude and mercy — and the war against arrogance, despotism and intolerance."},{"f":"The stars","b":"Hope and fraternal duties."}]},{"id":"fechas","title":"Dates every DeMolay knows","desc":"The milestones of the Order's history.","cards":[{"f":"When and where was DeMolay founded?","b":"March 1919, at the Scottish Rite Temple in Kansas City, Missouri — Frank S. Land and 9 founders."},{"f":"What happened on March 18, 1314?","b":"Jacques DeMolay was burned at the stake in Paris. That's why it's the central date of the DeMolay calendar."},{"f":"What happened on Friday, October 13, 1307?","b":"The arrest of every Knight Templar in France, ordered by Philip the Fair."},{"f":"When was the Grand Council's first session?","b":"March 7, 1921, at the Scottish Rite Temple in Kansas City — 52 Chapters were already awaiting charters."},{"f":"When was the world's second Chapter born?","b":"May 8, 1920, in Omaha, Nebraska."},{"f":"When did Frank S. Land die?","b":"November 8, 1959 — honored today as Frank S. Land Memorial Day."},{"f":"When was the name International Supreme Council adopted?","b":"March 1, 1954 (it was previously the Grand Council)."},{"f":"What was the largest initiation class?","b":"1,099 initiates — Templar Chapter, Pittsburgh, February 12, 1923."},{"f":"When is the official DeMolay pin from?","b":"1949, designed by Dad Land himself."},{"f":"When was the Ritual written?","b":"In 1919, by Frank A. Marshall — and it remains virtually unchanged."}]},{"id":"terminos","title":"Essential terms","desc":"The vocabulary you'll use every week.","cards":[{"f":"eScribe","b":"DeMolay International's online portal for reporting members, awards and the Annual Report."},{"f":"Obligation card","b":"The card proving your approved Obligations. Without it you cannot vote or hold office."},{"f":"Letters Temporary","b":"A new Chapter's provisional authority, until it reaches 15 members and earns its Charter."},{"f":"Patent","b":"The official membership certificate, issued once both Degrees are reported and paid."},{"f":"Jurisdiction","b":"DeMolay's administrative territory (state, province or country) under an Executive Officer."},{"f":"Executive Officer (EO)","b":"DeMolay International's official representative in a Jurisdiction. Almost everything needs his approval."},{"f":"Advisory Council","b":"The certified adult body overseeing the Chapter. Minimum 3 Master Masons; minimum 5 advisors."},{"f":"Sponsoring Body","b":"The organization (usually Masonic) that sponsors the Chapter and provides a meeting place."},{"f":"First-line signer","b":"The first recommender signing a Membership Application — what counts toward the Blue Honor Key."},{"f":"Majority","b":"Becoming a Senior DeMolay at 21, ideally celebrated with the Majority Service."},{"f":"Two-Deep Leadership","b":"Youth Protection's golden rule: at least 2 registered Advisors at every activity, always."},{"f":"Conclave","b":"The Jurisdiction's annual convention: competitions, elections, brotherhood."},{"f":"Chevalier","b":"The highest honor for an active DeMolay: unanimous ISC vote, never applied for."},{"f":"Stated meeting","b":"The Chapter's regular business meeting, fixed in its Bylaws."}]}]};